description: Any anatomic component of one or both breasts.
label: Breast Part

description: A mass of adipose tissue in the breast that is surrounded by fibrous tissue.
label: Breast Fat Pad

description: The superolateral extension of the mammary gland into the axilla that consists of fibroadipose tissue, lymph nodes, and lymphatics.
label: Axillary Tail of the Breast

description: The pigmented protuberance on the surface of the breast through which milk is drawn from the breast.
label: Nipple

description: The part of the breast which is in the center.
label: Central Portion of the Breast

description: The quarter of the breast which is superior and medial.
label: Upper-Inner Quadrant of the Breast

description: The quarter of the breast which is inferior and medial.
label: Lower-Inner Quadrant of the Breast

description: The quarter of the breast which is superior and lateral.
label: Upper-Outer Quadrant of the Breast

description: The quarter of the breast which is inferior and lateral.
label: Lower-Outer Quadrant of the Breast

description: In humans, the glands of the breast, consisting of fibrous tissue connecting the lobes and fatty tissue in between the lobes.
label: Mammary Gland

description: The pigmented circle or ring of skin that surrounds the nipple.
label: Areola

description: A branched system of tubules that connect the lobules of the mammary gland to the tip of the nipple.
label: Breast Duct

description: A unit of the female breast made up of a group of terminal secretory lobules. On average there are 15-20 lobes in each breast.
label: Breast Lobe

description: Milk-producing glands found in the breasts. They are grouped together into larger units called lobes.
label: Breast Lobule

description: Any component of the complex group of organs including the thymus, spleen, tonsils, lymphatic system, hematopoietic system and cells like lymphocytes, granulocytes, monocytes and macrophages that defends the body against infection or disease.
label: Immune System Part

description: Any component of the bean-shaped organ that is part of the lymphatic system found throughout the body which is composed predominantly of lymphocytes and is involved in immune protection.
label: Lymph Node Part

description: Lymphatic vessels that transport unfiltered lymph to the lymph nodes.
label: Lymph Node Afferent Vessel

description: The dense connective tissue that surrounds a lymph node.
label: Lymph Node Capsule

description: Lymphatic vessels that transport filtered lymph out of lymph nodes.
label: Lymph Node Efferent Vessel

description: The concave side of the lymph node.
label: Lymph Node Hilum

description: Tissue composed of specialized cells that are organized as a definite organ, situated along the course of lymphatic vessels, and consisting of an outer cortical and an inner medullary part. The lymph nodes are the main source of lymphocytes of the peripheral blood and serve as a defense mechanism by removing noxious agents, such as bacteria and toxins, and probably play a role in antibody production.
label: Lymph Node Tissue

description: The portion of the lymph node that contains nodules with germinal centers where B lymphocyte mature into plasma cells after activation. The nodules are separated by diffuse lymphatic tissue, lymph sinuses and trabeculae.
label: Lymph Node Cortex

description: The central portion of the lymph node. It is divided into sections by tracts of lymphatic tissue called medullary cords. Between the medullary cords are the medullary sinuses, which consist mainly of macrophages that engulf microorganisms as part of the lymph node's filtering function. Lymphocytes and plasma cells are also found in the medullary portion.
label: Lymph Node Medullary Portion

description: An irregular tortuous space within lymph nodes through which a continuous stream of lymph passes entering into the efferent lymphatic vessels.
label: Lymph Node Sinus

description: The portion of the lymph node between the capsule and cortex. The subcapsular sinus receives lymph from the afferent lymph vessels and passes it to the cortical sinus.
label: Lymph Node Subcapsular Sinus

description: The supporting and anchoring strand of connective tissue radiating out from the capsule through the interior of the lymph node.
label: Lymph Node Trabecula

description: list()
label: Marginal Zone of the Lymph Node

description: list()
label: Interfollicular Area of the Lymph Node

description: list()
label: Lymph Node Germinal Center

description: list()
label: Lymph Node Lymphoid Follicle

description: Any component of the two organs situated in the throat on either side of the narrow passage from the mouth to the pharynx that are composed of lymphoid tissues.
label: Tonsil Part

description: A triangular shaped space that lies on each side of the oropharynx and houses the palatine tonsils.
label: Tonsillar Fossa

description: The anterior and posterior borders of the tonsillar fossa.  They are composed of muscle tissue.
label: Tonsillar Pillar

description: The anterior border of the tonsillar fossa.  It is composed of the palatoglossus muscle.
label: Anterior Tonsillar Pillar

description: One of many deep mucosal invaginations on the medial surface of the palatine tonsil that extend through the whole thickness of the tonsil, which serve to increase the surface area of the tonsil.
label: Tonsillar Crypt

description: Nodules of lymphoid tissue located on either side of the back of the nasal canal and throat.
label: Tonsillar Tissue

description: Lymphoid tissue of the tonsils. It is composed of B and T lymphocytes. Lymphoid follicles with germinal centers occupy the areas that are populated with B lymphocytes.
label: Tonsillar Lymphoid Tissue

description: The ring of lymphoid tissue located in the pharynx, consisting of the pharyngeal, tubal, palatine, and lingual tonsils.
label: Waldeyer Ring

description: Any component of the organ that is part of the hematopoietic and immune systems consisting of white and red pulp within the left hypochondriac region.
label: Spleen Part

description: A tiny terminal artery that is continuous with the capillaries in the spleen.
label: Splenic Arteriole

description: The layer of dense fibrous tissue that surrounds the splenic parenchyma.
label: Splenic Capsule

description: The area of the spleen through which the vessels and nerves enter or exit the organ.
label: Splenic Hilum

description: The largest mass of lymphatic tissue in the body. It consists of cells and vessels contained within a capsule lined by mesothelium, from which trabecula enter the splenic parenchyma. The parenchyma is supported by a framework of reticular fibers. The spleen consists of two types of parenchymal tissue, the white and red pulp. The white pulp is composed of elongated cords of compact lymphatic tissue containing nodules. The red pulp is composed of pulp cords and splenic sinusoids.
label: Splenic Tissue

description: The parenchyma of the spleen, consisting of lymphocytes and macrophages. It lies between the splenic trabecula. Red pulp is the part suffused with blood and white pulp consists of areas of lymphatic tissue where there are sleeves of lymphocytes and macrophages.
label: Splenic Pulp

description: Splenic pulp seen grossly as a reddish brown substance, due to its abundance of red blood cells, consisting of splenic sinuses and the tissue intervening between them (splenic cords).
label: Splenic Red Pulp

description: The part of the spleen that consists of nodules and other lymphatic concentrations.
label: Splenic White Pulp

description: list()
label: Splenic Sinus

description: list()
label: Splenic Marginal Sinus

description: Dense connective tissue structures composed of collagen, elastic, reticular fibers, and smooth muscle cells. They are projections from the splenic capsule into the parenchyma. The arrangement of the fibers permits the spleen to expand passively and to serve as a small temporary reservoir for blood. The trabeculae which originate at the hilus contain and support trabecular arteries and veins which enter and leave the organ at the hilus. Trabeculae from other areas of the capsule do not contain vessels. Arteries branching out of the trabeculae are immediately surrounded by lymphocytes forming the white pulp.
label: Splenic Trabecula

description: list()
label: Periarteriolar Lymphoid Sheath

description: list()
label: Splenic Cord

description: list()
label: Splenic Lymphoid Follicle

description: list()
label: Splenic Germinal Center

description: Any component of the organs involved in the creation and excretion of urine.
label: Urinary System Part

description: The area where the ureter joins the urinary bladder.
label: Ureterovesical Junction

description: The area where the ureter joins the renal pelvis.
label: Ureteropelvic Junction

description: One or both of the muscles that surround the urethra and contract to control the flow of urine, either involuntarily (the internal sphincter) or voluntarily (the external sphincter).
label: Urethral Sphincter

description: The muscle that surrounds the membranous urethra, functioning to control the voluntary flow of urine.
label: Male External Urethral Sphincter

description: The division of the urinary tract comprising the kidney and the ureters.
label: Upper Urinary System

description: A named segment of the urethra.
label: Urethra Part

description: The part of the urethra that is closer to the bladder.
label: Proximal Urethra

description: The part of the urethra that is closer to the external urethral orifice.
label: Distal Urethra

description: That part of the male urethra that passes through the prostate gland.
label: Prostatic Urethra

description: The portion of the penile urethra that spans the bulb of the penis.
label: Bulbar Urethra

description: The most narrow and shortest part of the male urethra, which is located between the prostatic urethra and the spongy (penile) urethra.
label: Membranous Urethra

description: The portion of the urethra that spans the corpus spongiosum.
label: Penile Portion of the Urethra

description: A portion of the urethra that extends between the apex of the prostate and the bulb of the corpus spongiosum and lies between the superior layers of the triangular ligament.
label: Bulbomembranous Urethra

description: The portion of the urethra that extends from the meatus to the membranous urethra.
label: Anterior Portion of the Urethra

description: The portion of the urethra that is located on the posterior aspect of the urogenital diaphragm.
label: Posterior Portion of the Urethra

description: A named segment of the ureter.
label: Ureter Part

description: The segment of the ureter that extends from the renal pelvis to the upper border of the sacrum.
label: Upper Ureter

description: The segment of the ureter that extends between the upper to lower borders of the sacrum.
label: Middle Ureter

description: The segment of the ureter that extends from the lower border of the sacrum to the bladder.
label: Distal Ureter

description: The segment of the ureter that extends from the renal pelvis to the iliac vessels.
label: Abdominal Ureter

description: The segment of the ureter that extends from the iliac vessels to the bladder.
label: Pelvic Ureter

description: The parts of the urinary system that discharge urine. These include the renal pelvis, ureter, bladder, and urethra.
label: Urinary Tract

description: The inferior portion of the urinary bladder which is formed as the walls of the bladder converge and become contiguous with the proximal urethra.
label: Bladder Neck

description: The opening of the ureter in the bladder that is situated at the lateral angle of the trigone.
label: Ureteric Orifice

description: The triangular area in the bladder mucosa that is formed by the two ureteral orifices and the urethral orifice.
label: Bladder Trigone

description: The upper, convex surface of the bladder.
label: Dome of the Bladder

description: The funnel-shaped proximal portion of the ureter located within the kidney into which urine is secreted, from the collecting duct system of the kidney.
label: Renal Pelvis

description: The portion of the bladder that is formed by the posterior wall and is located opposite to the bladder opening.
label: Bladder Fundus

description: The tissue layers that form the urinary bladder. They include the mucosa, submucosa, smooth muscle, and serosa.
label: Bladder Wall

description: The aspect of the bladder wall that is located on the side.
label: Lateral Wall of the Bladder

description: The anterior aspect of the bladder wall.
label: Anterior Wall of the Bladder

description: The posterior aspect of the bladder wall.
label: Posterior Wall of the Bladder

description: The upper tract of the renal system. The renal pelvis is the large cavity in the middle of each kidney. Urine drains from each kidney through a long tube called the ureter, into the bladder, where it is stored until it is passed from the body through the urethra.
label: Renal Pelvis and Ureter

description: The anterosuperior part of the bladder that points towards the abdominal wall.
label: Bladder Apex

description: The large area of the bladder situated between the apex and the fundus.
label: Bladder Body

description: Any component of one of the two bean-shaped organs located on each side of the spine in the retroperitoneum, which filters and secrets the metabolic products and minerals from the blood, thus maintaining the homeostasis.
label: Kidney Part

description: A layer of dense connective tissue that covers the outer surface of each kidney.
label: Renal Capsule

description: An intrarenal space located in the renal medulla that serves to collect and transport urine.
label: Renal Calyx

description: A tuft of capillaries situated at the entrance to each nephron, within the Bowman's capsule. This tuft functions as the first stage in filtering blood in the kidney.
label: Glomerulus

description: The recessed central fissure of the kidney, though which pass the ureter and vessels of the kidney.
label: Renal Pedicle

description: The portion of the kidney comprising the renal calices and pelvis.
label: Renal Calyx and Pelvis

description: The functional part of the kidney, comprising the renal cortex and medulla.
label: Renal Parenchyma

description: A cavity in the kidney containing the pelvicalyceal system, blood vessels, nerves and fat. It communicates with the perinephric space.
label: Renal Sinus

description: The portion of the kidney that is located between the upper and lower poles and contains the renal hilum.
label: Kidney Interpolar Region

description: The blood vessels that supply the nephrons of the kidney with oxygenated blood.
label: Renal Afferent Vessel

description: A component of the nephron comprising two structures: Bowman capsule and the glomerulus, and which is responsible for the filtration of plasma.
label: Renal Corpuscle

description: The blood vessels that drain blood from the nephrons of the kidney.
label: Renal Efferent Vessel

description: The tip of a renal pyramid, which delivers urine into a minor calyx.
label: Renal Papilla

description: Nephrons located superior to the juxtamedullary region but inferior to the superficial nephrons in the middle region of the renal cortex.
label: Midcortical Nephron

description: The aspect of the kidney facing the abdominal cavity.
label: Anterior Surface of the Kidney

description: A double-walled, cup-like sac that surrounds the glomerulus. It is located at the beginning of a nephron in the kidney.
label: Bowman Capsule

description: The arched form consisting of a reddish-brown cortical substance running from one cortical column to the next between the base of the pyramid and the capsule in the kidney.
label: Cortical Arch

description: Bands of cortical tissue in the renal cortex that extend into the medulla between the renal pyramids helping to anchor the cortex.
label: Cortical Column

description: A nephron with its corpuscle in the cortex and Loop of Henle in the renal medulla close to its junction with the renal cortex.
label: Cortical Nephron

description: list()
label: Foot Process

description: The concave area of the kidney through which the renal artery enters and the renal vein and ureter exit the organ.
label: Hilar Area of the Kidney

description: A nephron in which the renal corpuscle is in close proximity to the renal medulla while the proximal convoluted tubule and loop of Henle are located much deeper in the kidney.
label: Juxtamedullary Nephron

description: A functional unit of the kidney consisting of a renal pyramid and the renal cortex surrounding it.
label: Kidney Lobe

description: The posterior aspect of the kidney.
label: Posterior Surface of the Kidney

description: An electron dense layer within the basement membrane.
label: Lamina Densa

description: One of the three layers comprising the basal lamina of the renal corpuscle membrane that is between the podocytes and the lamina densa.
label: Lamina Rara Externa

description: One of the three layers comprising the basal lamina of the renal corpuscle membrane that is between the lamina densa and the endothelial cells.
label: Lamina Rara Interna

description: An area of densely packed modified epithelial cells lining the wall of the distal convoluted tubule of the kidney that is adjacent to the afferent arteriole just before it enters the glomerulus and is in direct apposition to the juxtaglomerular cells.
label: Macula Densa

description: The outermost layer of the renal capsule, which is composed of a single layer of simple squamous epithelium.
label: Parietal Layer of Bowman Capsule

description: The space between the visceral and parietal layers of the glomerular capsule where the glomerular ultrafiltrate is formed.
label: Urinary Space

description: The layer of podocytes found immediately superior to the thickened glomerular basement membrane.
label: Visceral Layer of Bowman Capsule

description: The anatomical segment of the kidney that is comprised of both the nephron and associated collecting tubules. These tubules or tubes contain fluid that has been filtered through the glomerulus.
label: Renal Tubule

description: The ascending limb of the U-shaped portion of the renal tubule.
label: Ascending Limb of Henle's Loop

description: The final section of a renal tubule in the nephron between the distal convoluted tubule and the ureter comprising of principal and intercalated cells. The collecting tube acts to reabsorb sodium and water while secreting potassium and maintaining acid-base homeostasis.
label: Collecting Tube

description: The curved portion of the nephron.
label: Curved Tube

description: The descending limb of the U-shaped portion of the renal tubule.
label: Descending Limb of Henle's Loop

description: The irregular portion of the nephron.
label: Irregular Tubule

description: The U-shaped portion of the nephron between the proximal and distal convoluted tubules with descending, ascending, and thick ascending limbs which sets up a concentration gradient in the medulla.
label: Henle's Loop

description: The portion of the renal tubule located inside the renal cortex between the proximal convoluted tubule and the loop of Henle.
label: Spiral Tube of Schchowa

description: list()
label: Convoluted Tubule

description: A coiled segment of the renal tubule found in the cortex of the kidney, which arises from the ascending loop of Henle, and functions to reabsorb certain electrolytes and regulate the pH of the urine.
label: Distal Convoluted Tubule

description: The coiled duct section of a nephron, located between Bowman's capsule and the loop of Henle in the renal cortex, that concentrates the urine.
label: Proximal Convoluted Tube

description: The pole of the kidney located in the uppermost region of the kidney.
label: Upper Pole of Kidney

description: The pole of the kidney located in the lowest region of the kidney.
label: Lower Pole of Kidney

description: Part of the upper urinary tract located in the retroperitoneum. The kidneys are the functional unit of the urinary system producing urine, which is transported from the renal pelvis of each kidney to the urinary bladder by the ipsilateral ureter.
label: Kidney and Ureter

description: Any component of the tissues capable of secreting hormones.
label: Endocrine System Part

description: The glandular or anterior lobe of the pituitary gland which secretes several hormones.
label: Anterior Lobe of the Pituitary Gland

description: The neural or post-neural lobe of the pituitary gland which stores and releases vasopressin, oxytocin, and neurophysins.
label: Posterior Lobe of the Pituitary Gland

description: Either one of the two lateral lobes of the thyroid gland, or the additional pyramidal lobe that is found superior to the isthmus between the lateral lobes in approximately one-third of cases as a normal variant. The pyramidal lobe is a remnant of the thyroglossal duct that is also called Lalouette's pyramid.
label: Thyroid Gland Lobe

description: The cone-like lobe of the thyroid gland that is located in the left side of the trachea.
label: Left Thyroid Gland Lobe

description: The cone-like lobe of the thyroid gland that is located in the right side of the trachea.
label: Right Thyroid Gland Lobe

description: A conical thyroid gland lobe.  When it is present, it usually arises from the isthmus.
label: Pyramidal Lobe

description: list()
label: Reticularis Zone

description: list()
label: Glomerulosa Zone

description: list()
label: Fasciculata Zone

description: The neurosecretory granules containing antidiuretic hormone (ADH), oxytocin, ATP or neurophysin in the axon terminals of neurons projecting from the hypothalamus to the posterior pituitary.
label: Herring Body

description: The narrow, central portion of the thyroid gland that crosses the trachea anteriorly and connects the lateral lobes of the gland. When present, the normal variant pyramidal lobe may extend from the isthmus.
label: Thyroid Gland Isthmus

description: Any component of the organs involved in the exchange of carbon dioxide and oxygen including the trachea, bronchi, bronchial tubes, lungs, and alveoli.
label: Respiratory System Part

description: Tubular structure in continuation with the trachea, serving as air passage. It terminates in the lung (terminal bronchiole).
label: Bronchus

description: The left and right main bronchi considered as a group.
label: Main Bronchus

description: One of the two main bronchi. It is narrower but longer than the right main bronchus and connects to the left lung.
label: Left Main Bronchus

description: One of the two main bronchi. It is wider but shorter than the left main bronchus and connects to the right lung.
label: Right Main Bronchus

description: A bronchial branch that is located within the lung tissue.
label: Intrapulmonary Bronchus

description: A part the bronchial tree, arising from the primary bronchi, with each one serving as the airway to a specific lobe of the lung.
label: Lobar Bronchus

description: One of the divisions of the lobar bronchus that supplies a bronchopulmonary segment.
label: Segmental Bronchus

description: A part the bronchial tree, an air passage arising from the segmental bronchus and passing to the naturally delimited part of lung segment (subsegment), where it further subdivides into smaller passages.
label: Subsegmental Bronchus

description: A part the bronchial tree of the left lung, an air passage arising from any segmental bronchus of the left lung and passing to the naturally delimited part of lung segment (subsegment), where it further subdivides into smaller passages.
label: Subsegmental Bronchus of Left Lung

description: A part the bronchial tree of the right lung, an air passage arising from any segmental bronchus of the right lung and passing to the naturally delimited part of lung segment (subsegment), where it further subdivides into smaller passages.
label: Subsegmental Bronchus of Right Lung

description: The smallest subdivisions of the bronchial tree, which are both acartilagenous and aglandular.
label: Bronchiole

description: The narrowest airway of the bronchial tree, which is formed by the division of terminal bronchioles, and which contains alveoli along its wall for gas exchange.
label: Respiratory Bronchiole

description: A respiratory bronchiole located in the left lung.
label: Left Lung Respiratory Bronchiole

description: A respiratory bronchiole located in the right lung.
label: Right Lung Respiratory Bronchiole

description: The narrowest and most distal component of the conducting portion of the respiratory system lined by ciliated cuboidal or columnar epithelium containing club cells. They branch off from the lesser bronchioles and divide distally into alveolated respiratory bronchioles (acinus).
label: Terminal Bronchiole

description: A terminal bronchiole located in the left lung.
label: Left Lung Terminal Bronchiole

description: A terminal bronchiole located in the right lung.
label: Right Lung Terminal Bronchiole

description: A bronchiole located in the left lung.
label: Left Lung Bronchiole

description: A bronchiole located in the right lung.
label: Right Lung Bronchiole

description: Any of the terminal sacs in the lungs through which gas exchange takes place with the pulmonary capillary blood.
label: Alveolus

description: An alveolus located in the left lung.
label: Left Lung Alveolus

description: An alveolus located in the right lung.
label: Right Lung Alveolus

description: The alveolar structure that contains alveolar cells type I and II and macrophages.
label: Alveolar Wall

description: The anterior basal segment of the inferior lobe of the left lung.
label: Left Lung, Inferior Lobe, Anterior Basal Segment

description: The lateral basal segment of the inferior lobe of the left lung.
label: Left Lung, Inferior Lobe, Lateral Basal Segment

description: The medial basal segment of the inferior lobe of the left lung.
label: Left Lung, Inferior Lobe, Medial Basal Segment

description: The posterior basal segment of the inferior lobe of the left lung.
label: Left Lung, Inferior Lobe, Posterior Basal Segment

description: The superior segment of the inferior lobe of the left lung.
label: Left Lung, Inferior Lobe, Superior Segment

description: The anterior segment of the superior lobe of the left lung.
label: Left Lung, Superior Lobe, Anterior Segment

description: The apicoposterior segment of the superior lobe of the left lung.
label: Left Lung, Superior Lobe, Apicoposterior Segment

description: The inferior lingual segment of the superior lobe of the left lung.
label: Left Lung, Superior Lobe, Inferior Lingular Segment

description: The superior inguinal segment of the superior lobe of the left lung.
label: Left Lung, Superior Lobe, Superior Lingular Segment

description: The anterior basal segment of the inferior lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Inferior Lobe, Anterior Basal Segment

description: The lateral basal segment of the inferior lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Inferior Lobe, Lateral Basal Segment

description: The medial basal segment of the inferior lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Inferior Lobe, Medial Basal Segment

description: The posterior basal segment of the inferior lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Inferior Lobe, Posterior Basal Segment

description: The superior segment of the inferior lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Inferior Lobe, Superior Segment

description: The lateral segment of the middle lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Middle Lobe, Lateral Segment

description: The medial segment of the middle lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Middle Lobe, Medial Segment

description: The anterior segment of the superior lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Superior Lobe, Anterior Segment

description: The apical segment of the superior lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Superior Lobe, Apical Segment

description: The posterior segment of the superior lobe of the right lung.
label: Right Lung, Superior Lobe, Posterior Segment

description: A ridge or ridge-like structure.  In humans it usually refers to the trachea.  The carina of trachea is part of the lowest tracheal cartilage which is placed between the orifices of the two bronchi.
label: Carina

description: The rounded, uppermost part of the lung, located above the level of the sternal end of the first rib.
label: Apex of the Lung

description: The bottom concave portion of the lung that is situated on the convexity of the diaphragm.
label: Base of the Lung

description: A branch of the right main bronchus that arises above the pulmonary artery and connects to the superior lobe of the right lung.
label: Eparterial Branch of the Right Main Bronchus

description: The portion of the right main bronchus that is below the right pulmonary artery.
label: Hyparterial Branch of the Right Main Bronchus

description: The part of the respiratory system below the bifurcation of the trachea. It includes the lungs and the parts of the lungs such as the bronchioles and alveoli.
label: Lower Respiratory System

description: list()
label: Lamellar Body

description: A complex of alveolated airways, located distal to the terminal bronchioles, comprising respiratory bronchioles, alveolar ducts, and alveolar sacs, which is the functional unit of the lung.
label: Pulmonary Acinus

description: The sinuses and those parts of the respiratory system above the trachea. It includes the nares, nasopharynx, oropharynx, larynx, vocal cords, glottis and upper trachea.
label: Upper Respiratory System

description: One of the subdivisions of the lung, 2 in the left lung and 3 in the right lung.
label: Lung Lobe

description: The lobe of the right lung that lies above the oblique and horizontal fissures and includes the apical, posterior and anterior bronchopulmonary segments; in the left lung, the lobe lies above the oblique fissure and contains the apicoposterior, anterior, superior lingular and inferior lingular segments.
label: Upper Lobe of the Lung

description: The smaller lobe of the left lung, situated above and in front the oblique fissure, which includes the apex.
label: Upper Lobe of the Left Lung

description: The lobe of the right lung, situated above the horizontal fissure, which includes the apex.
label: Upper Lobe of the Right Lung

description: The bottom most subdivision of either the right or left lung.
label: Lower Lobe of the Lung

description: The larger lobe of the left lung, situated below and behind the oblique fissure.
label: Lower Lobe of the Left Lung

description: The lobe of the right lung situated below the oblique fissure.
label: Lower Lobe of the Right Lung

description: One of the three lobes that comprise the right lung.
label: Lobe of the Right Lung

description: The smallest lobe of the right lung, situated above the oblique fissure and below the horizontal fissure.
label: Middle Lobe of the Right Lung

description: A small lobe sometimes found on the upper part of the right lung, formed by an infolding of the pleura and separated from the rest of the upper lobe by a deep groove lodging the azygos vein.
label: Azygos Lobe

description: Either of the two (upper or lower) lobes that comprise the left lung.
label: Lobe of the Left Lung

description: A small tongue-like projection from the lower portion of the upper lobe of the left lung.
label: Lingula of the Lung

description: The area associated with the hilum of the left lung.
label: Hilar Area of the Left Lung

description: The wedge-shaped area at the central portion of the lung through which the bronchi, vessels and nerves enter or exit the organ.
label: Hilar Area of the Lung

description: The area associated with the hilum of the right lung.
label: Hilar Area of the Right Lung

description: The part of the respiratory system between the nose or mouth and the lungs.
label: Airway

description: Any component of the entire nerve apparatus, including the brain, spinal cord, spinal nerves, autonomic ganglia, and plexuses.
label: Nervous System Part

description: The part of the nervous system that consists of the brain, spinal cord, and meninges.
label: Central Nervous System

description: That part of the nervous system consisting of the nerves and neurons that reside or extend outside the central nervous system.
label: Peripheral Nervous System

description: Part of the peripheral nervous system composed of bundles of nerve fibers running to various organs and tissues of the body using chemical and electrical signals to transmit sensory and motor information from one body part to another.
label: Nerve

description: Any of the 12 paired nerves that originate in the brain stem.
label: Cranial Nerve

description: The tenth cranial nerve. It is the longest cranial nerve. It originates in the medulla and exits the cranium through the jugular foramen. It supplies various muscles, including muscles of the pharynx and soft palate.
label: Vagus Nerve

description: The second cranial nerve.
label: Optic Nerve

description: A cranial nerve that supplies motor impulses to the lateral rectus muscle of the eye.
label: Abducens Nerve

description: The cochlear portion of cranial nerve VIII (the vestibulocochlear nerve), which transmits auditory sensory impulses to the cochlear nucleus in the brainstem.
label: Cochlear Nerve

description: Cranial nerve VII, which originates in the brainstem between the pons and the medulla. It controls the facial expression muscles and transports taste and sensation from the tongue and mouth.
label: Facial Nerve

description: The twelfth cranial nerve. It arises from the hypoglossal nucleus and leads to the tongue.
label: Hypoglossal Nerve

description: The ninth cranial nerve. It originates in the brainstem and passes through the jugular foramen. It has motor and sensory functions that relate to the tongue, pharynx and middle ear.
label: Glossopharyngeal Nerve

description: The third cranial nerve that originates originating at the oculomotor nerve nucleus at the level of the superior colliculus in the midbrain, provides motor innervation to the levator palpebrae superioris, the superior, inferior, and medial rectus muscles, and the inferior oblique muscles, and provides parasympathetic innervation to the ciliary ganglion.
label: Oculomotor Nerve

description: The first cranial nerve. It is the shortest cranial nerve and of paramount importance in the sense of smell. Its neurons are in the olfactory mucosa in the nasal cavity.
label: Olfactory Nerve

description: The fifth set of paired nerves of the face that emerge from the brain steam. These nerves have sensory and motor functions in the face, oral cavity, and nasal cavity.
label: Trigeminal Nerve

description: The cranial nerve that controls the superior oblique muscle of the eye.
label: Trochlear Nerve

description: One of the two branches of cranial nerve VIII (vestibulocochlear nerve), which transmits sensory information transmitted from vestibular hair cells located in the utricle, the saccule, and the three semicircular canals.
label: Vestibular Nerve

description: The eighth cranial nerve composed of the acoustic nerve and the vestibular nerve. The nerve travels from the inner ear, enters the cranial cavity through the internal auditory foramen and joins the brainstem. The auditory nerve conveys impulses from the cochlea of the inner ear to the auditory nuclei of the brainstem. The vestibular nerve carries information from the labyrinths of the inner ear to the vestibular nuclei of the brainstem.
label: Vestibulocochlear Nerve

description: The 11th cranial nerve, which sends motor impulses to the muscles of the upper thorax, back, shoulders, and pharynx.
label: Accessory Nerve

description: Any nerve outside the brain or spinal cord that connects with peripheral receptors or effectors.
label: Peripheral Nerve

description: A branch of the facial nerve that innervates the musculature of the lower lip.
label: Marginal Mandibular Branch of the Facial Nerve

description: A branch of the mandibular division of the trigeminal nerve that supplies sensory innervation to the tongue.
label: Lingual Nerve

description: A branch of the femoral nerve traveling the length of the leg/hindlimb, which innervates the sartorius and the skin of the medial aspect of the leg/hindlimb from the knee/stifle joint to the metatarsus.
label: Saphenous Nerve

description: The anterior primary branches of the thoracic spinal nerves (T1 to T11).
label: Intercostal Nerve

description: A somatic nerve branching from the ophthalmic nerve that innervates the forehead, eye lids and frontal sinus.
label: Frontal Nerve

description: The smallest branch of the ophthalmic nerve that innervates the lacrimal gland, conjunctiva, and the lateral portion of the upper eyelid.
label: Lacrimal Nerve

description: Any nerve supplying innervation to the external nose and nasal cavity.
label: Nasal Nerve

description: The largest of three branches of the trigeminal nerve containing both sensory and motor neurons that project to the tongue, the lower face, lip, teeth and gums as well as the temple and external ear.
label: Inferior Maxillary Nerve

description: A branch of the maxillary nerve (CN V2) that innervates the meninges.
label: Meningeal Nerve

description: The first and smallest of three divisions of the trigeminal nerve, which carries only sensory fibers supplying innervation to the forehead, scalp, lacrimal gland, eye, and side of the nose.
label: Ophthalmic Nerve

description: The second division of the fifth cranial nerve, the trigeminal nerve, which supplies sensory fibers to all structures in and around the maxillary bone and the midfacial region.
label: Superior Maxillary Nerve

description: A major peripheral nerve of the upper limb; it originates as the medial cord of the brachial plexus, and contains fibers from the C8-T1 nerve roots. It functions to supply both sensory and motor innervation to parts of the forearm and hand.
label: Ulnar Nerve

description: One of two major branches of the sciatic nerve. It innervates the muscles of the posterior aspect of the lower limb, the muscles of the plantar aspect of the foot, as well as the skin on the posterior aspect of the leg and on the sole of the foot.
label: Tibial Nerve

description: The long nerve that is formed by the merging of the ventral rami of the L4, L5, and S1 in the pelvis and passes down the lower limb where it divides into the common peroneal and tibial nerves.
label: Sciatic Nerve

description: A large nerve that arises from the brachial plexus and enervates the extensor muscles and skin of the entire upper limb's posterior aspect.
label: Radial Nerve

description: Either of a pair of nerves that arise in the cervical plexus and provide innervation of the diaphragm.
label: Phrenic Nerve

description: Any one of the three (common, deep, and superficial) peroneal nerves.
label: Peroneal Nerve

description: A terminal branch of the sciatic nerve. It innervates the calf and foot.
label: Common Peroneal Nerve

description: A branch of the common peroneal nerve. It innervates the ankle and toes.
label: Deep Peroneal Nerve

description: A branch of the common peroneal nerve. It innervates the surface of the calf and foot.
label: Superficial Peroneal Nerve

description: A branch of the brachial plexus that extends along the anterior aspect of the forearm and the hand.
label: Median Nerve

description: A nerve that originates from the lumbar nerves and innervates the anterior region of the thigh.
label: Femoral Nerve

description: A nerve originated from the posterior cord of the brachial plexus within the axilla then passing through the quadrangular space to innervate the deltoid and teres minor muscles and terminating as the superior lateral brachial cutaneous nerve.
label: Axillary Nerve

description: A nerve that arises from the second, third, and fourth lumbar nerves and enters the thigh through the obturator canal. It is responsible for the sensory innervation of the skin of the medial aspect of the thigh and also responsible for the motor innervation of the adductor muscles of the lower extremity.
label: Obturator Nerve

description: A nerve that innervates the sole of the foot. This term may refer to the medial plantar nerve or lateral plantar nerve, both of which originate from the tibial nerve.
label: Plantar Nerve

description: A peripheral nerve that runs close to the small saphenous vein. It supplies innervation to the skin of the lower back of the leg and sends a branch to the lateral side of the foot and little toe.
label: Sural Nerve

description: Paired nerves that arise from the spinal cord. In all, there are 31 pairs of spinal nerves located in the human body.
label: Spinal Nerve

description: Any of the spinal nerves originating from the thoracic region.
label: Thoracic Nerve

description: The thirty-first and final spinal nerve arising from the sacral plexus.
label: Coccygeal Nerve

description: Any of the eight nerves arising from one of the seven cervical vertebrae.
label: Cervical Nerve

description: Any of the five spinal nerves originating from the lumbar region.
label: Lumbar Nerve

description: Any one of the five pairs of spinal nerves emerging from each side of the sacrum, which contain both afferent and efferent fibers.
label: Sacral Nerve

description: The posterior root of a spinal nerve, which emerges from the dorsal part of the spinal cord and transmits sensory information via an ascending tract to the brain.
label: Spinal Dorsal Nerve

description: Any component of the nervous system that consists of the brain, spinal cord, and meninges.
label: Central Nervous System Part

description: An organ composed of grey and white matter containing billions of neurons that is the center for intelligence and reasoning. It is protected by the bony cranium.
label: Brain

description: The elongated, approximately cylindrical part of the central nervous system of vertebrates that lies in the vertebral canal and from which the spinal nerves emerge.
label: Spinal Cord

description: Located at the brainstem, this sensory organ receives auditory signals from the cochlear auditory nerve fibers. It is composed of the dorsal cochlear nucleus located on the dorsolateral surface of the inferior peduncle and the ventral (or accessory) cochlear nucleus located on the ventral aspect of the inferior peduncle.
label: Cochlear Nucleus

description: A double-fold of dura mater that lies within the medial longitudinal fissure, and which separates the two cerebral hemispheres. It is attached rostrally to the crista galli and caudally to the surface of the tentorium cerebelli.
label: Falx Cerebri

description: Any component of the central nervous system that is contained within the cranium.
label: Brain Part

description: The brain area that is composed of the caudate nucleus and putamen.
label: Neostriatum

description: The medial aspect of the posterior parietal lobe, which is bounded anteriorly by the marginal branch of the cingulate sulcus, posteriorly by the medial portion of the parieto-occipital fissure and inferiorly by the subparietal sulcus. It is involved in a wide range of higher-order cognitive function, such as episodic memory, visuospatial processing, reflections upon self, and aspects of consciousness.
label: Precuneus

description: The two pairs of colliculi located on the dorsal surface of the midbrain known as the inferior and superior colliculus.
label: Corpora Quadrigemina

description: The anterior eminence of the lamina tecti mesencephali.
label: Anterior Quadrigeminal Body

description: A nucleus located in the tectum of the midbrain, caudal to the superior colliculus and composed of a large central nucleus, bordered posteriorly by a smaller pericentral nucleus and laterally by an external nucleus, that is involved in the relay of auditory information.
label: Posterior Quadrigeminal Body

description: Clusters of neurons comprising the globus pallidus, putamen, caudate, nucleus accumbens, substantia nigra and subthalamic nucleus. They are involved with high level aspects of inhibitory motor activity in coordination with the excitation commands issued from the cerebellum.
label: Basal Ganglia

description: The part of the brain that controls muscle functions and also controls speech, thought, emotions, reading, writing, and learning. The right hemisphere controls the muscles on the left side of the body, and the left hemisphere controls the muscles on the right side of the body.
label: Cerebral Hemisphere

description: The left half of the cerebrum that controls the muscles on the right side of the body.
label: Left Cerebral Hemisphere

description: The right half of the cerebrum that controls the muscles on the left side of the body.
label: Right Cerebral Hemisphere

description: One of 47 numbered regions within a map of the cerebral cortex. Each is characterized by a particular cell organization and also corresponds to a particular cortical function.
label: Brodmann's Area

description: The part of the brain located anterior to the parietal lobes at the front of each cerebral hemisphere.
label: Frontal Lobe

description: One of the cerebral lobes. It is located inferior to the frontal and parietal lobes and anterior to the occipital lobe.
label: Temporal Lobe

description: One of the lobes of the cerebral hemisphere located superiorly to the occipital lobe and posteriorly to the frontal lobe. Cognition and visuospatial processing are its main functions.
label: Parietal Lobe

description: One of the four regions of cortex in each cerebral hemisphere. It is located posterior to the temporal lobe and inferior to the parietal lobe.
label: Occipital Lobe

description: The four connected cavities (hollow spaces) centrally located within the brain that connect posteriorly with the central canal of the spinal cord.
label: Brain Ventricle

description: A centrally placed component of the ventricular system of the brain located in the diencephalon. Cerebrospinal fluid from the lateral ventricles flows into the third ventricle via the foramina of Monroe and exits the third ventricle via the aqueduct of Sylvius. The thalamus and hypothalamus border the lateral walls of the third ventricle.
label: Third Ventricle

description: A diamond-shaped cavity filled with cerebrospinal fluid within the pons extending between the obex in the caudal medulla and the aqueduct of Sylvius in the cerebellum.
label: Fourth Ventricle

description: The rostral extensions of the ventricular system of the brain consisting of two cavities, one on each side of the brain within the central regions of each cerebral hemisphere.  Cerebrospinal fluid flows from the lateral ventricles into the centrally third ventricle via the foramen of Monroe.
label: Lateral Ventricle

description: A normal variant CSF filled cavity in the brain situated between the leaves of the septum pellucidum. Also called cavum septi pellucidum.
label: Fifth Ventricle

description: A cluster of nuclei located deep and medially within each temporal lobe of the brain. These limbic system structures serve a role in processing memory, emotional reactions and decision-making.
label: Amygdala

description: Three sections, the midbrain, pons and medulla oblongata, that are located at the base of the brain. The brain stem regulates the central nervous system, and is vital as a conduit for motor and sensory innervations.
label: Brain Stem

description: The lower portion of the brainstem located between the pons and brainstem. This structure contains several descending and ascending tracts, lower cranial nerve nuclei, a significant proportion of the reticular system of the brainstem and other structures.
label: Medulla Oblongata

description: The striped grey and white matter that comprises the caudate and the lentiform nuclei, and is located anterior and lateral to the thalamus in each hemisphere of the brain.
label: Corpus Striatum

description: A sub-cortical, paired nuclei that, though migrated to the telencephalon, is a critical part of the basal ganglia, along with the caudate nucleus and the putamen, the latter of which it joins to form the lentiform nucleus. Each nucleus is subdivided into internal and external parts, called globus pallidus interna and globus pallidus externa, which are separated by an internal medullary lamina.
label: Globus Pallidus

description: The outer layer of the cerebrum composed of neurons and unmyelinated nerve fibers. It is responsible for memory, attention, consciousness and other higher levels of mental function.
label: Cerebral Cortex

description: The outermost layer of the parietal lobe, made up primarily of gray matter.
label: Parietal Lobe Cortex

description: The grey matter, or outermost layer of the frontal lobe.
label: Frontal Lobe Cortex

description: The grey matter, or outermost layer of the occipital lobe.
label: Occipital Lobe Cortex

description: The grey matter, or outermost layer of the temporal lobe.
label: Temporal Lobe Cortex

description: The area in the cerebral cortex that receives and processes auditory input.
label: Auditory Cortex

description: Part of the medial aspect of the cerebral cortex.
label: Cingulate Cortex

description: A brain region in the medial temporal lobe near the hippocampus.
label: Entorhinal Cortex

description: A brain region that is located in the dorsal part of the precentral gyrus.
label: Primary Motor Cortex

description: A brain region in the occipital cortex that receives visual stimuli from the retina.
label: Primary Visual Cortex

description: A curved gray matter structure of the temporal lobe lying on the floor of the lateral ventricle of the brain.
label: Hippocampus

description: A structure located in the middle of the brain. The putamen is part of the basal ganglia and together with the caudate forms the striatum that influences motor activity.
label: Putamen

description: The portion of the brain located at the base of the skull that is responsible for balance, equilibrium and movement.
label: Cerebellum

description: The portion of the forebrain that is located between the telencephalon and the brainstem; it is composed of the thalamus, hypothalamus, subthalamus, and epithalamus, which functions to help regulate many activities of the autonomic nervous system.
label: Diencephalon

description: A dorsal posterior section of the diencephalon that comprises the trigonum habenula, habenular commissure, stria medullaris, and pineal gland. The epithalamus is the connection between the limbic system and basal ganglia, and is involved in the secretion of melatonin and the regulation of motor pathways and emotions.
label: Epithalamus

description: An important supervisory center in the brain, rich in ganglia, nerve fibers, and synaptic connections. It is composed of several sections called nuclei, each of which controls a specific function. The hypothalamus regulates body temperature, blood pressure, heartbeat, metabolism of fats and carbohydrates, and sugar levels in the blood. Through direct attachment to the pituitary gland, the hypothalamus also meters secretions controlling water balance and milk production in the female. The role of the hypothalamus in awareness of pleasure and pain is well established in the laboratory. It is involved in the expression of emotions, such as fear and rage, and in sexual behaviors. Despite its numerous vital functions, the hypothalamus in humans accounts for only 1/300 of total brain weight, and is about the size of an almond. Structurally, it is joined to the thalamus; the two work together to monitor the sleep-wake cycle.
label: Hypothalamus

description: An ovoid mass composed predominantly of gray substance and associated laminae of white substance. The thalamus is divided into anterior, medial, and lateral parts. The function of the thalamus is to relay sensory impulses and cerebellar and basal ganglia projections to the cerebral cortex. The thalamus is positioned within the posterior part of the diencephalon forming most of each lateral wall of the third ventricle.
label: Thalamus

description: The part of the diencephalon that is located between the dorsal thalamus and the tegmentum of the midbrain, including the subthalamic nucleus, the medially adjacent prerubral area, and, posteriorly, the zona incerta.
label: Ventral Thalamus

description: The dorsal part or roof plate of the midbrain, which consists of the pretectal area and the paired superior and inferior colliculi.
label: Tectum Mesencephali

description: A region in the brain that is located below the tentorium cerebelli and contains the cerebellum.
label: Infratentorial Brain

description: The uppermost portion of the brainstem located between the pons and the diencephalon. The midbrain contains the cerebral peduncles, oculomotor, trochlear and red nuclei, substantia nigra and various other nuclei and tracts.
label: Mesencephalon

description: The middle portion of the brainstem located between the midbrain and the medulla oblongata. The fourth ventricle lies dorsal to the pons which also contains the motor trigeminal nuclei and the abducens nuclei. The cerebellum contributes a large number of afferent fibers to the pons.
label: Pons Varolii

description: The anterior pointed end of a cerebral hemisphere.
label: Frontal Pole

description: Blood vessels forming villous structures in the third, fourth, and lateral ventricles of the brain.
label: Choroid Plexus

description: Two vascular fringes, one on each side of the lower part of the roof of the fourth ventricle where cerebrospinal fluid is produced.
label: Choroid Plexus of the Fourth Ventricle

description: A vascular fringe projecting from the choroidal fissure into each lateral ventricle where cerebrospinal fluid is produced.
label: Choroid Plexus of the Lateral Ventricle

description: Two rows of vascular fringes projecting from the underside of the tela choroidea where it exists over the third ventricle where cerebrospinal fluid is produced.
label: Choroid Plexus of the Third Ventricle

description: Area within the sulci of the brain, usually anterior to the rolandic fissure.
label: Cerebral Convexity

description: Cranial cavity between the brow and nose in the frontal area of the brain.
label: Olfactory Groove

description: The portion of the pons, located ventral to the medial lemnisci, that contains the pontine nuclei and the cortocobulbar, corticospinal, corticopontine, and transverse pontocerebellar fibers.
label: Pontine Base

description: A white matter structure in the subcortical region of the brain that contains a high concentration of motor and sensory projection nerve fibers. It consists of the anterior limb, genu, posterior limb, and the retrolentiform and sublentiform parts.
label: Internal Capsule

description: The front region of the cingulate cortex that is located in the medial frontal lobe, adjacent to the corpus callosum. The anterior cingulate functions in decision making and in the regulation of emotions and physiological processes like blood pressure and heart rate.
label: Anterior Cingulate Cortex

description: The segments of the corticospinal and corticobulbar tracts that either traverse or terminate in the brainstem.
label: Brainstem Portion of the Pyramidal Tracts

description: The segments of the corticospinal and corticobulbar tracts that traverse the internal capsule.
label: Internal Capsule of the Pyramidal Tracts

description: The region of the brain that consists of the precentral and postcentral gyri and is involved in somatosensory and motor functions.
label: Sensorimotor Cortex

description: The caudal region of the cingulate cortex, located within the medial part of the inferior parietal lobule, that is thought to function as an interface between emotion and cognition.
label: Posterior Cingulate Cortex

description: A rounded division of the brain; the brain has 4 lobes.
label: Lobe of Brain

description: A tract of white matter ascending from the thalamus to the cortex. These tracts support cognitive, perceptual and motor systems in the cortex.
label: Corona Radiata

description: Any one of the three lobes that make up the cerebellum of the brain.
label: Cerebellar Lobe

description: The portion of the internal capsule of the brain that is located posterior to the genu.
label: Posterior Limb of Internal Capsule

description: The posterior bulbous part of the corpus callosum situated, which is located anterior to the occipital lobe, and which overhangs the thalamic pulvinars, the pineal gland and tectum of the midbrain; Its fibers connect occipital and parietal cortices, as well as inferior and medial temporal regions.
label: Splenium of the Corpus Callosum

description: A gyrus or ridge in the occipital lobe of the brain between the superior and middle occipital sulci.
label: Middle Occipital Convolution

description: A channel that connects the third and fourth ventricles of the brain.
label: Aqueduct of Sylvius

description: A region of the brain located in the frontal lobe of the dominant hemisphere; it plays an essential role in the motor control of speech.
label: Area of Broca

description: A convolution in the cerebral hemisphere between the central sulcus and the precentral sulcus.
label: Ascending Frontal Convolution

description: A convolution in the temporal lobe between the interparietal sulcus and the central sulcus.
label: Ascending Parietal Convolution

description: Anatomical structure located in the vertebral forebrain that receives neural input regarding odors that have been detected by cells within the nasal cavity. The axons of olfactory receptor cells extend into the olfactory bulb.
label: Olfactory Bulb

description: The white myelinated fibers in the hippocampus adjacent to the wall of the lateral ventricle.
label: Alveus

description: The inferior surface of the brain as viewed from below.
label: Base of the Brain

description: A rounded band or bundle of nerve fibers that connects the two hemispheres of the brain.
label: Anterior Commissure

description: An experimental concept that relates to the anterior region of the olfactory bulb.
label: Anterior Olfactory Lobule

description: The frontal aspect of the cistern of the corpus callosum.
label: Anterior Portion of the Corpus Callosum Cistern

description: A very thin, curved lamina comprised of subcortical gray matter that is lateral to the putamen, medial to the insular cortex, and between the external and extreme capsules.
label: Claustrum

description: An area within the corpus callosum, a white matter structure within the cleft that separates the left and right cerebral hemispheres in the mammalian brain, between the genu (anterior region) and the splenium (posterior region).
label: Body of the Corpus Callosum

description: An irregularly curved cavity that extends from the interventricular foramen to the splenium of the corpus callosum in the brain.
label: Body of the Lateral Ventricle

description: A funnel-shaped tube of grey matter and axons that connects the hypothalamus to the posterior pituitary. The infundibulum is open to the third ventricle to allow for the release of antidiuretic hormone and oxytocin.
label: Brain Infundibulum

description: The horn shaped region in the brain, also known as the hippocampus, which is divided into four sub-areas, CA1 through CA4.
label: Cornu Ammonis

description: White fibrous bodies that form as a result of ruptured follicles in the ovary.
label: Corpora Albicantia

description: The nerve fibers running from the cortex to the tegmentum, pontine gray matter, and the spinal cord. They form a large bundle of corticofugal fibers extending longitudinally on each side of the midline on the ventral surface of the midbrain.
label: Crus Cerebri

description: The first of four fields in the cornu ammonis of the hippocampus which receives inputs from the perforant path originating in layer III of the entorhinal cortex. This area consists of pyramidal cells that send axons to layer V of the entorhinal cortex and the subiculum.
label: CA1 Field of the Cornu Ammonis

description: The second of four fields in the cornu ammonis of the hippocampus which receives inputs from the perforant path originating in layer II of the entorhinal cortex. This area is small, contains pyramidal cells, and does not contain mossy fiber connections from the dentate gyrus.
label: CA2 Field of the Cornu Ammonis

description: The third of four regions in the cornu ammonis of the hippocampus which receives inputs from mossy fibers originating from the granule cells in the dentate gyrus and from inputs along the perforant path originating in layers II and III within the entorhinal cortex. This area contains pyramidal cells that send axons to the CA1 field and acts as a pacemaker, setting the pace for neuronal firing in the hippocampus.
label: CA3 Field of the Cornu Ammonis

description: The last of four regions in the cornu ammonis of the hippocampus and is also part of the hilus of the dentate gyrus. This area contains mostly mossy cells that receive inputs from the dentate gyrus and pyramidal cells in the CA3 region and also projects back to the dentate gyrus.
label: CA4 Field of the Cornu Ammonis

description: An invaginated portion of the cerebral cortex forming the base of the sylvian fissure.  It is part of the lateral side of the cortex and its function includes the processing of emotions, memory, and higher autonomic control.
label: Central Lobe

description: The short gyri in the anterior insula.
label: Gyri Breves Insulae

description: The longer gyri in the posterior insula.
label: Gyrus Longus Insulae

description: A thin lamina of white matter comprising long association fibers located between the claustrum and putamen in the brain, and which connects the midportion of the superotemporal region with the midportion of the ventral and lateral aspects of the prefrontal cortex.
label: External Capsule

description: A serrated strip of gray matter under the medial border of the hippocampus and in its depths. It is an archicortex which develops along the edge of the hippocampal fissure and which consists of molecular, granular, and polymorphic layers.
label: Dentate Gyrus

description: A header term that encompasses the various cerebral fissure terms.
label: Cerebral Fissure

description: The anterior portion of a deep fissure or furrow on the medial surface of the cerebral cortex.
label: Anterior Part of the Calcarine Fissure

description: A narrow groove along the medial wall of the lateral ventricle from which the choroid plexus attaches.
label: Choroidal Fissure

description: A long deep groove on the tentorial surface below the posterior and descending horns of the lateral ventricle which extends from the posterior extremity of the brain to the tip of the temporal lobe.
label: Collateral Fissure

description: The double-S-shaped fold or fissure on the lateral surface of each hemisphere of the cerebral cortex. The central sulcus separates the primary somatosensory cortex from the primary motor cortex and the frontal lobe from the parietal lobe.
label: Fissure of Rolando

description: The deepest and most prominent groove on the lateral surface of the brain beginning at the anterior perforated substance that runs back and slightly upwards. The fissure of Sylvius, also known as the lateral cerebral sulcus, separates the frontal and parietal lobes from the temporal lobe.
label: Fissure of Sylvius

description: A shallow groove between the dentate gyrus and the parahippocampal gyrus; the remains of a fissure extending deep into the hippocampus between Ammon's horn and the dentate gyrus which becomes obliterated during foetal development.
label: Hippocampal Fissure

description: A long deep groove extending the entire length of the brain separating the two hemispheres.
label: Longitudinal Fissure

description: A long deep groove with an internal and external portion in the cerebral cortex creating a boundary between the parietal lobe and cuneus.
label: Parieto-Occipital Fissure

description: The deep, one inch long portion of the parieto-occipital fissure, a groove, on the outer surface of the cerebral cortex midway between the occipital lobe and the fissure of Rolando.
label: External Parieto-Occipital Fissure

description: The longer vertical portion of the parieto-occipital fissure, a deep groove, on the medial surface of the cerebral cortex extending from the hippocampal gyrus and separating the precuneus and cuneus as well as the occipital and parietal lobes.
label: Internal Parieto-Occipital Fissure

description: The C-shaped bundle of axons in the midline of the brain which originate in both hemispheres of the hippocampus and project to the contralateral hippocampus and septum, mammillary body, and the anterior nucleus of the thalamus.
label: Cerebral Fornix

description: The convolutions or ridges between one or more sulci on the surface of the cerebral cortex.
label: Cerebral Gyrus

description: The portion of the cingulate gyrus that lies inferior to the superior frontal gyrus, and is separated from it by the cingulate sulcus; it ends inferior to the rostrum of the corpus callosum.
label: Anterior Cingulate Gyrus

description: The portion of the brain located in the parietal lobe that plays a role in intersensory processing, language comprehension, and cognition.
label: Angular Gyrus

description: The convolutions or ridges on either side of the collateral sulcus.
label: Collateral Gyrus

description: A gyrus or ridge on the outer surface of the temporal lobe below the middle sulcus.
label: Inferior Temporal Gyrus

description: A set of cerebral gyri or ridges (superior, middle, and inferior frontal gyri) located anteriorly to the precentral gyrus on the lateral surface of the frontal lobe.
label: Frontal Gyrus

description: A relatively large region on the lateral surface of the frontal lobe and part of the prefrontal cortex, which lies between the superior and the inferior frontal sulci and rostral to the precentral gyrus.
label: Middle Frontal Gyrus

description: A region on the surface of the frontal lobe visibly divided into three parts: the pars opercularis, the pars triangularis, and the pars orbitalis. It is bound by the inferior frontal sulcus dorsally and the lateral fissure ventrally.
label: Inferior Frontal Gyrus

description: A region of the brain, located on the inferior frontal gyrus, that contains part of Broca's area, which is an important neuroanatomical region used in speech and language production.
label: Middle Inferior Frontal Convolution

description: The orbital part of the inferior frontal convolution.
label: Anterior Inferior Frontal Convolution

description: A gyrus on the outer surface of the left frontal lobe of the cerebrum located between the inferior frontal sulcus and the fissure of Sylvius that is involved in response inhibition.
label: Left Inferior Frontal Convolution

description: A gyrus on the outer surface of the right frontal lobe of the cerebrum located between the inferior frontal sulcus and the fissure of Sylvius that is involved in response inhibition.
label: Right Inferior Frontal Convolution

description: The dorsal portion of the inferior frontal gyrus, located on the frontal lobe of the brain, that is important for phonological word decisions.
label: Posterior Inferior Frontal Convolution

description: A large region of the frontal lobe of the brain located above the superior frontal sulcus that participates with the primary motor cortex in the control and initiation of voluntary movements and possibly contributes to higher cognitive functions.
label: Superior Frontal Gyrus

description: A gyrus or ridge on the outer surface of the temporal lobe between the superior and middle temporal sulci.
label: Middle Temporal Gyrus

description: A convolution located with fractions in both the occipital and temporal lobes of the brain, which is bound by the lingual (medial occipitotemporal) gyrus and parahippocampal gyrus superiorly, and the inferior temporal gyrus inferiorly.
label: Fusiform Gyrus

description: A large convolution located on the parietal lobe of the brain, located between the central and postcentral sulci, that corresponds to the primary somatic sensory cortex area.
label: Postcentral Gyrus

description: A cortical region or convolution on the dorsal surface of each cerebral hemisphere overlying the hippocampus between the hippocampal and collateral fissures, which includes the entorhinal cortex, the temporal cortical fields, and is considered part of the limbic system.
label: Parahippocampal Gyrus

description: A convolution located on the convex side of both cerebral hemispheres, anterior to the post central gyrus and parallel to the central sulcus, which separates the pre and post central gyri; much of the primary motor cortex corresponds to this gyrus.
label: Precentral Gyrus

description: A gyrus or ridge on the outer surface of the temporal lobe between the horizontal portion of the fissure of Sylvius and the superior temporal sulcus.
label: Superior Temporal Gyrus

description: A convolution located on the anterior part of the inferior parietal lobe of the brain. In the dominant hemisphere, it plays a role in the comprehension of written language.
label: Supramarginal Gyrus

description: A long curved fold located in the medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere.
label: Cingulate Gyrus

description: A region of the brain encompassing the crus cerebri and the midbrain tegmentum.
label: Cerebral Peduncle

description: A header term that encompasses the various cerebral sulcus terms.
label: Cerebral Sulcus

description: A semicircular groove or fissure separating the insula from the opercula.
label: Circular Sulcus

description: A cerebral fissure that originates near the occipital lobe and terminates below the corpus callosum.
label: Calcarine Sulcus

description: Cerebral sulci (grooves) located in the frontal lobe, including the superior frontal sulcus, inferior frontal sulcus, olfactory sulcus, and the orbital sulci.
label: Frontal Sulcus

description: A sulcus or fissure located in the frontal lobe between the middle frontal gyrus and the inferior frontal gyrus.
label: Inferior Frontal Sulcus

description: A fissure or narrow groove running rostrocaudally on the anterior surface of each frontal lobe of the brain separating the gyrus rectus from the medial orbital gyrus and containing the olfactory bulb and tract.
label: Olfactory Sulcus

description: An H shaped groove on the inferior surface of the frontal lobe dividing it into four orbital gyri.
label: Orbital Sulcus

description: A groove on the surface of each frontal lobe of the brain that separates the superior frontal gyrus from the middle frontal gyrus.
label: Superior Frontal Sulcus

description: A horizontal groove on the surface of the parietal lobe extending backward from the postcentral sulcus forming the ascending, superior and inferior parietal convolutions.
label: Intraparietal Sulcus

description: A sulcus or fissure located on the convex surface of the occipital lobe, posterior to the gyrus descendens and occasionally joined to the calcarine sulcus.
label: Lunate Sulcus

description: A horizontal groove on the lateral surface of the occipital lobe extending from the accessory lateral occipital sulci to the lunate sulcus that separates the superior occipital gyrus from the inferior occipital gyrus.
label: Lateral-Occipital Sulcus

description: Any one of the narrow grooves located on the surface of the occipital lobe of the brain.
label: Occipital Sulcus

description: A prominent furrow or groove located on the parietal lobe of the brain posteriorly and parallel to the central sulcus and ending superiorly to the posterior ramus of the lateral fissure.
label: Postcentral Sulcus

description: A long groove or furrow, located on the lateral surface of the frontal lobe of the brain, anterior and parallel to the central sulcus, and forming the rostral limit of the precentral gyrus; it is usually dived into a superior and an inferior segment and serves as a primary motor area of the brain.
label: Precentral Sulcus

description: A furrow or groove in the insular cortex that divides it into two parts: the larger, anterior; the smaller, posterior insula.
label: Sulcus Centralis Insulae

description: Any of three grooves in the temporal lobe including the inferior, middle, and superior temporal sulci.
label: Temporal Sulcus

description: A groove or cleft on the inferior surface of the temporal lobe running from the occipital pole to the anterior boundary of the temporal lobe.
label: Inferior Temporal Sulcus

description: A groove or cleft that divides the outer surface of the temporal lobe running in the same direction but at a lower level to the superior temporal sulcus.
label: Middle Temporal Sulcus

description: A groove or cleft that divides the outer surface of the temporal lobe running parallel to the horizontal portion of the fissure of Sylvius.
label: Superior Temporal Sulcus

description: One of four small oval masses that protrude slightly from the underside of the thalamus and function as synaptic centers on the way to the cerebral cortex.
label: Geniculate Body

description: The lateral of a pair of small oval masses that protrude slightly from the posteroinferior aspect of the thalamus; commonly considered a part of the metathalamus.
label: External Geniculate Body

description: The medial one of a pair of small masses that protrude from the posteroinferior part of the thalamus; commonly considered a part of the metathalamus.
label: Internal Geniculate Body

description: The anterior portion of the corpus callosum that bends downward and backward.
label: Genu of the Corpus Callosum

description: A fringe like structure.
label: Fimbria

description: Either side of the cerebellum separated by the vermis.
label: Hemisphere of the Cerebellum

description: The lower or ventral portion of the fourth ventricle transversed by the median sulcus with numerous nuclei and structures including the striae acusticae (or medullaris), fovea inferior and fovea superior, clava, obex, area postrema, and the trigonum hypoglossi and trigonum vagi.
label: Floor of the Fourth Ventricle

description: One of two openings into the subarachnoid space on the lateral surface of the fourth ventricle.
label: Foramen of Luschka

description: A large opening in the midline of the roof of the posterior interior section of the fourth ventricle.
label: Foramen of Magendie

description: The connection between the lateral ventricles with the third ventricle, which allows for the flow of CSF between the structures.
label: Foramen of Monroe

description: The part of the lateral ventricle located in the frontal lobe, anterior to the interventricular foramen (of Monro), and bounded by the septum pellucidum, fornix, and genu of the corpus callosum.
label: Frontal Horn of the Lateral Ventricle

description: An area of the brain comprised of the cerebellum, pons and medulla.
label: Epencephalon

description: A shallow groove dividing the dentate gyrus from the hippocampal CA1 field and the subiculum.
label: Hippocampal Sulcus

description: A triangular area containing the hypoglossal nucleus on either side of the dorsal median sulcus and superior to the vagal triangle.
label: Hypoglossal Triangle

description: Any one of the many cell groups located in the internal medullary lamina of the thalamus.
label: Intralaminar Nucleus

description: The main portion of the superior part of each hemisphere of the cerebellum, corresponding to the monticulus of the vermis; it is divided into two portions, the anterior and the posterior crescentic lobules, corresponding to the culmen and the declive of the vermis.
label: Lobus Quadratus

description: A gyrus or ridge in the occipital lobe of the brain below the middle occipital sulcus.
label: Inferior Occipital Convolution

description: A gyrus or ridge in the parietal lobe surrounded by the ascending and horizontal sections of the intra-parietal sulcus, the horizontal section of the fissure of Sylvius and the edge of the posterior parietal lobe. The inferior parietal convolution further divides into the supra-marginal and angular convolutions.
label: Inferior Parietal Convolution

description: A thin membrane of grey substance extending form the corpus callosum to the tuber cinereum above the optic chiasm and forming the anterior portion of the inferior border of the third ventricle.
label: Lamina Cinerea

description: One of the four areas of the lateral nucleus within the thalamus that receives inputs from the superior colliculus.
label: Lateral Posterior Nucleus of the Thalamus

description: A small, paired, spherical protuberance lying between the cerebral peduncles on the posterior portion of the hypothalamus, which functionally belongs to the medial limbic circuit.
label: Mamillary Body

description: The part of the lateral ventricle that projects posteriorly into the occipital lobe.
label: Occipital Horn of the Lateral Ventricle

description: A small, rounded neural structure involved in olfaction, which is located at the anterior end of the olfactory sulcus on the orbital surface of the frontal lobe, and which is attached to the rest of the brain by the olfactory tract.
label: Olfactory Lobe

description: A white band comprising axons originating in the olfactory bulb and running caudally along the orbital surface of each frontal lobe that terminate in the primary olfactory cortex at the base of the cerebral hemisphere.
label: Olfactory Tract

description: The bundle of optic nerve fibers that cross to the opposite side of the brain at the optic chiasm.
label: Optic Commissure

description: A continuation of the optic nerves just dorsal to the optic chiasm, formed by temporal fibers of the ipsilateral optic nerve and nasal fibers of the contralateral optic nerve, that carries axons to nuclei within the thalamus and relays visual information to the primary visual cortex of the occipital lobe.
label: Optic Tract

description: The most rostral and prominent of three divisions of the inferior frontal gyrus, which merges anteriorly with the lateral orbital gyri, superiorly with the anterior parts of the middle frontal gyrus, and posteriorly with the triangular part the inferior frontal gyrus.
label: Orbital Part of the Inferior Frontal Gyrus

description: A small fasciculus that decussates in the inferior pineal lamina in the midbrain, and is the junctional landmark between the diencephalon and the mesencephalon.
label: Posterior Commissure

description: The upper or dorsal portion of the fourth ventricle formed by a section of the superior peduncles of the cerebellum, the superior and inferior medullary velum, the tela choroidea inferior, the obex, and the ligula.
label: Roof of the Fourth Ventricle

description: The anterior-inferior aspect of the corpus callosum, which projects posteriorly and inferiorly from the genu, and which is continuous with the lamina terminalis.
label: Rostrum of the Corpus Callosum

description: An experimental concept that relates to the posterior region of the olfactory bulb.
label: Posterior Olfactory Lobule

description: The dorsal portion of the cistern that lies superior to the splenium of the corpus callosum and communicates with the quadrigeminal cistern.
label: Posterior Portion of the Corpus Callosum Cistern

description: A bilateral laminae of fibers, sparse grey matter, and neuroglia in the brain that separates the lateral ventricles and stretches inferiorly between the column and body of the fornix, and both superiorly and anteriorly to the corpus callosum.
