label: Septum Pellucidum

description: A bundle of nerve fibers that originates in the arcuate nuclei, traverses the floor of the fourth ventricle, and terminates in the inferior cerebellar peduncle.
label: Striae Medullares

description: A complex of structures, including the prosubiculum, presubiculum, postsubiculum and parasubiculum, and the subiculum proper, that is located between the entorhinal cortex and the CA1 subfield of the hippocampus proper, forming the most inferior portion of the hippocampal formation. The structure complex has a variety of functions, including working memory, spatial relations, and regulation of the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis.
label: Subiculum

description: A prominent furrow or groove in the cerebral cortex that divides the frontal lobe from the parietal lobe in the coronal plane, which demarcates the primary motor and somatosensory areas of the cortex.
label: Sulcus Centralis

description: A groove running rostrocaudally the length of the floor of the fourth ventricle on either side of the midline that separates structures derived from the basal plate (cranial nerve motor nuclei) from those derived from the alar plate (cranial nerve sensory nuclei).
label: Sulcus Limitans

description: A gyrus or ridge in the occipital lobe of the brain above the superior sulcus.
label: Superior Occipital Convolution

description: A gyrus or ridge in the parietal lobe surrounded by the post-central sulcus, external parieto-occipital fissure, horizontal section of the intra-parietal sulcus and the inner surface of the quadrate lobe.
label: Superior Parietal Convolution

description: The middle of three divisions of the inferior frontal gyrus (the other two being the pars opercularis, and the pars orbitalis) situated between the ascending ramus and the horizontal ramus of the lateral fissure and contains part of Broca's area, which is an important neuroanatomical region used in speech and language production.
label: Triangular Part of the Inferior Frontal Gyrus

description: The flattened, triangular portions of the olfactory tract located near the anterior perforated substance in the brain.
label: Trigonum Olfactorium

description: A convex mass of grey matter located between the mammillary bodies and the optic chiasma on the inferior surface of the hypothalamus, and from which the infundibulum extends to the posterior lobe of the hypophysis.
label: Tuber Cinereum

description: The anterior-most portion of the parahippocampal gyrus; it is part of the piriform cortex of the olfactory system.
label: Uncus

description: The inferior orbital portion of the prefrontal cortex that is concave and rests on the orbital plate of the frontal bone; it is divided into four gyri by a well-marked, H-shaped orbital sulcus: the medial, the anterior, the lateral, and the posterior orbital gyri.
label: Undersurface of the Frontal Lobe

description: The inferior or ventral portion of the temporal lobe, which is functionally part of the parahippocampal gyrus, and which, if damaged, will result in difficulty with memory encoding and retrieval.
label: Undersurface of the Temporal Lobe

description: A triangularly-shaped area that is located in the caudal part of the floor of the fourth ventricle of the brain, between the hypoglossal triangle and the vestibular area; it overlies multiple nuclei, including the vagus, glossopharyngeal, and cranial accessory nerves.
label: Vagal Triangle

description: A thin sheet of tissue that is continuous with the cerebellar white matter; it stretches across the fourth ventricle, between the two superior and the two inferior cerebellar peduncles, and, together with the inferior medullary velum, comprises the roof of the fourth ventricle.
label: Valve of Vieussens

description: A medial narrow structure connecting the two hemispheres of the cerebellum.
label: Vermis

description: The part of the diencephalon comprising the thalamus, metathalamus, and epithalamus.
label: Thalamencephalon

description: The largest part of the brain composed of the cerebral hemispheres, thalamus, hypothalamus, and the limbic system.
label: Forebrain

description: One of three major developmental divisions of the brain, comprising the pons, the medulla oblongata, and the cerebellum.
label: Hind-Brain

description: A hollow, funnel-shaped process of gray matter that connects the posterior lobe of the pituitary gland to the tuber cinereum of the hypothalamus.
label: Pituitary Stalk

description: The covering of the cerebellum, which is made up of a very tightly folded layer of gray matter
label: Cerebellar Cortex

description: The areas of the brain composed of neurons and (in contrast to the white matter) unmyelinated nerve fibers.
label: Brain Gray Matter

description: A large cell mass extending forward, over the dorsal surface of the crus cerebri, from the rostral border of the pons into the subthalamic region. It is composed of a dorsal stratum of closely spaced pigmented cells, the pars compacta, and a larger ventral region of widely scattered cells, the pars reticulata. The pars compacta includes numerous cells that project forward to the striatum (caudate nucleus and putamen) and contain dopamine, which acts as the primary neurotransmitter at the synaptic endings. Other, apparently non-dopaminergic cells project to portions of the ventral nucleus of thalamus, the superior colliculus and reticular formation. The nigrostriatal projection is reciprocated by a striatonigral fiber system with multiple neurotransmitters, chief among which is gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA). The substantia nigra is involved in the metabolic disturbances associated with Parkinson's disease and Huntington's disease.
label: Substantia Nigra

description: The grey matter on the medial, lateral, and orbital surfaces of the anterior part of the frontal cortex, which play a role in complex cognitive control, emotion, and social behavior.
label: Prefrontal Cortex

description: The gray matter that includes the basal ganglia and/or thalamus.
label: Deep Gray Matter

description: list()
label: Brain White Matter

description: list()
label: Cerebellum White Matter

description: A type of brain tissue in the cerebrum consisting of myelinated axons and glial cells.
label: Cerebral White Matter

description: A white matter structure within the cleft that separates the left and right cerebral hemispheres in the mammalian brain. It is composed of a wide, flat bundle of 200-250 million axonal projections.
label: Corpus Callosum

description: A mass of neuronal cells in a distinct area of the brain.
label: Brain Nucleus

description: The grey matter adjacent to each lateral ventricle of the brain that comprises the medial dorsal striatum of the basal ganglia. The caudate nucleus is primarily involved in body and limb posture and movement.
label: Caudate Nucleus

description: The paired, biconvex cluster of neurons located under the thalamus that plays a major role in the motor cortico-basal ganglia-thalamo-cortical circuit. The subthalamic nucleus is primary involved in the control of voluntary movement.
label: Subthalamic Nucleus

description: An oval shaped cell group located in the subthalamus of the diencephalon, located between the medial part of the cerebral peduncle and the thalamus, and considered part of the functional basal ganglia.
label: Oval Subthalamic Nucleus

description: The part of the brain that is located superior to the tentorium cerebelli.
label: Supratentorial Brain

description: A collection of neurons of cranial nerve III located in the rostral half of the midbrain at the level of the superior colliculus, which contain somatic efferent motor neurons that innervate all the extraocular muscles except the superior oblique and lateral rectus.
label: Oculomotor Nucleus

description: The cranial nuclei, located in both the pons and the medulla, for the vestibular nerve.
label: Vestibular Nucleus

description: A locus on the floor of the lateral surface of the fourth ventricle where auditory nerves form the cochlea synapse in the brain stem.
label: Dorsal Cochlear Nucleus

description: One of the four vestibular nuclei situated on the floor and lateral wall of the fourth ventricle that receives inputs from the vestibular nerve.
label: Lateral Vestibular Nucleus

description: The largest of four vestibular nuclei, located on the floor of the fourth ventricle, on either side of the medulla oblongata.
label: Medial Vestibular Nucleus

description: The smallest of the four vestibular nuclei located dorsally and rostrally in the vestibular complex and limited to the caudal pons, where it is situated in the wall of the 4th ventricle in the brain; it is involved in vestibuloocular reflex pathways.
label: Superior Vestibular Nucleus

description: The smallest of four vestibular nuclei, which is located in the lower medulla near the fourth ventricle, lying between the medial vestibular nucleus and the inferior cerebellar peduncle.
label: Spinal Vestibular Nucleus

description: A very slender, longitudinal column of motor neurons in the ventrolateral medulla oblongata; its efferent fibres leave with the vagus and glossopharyngeal nerve and innervate the striated muscle fibres of the pharynx (including the musculus levator veli palatini) and the vocal cord muscles of the larynx.
label: Nucleus Ambiguus

description: The cranial nerve nucleus from which the abducens nerve originates from. It is located in the middle portion of the brain stem.
label: Abducens Nucleus

description: A collection of cell bodies of cranial nerve VII found in the brainstem. There are three nuclei with distinct functions: the facial motor nucleus, which sends muscular efferent nerves to the muscles of facial expression and the stapedius; the superior salivary nucleus, which sends visceral parasympathetic efferent nerves mostly to the lacrimal and salivary glands; and the geniculate ganglion, which receives mostly afferent nerves for taste sensation.
label: Facial Nerve Nucleus

description: A motor nucleus within the medulla oblongata with axons projecting to the tongue muscles.
label: Nucleus of the Hypoglossal Nerve

description: A brain nucleus located in the medulla oblongata.
label: Dorsal Motor Nucleus

description: A cluster of nerve cell bodies that form a column of gray matter in the dorsomedial region of the medulla oblongata. The solitary nucleus comprises the gustatory and visceral sensory nuclei of the brainstem, processing impulses from the taste buds, pharynx, larynx, intestinal and respiratory tracts, heart, and large blood vessels.
label: Solitary Nucleus

description: A group of subcortical nuclei of the basal ganglia comprising the caudate and putamen dorsally, and the nucleus accumbens as well as the olfactory tubercle ventrally.
label: Striatum Nuclei

description: One of a pair of nuclei of the intralaminar nucleus of the dorsal thalamus, which receives afferent fibers from the cerebral cortex, vestibular nuclei, globus pallidus, superior colliculus, reticular formation, and spinothalamic tract, and sends efferent fibers to the subthalamic nucleus and putamen.
label: Centromedian Nucleus of the Thalamus

description: The principal parasympathetic nucleus of the brain located within the fourth ventricle of the medulla oblongata, which transmits parasympathetic signals to thoracic and abdominal viscera.
label: Dorsal Nucleus of the Vagus Nerve

description: The principal thalamic nucleus for the prefrontal cortex, which relays signals to the prefrontal cortex and limbic system, and assists with memory and pain processing.
label: Dorsomedial Nucleus of the Thalamus

description: A large, cone-shaped area of gray matter within the basal ganglia comprised of the globus pallidus and putamen that is surrounded primarily by the caudate nucleus and the thalamus.
label: Lenticular Nucleus

description: An aggregation of CN V cell bodies located in the mid-pons at the level of attachment of the trigeminal nerve to the brainstem; it is the origin of special visceral efferent (motor) fibers that innervate the muscles of mastication.
label: Motor Nucleus of the Trigeminal Nerve

description: A collection of cell bodies of cranial nerve V, extending from the chief sensory nucleus through the midbrain, that connect to primary afferents receiving proprioceptive input from the face.
label: Nucleus of the Mesencephalic Tract of the Trigeminal Nerve

description: The site of termination for fibers of the spinal trigeminal tract, located in the lateral medulla and extending in into the caudal pons, that receives input from the ipsilateral face via somatic afferent fibers for touch, pain, and temperature.
label: Nucleus of the Spinal Tract of the Trigeminal Nerve

description: Part of the posterior (caudal) intralaminar group of thalamic nuclei, located medial to the centromedian nucleus and ventral to the dorsomedial nuclei, that is associated with the limbic and associative striatum.
label: Parafascicular Nucleus of the Thalamus

description: list()
label: Posterior Nucleus of the Thalamus

description: A collection of second order neurons, located in the pons lateral to the trigeminal motor nucleus and medial to the middle cerebellar peduncle, that receive and relay data regarding both light touch and discriminative sensation of the face, as well as conscious proprioception of the jaw.
label: Principal Sensory Nucleus of the Trigeminal Nerve

description: A motor nucleus that is part of the ventral tier of the lateral thalamic nuclei group, which connects with the corpus striatum.
label: Ventroanterior Nucleus of the Thalamus

description: A motor nucleus that is part of the ventral tier of the lateral thalamic nuclei group, which projects to the cerebral motor cortex.
label: Ventrolateral Nucleus of the Thalamus

description: Part of the ventral posterior nuclei of the thalamus, which relays sensory input from the body.
label: Ventroposterior Lateral Nucleus of the Thalamus

description: Part of the ventral posterior nuclei of the thalamus, which relays sensory input from the face.
label: Ventroposterior Medial Nucleus of the Thalamus

description: A nucleus that is located in the olfactory tract.
label: Anterior Olfactory Nucleus

description: A nucleus located in the middle hypothalamus in the most ventral part of the third ventricle near the entrance of the infundibular recess. Its small cells are in close contact with the ependyma.
label: Arcuate Nucleus

description: One of the dorsal column nuclei in the medulla oblongata, which is part of posterior column-medial lemniscus pathway, carrying sensory information from most the upper body to the contralateral thalamus via the medial lemniscus.
label: Cuneate Nucleus

description: A nucleus composed of neurons in the forebrain.
label: Accumbens Nucleus

description: A tear-shaped dense area of cells in the hypothalamus, which is responsible for regulating circadian rhythms.
label: Suprachiasmatic Nucleus

description: A brainstem nucleus. It is the major brain site for the synthesis and secretion of norepinephrine.
label: Locus Coeruleus

description: A group of nuclei that are located in the midline of the brainstem and release serotonin.
label: Raphe Nuclei

description: A brain structure that is part of the septal nuclear complex. It is connected with the hippocampus, hypothalamus and amygdala.
label: Nucleus of Diagonal Band

description: A region of the brain at the junction of the pons, cerebellum, and medulla. It is a frequent site of tumor formation.
label: Cerebellopontine Angle

description: One of three pairs of nerve fiber bundles that originate from the cerebellum and link it to the brainstem.
label: Cerebellar Peduncle

description: The left and right middle cerebellar peduncles that connect the cerebellum to the pons.
label: Brachium Pontis

description: An anatomic structure formed by the crossing of the two optic nerves under the hypothalamus.
label: Optic Chiasm

description: A complex brain system comprised of primitive cortical and subcortical structures and fiber pathways that connect with the diencephalon and brain stem, which plays a role in the control of emotional behavior and motivational drives.
label: Limbic System

description: A part of the substantia nigra. The pars compacta nerve cells contain melanin and are involved in motor control.
label: Pars Compacta

description: The layer located below the cerebral cortex that includes the forebrain, midbrain and hindbrain.
label: Cerebral Subcortex

description: The mechanism for restricting the passage of charged ions and large molecules from the blood into the brain and central nervous system (CNS) by employing a unique capillary bed with tight junctions between the endothelial cells.
label: Blood-Brain Barrier

description: The space between the arachnoid membrane and the pia mater; it contains connective tissue, cerebrospinal fluid, and large blood vessels that supply the brain and spinal cord.
label: Subarachnoid Space

description: The parenchyma of the spinal cord, which consists of a canal surrounded by a neuron containing gray matter centrally and white matter containing myelinated nerve tracts peripherally.
label: Spinal Cord Parenchyma

description: The potential body space between the arachnoid membrane and the dura mater.
label: Subdural Space

description: An opening in the medial portion of the middle cranial fossa through which the trigeminal nerve passes.
label: Trigeminal Cave

description: Any component of the central nervous system contained within the spinal column or the vertebral canal.
label: Spinal Cord Part

description: A collection of gelatinous-appearing grey matter cells in the dorsal horn of the spinal cord that receives direct input from the dorsal nerve roots and plays a role in regulating pain impulses at the spinal cord level.
label: Substantia Gelatinosa

description: The portion of the spinal cord located in the sacral region.
label: Sacral Spinal Cord

description: The terminal, cone-shaped end of the spinal cord.
label: Conus Medullaris

description: The hollow tube filled with cerebrospinal fluid that begins in the inferior portion of the fourth ventricle and runs the entire length of the spinal.
label: Central Canal of Spinal Cord

description: The portion of the spinal cord located in the cervical region.
label: Cervical Spinal Cord

description: The portion of the spinal cord located in the thoracic region.
label: Thoracic Spinal Cord

description: The portion of the spinal cord located in the lumbar region.
label: Lumbar Spinal Cord

description: The point at the base of the skull where the brainstem and cervical spine intersect.
label: Cervicomedullary Junction

description: A bundle of nerve fibers crossing from one side to the other side of the brain or spinal cord.
label: Commissure

description: A small area of gray matter surrounding the central canal in the spinal cord.
label: Gray Commissure

description: A collection of myelinated fibers, comprising fibers from both the spinothalamic tract and the anterior corticospinal tract, that crosses the midline of the spinal cord immediately ventral to the gray commissure.
label: White Commissure

description: The nervous tissue found in that part of the central nervous system that is lodged in the vertebral canal. It contains fewer myelinated fibers, but more nerve cell bodies, unmyelinated nerve fibers and blood vessels than the white matter.
label: Gray Matter of the Spinal Cord

description: Any of the four main columns of gray matter, which are located in the spinal cord, and which are composed primarily of neuronal cell bodies and neuroglia.
label: Spinal Cord Gray Matter Column

description: The posterior column of gray matter extending the length of the spinal cord.
label: Dorsal Horn of the Spinal Cord

description: An area of grey matter in the thoracic region of the spinal cord forming a laterally projecting triangle from the center of either side of the spinal cord.
label: Lateral Horn of the Spinal Cord

description: An area of grey matter containing motor neurons that projects anteriorly from either side of the center of the spinal cord.
label: Ventral Horn of the Spinal Cord

description: Any of the grooves on in the spinal cord.
label: Spinal Cord Fissure

description: A fissure in the midline of the anterior surface of the spinal cord.
label: Anterior Median Fissure of the Spinal Cord

description: A narrow groove in the center of the posterior surface of the spine.
label: Posterior Median Fissure of the Spinal Cord

description: A narrow groove on either side of the posterior median fissure of the spinal cord where the posterior nerve roots enter.
label: Posterolateral Fissure of the Spinal Cord

description: The initial segment of a spinal nerve as it emerges from the spinal cord as an anterior motor root, after which it unites with the dorsal sensory root to form the single spinal nerve.
label: Ventral Nerve Root

description: The superficial nerve tissue of the spinal cord. It is composed of nerve cell processes, i.e. extensions (axons), which connect various grey matter areas of the spinal cord to each other and carry nerve impulses to and from the nerve cell bodies within the central nervous system (neurons). Spinal white matter does not contain dendrites. White matter is distinguished in that it is composed of axonal nerve fibers covered by a myelin sheath.
label: White Matter of the Spinal Cord

description: White matter in the spinal cord comprising longitudinally oriented nerve fibers (axons) that transmit impulses in both directions: ascending tracts transmit sensory information to the brain from the body, and descending tracts transmit impulses from the brain to the muscles.
label: Spinal Cord Tract

description: A nervous tract that transmits pain, temperature, and touch sensations and position and vibratory sense to the brain.
label: Ascending Spinal Cord Tract

description: A bundle of axon fibers and a sensory (ascending) tract in the lateral portions of the dorsal columns of the spinal cord lying between the posterolateral sulcus and the anterolateral sulcus, which transmits information from the upper half of the body.
label: Tract of Burdach

description: A bundle of axon fibers and a sensory (ascending) tract in the dorsal column of the spinal cord that lies medial to the cuneate fasciculus (above the mid-thoracic region), which transmits information from the lower half of the body.
label: Tract of Goll

description: A small bundle of axon fibers and a sensory (ascending) tract located at the periphery of the dorsal horn that runs throughout the length of the spinal cord and, after synapsing on second-order neurons in the dorsal horn, decussates, and then ascends within the spinothalamic tracts.
label: Tract of Lissauer

description: The nervous tract that carries pain, temperature, and tactile signals from the periphery to the brain.
label: Anterolateral Ascending Tract

description: Neural fibers of the spinal cord, that are grouped into tracts or fasciculi, and send motor signals from the brain to lower motor neurons. These tracts function to control muscle tone, posture, precise motor movements, spinal reflexes, and spinal autonomic functions.
label: Descending Spinal Cord Tract

description: An oval shaped area within the corticospinal tract that runs the entire length of the spinal cord just medial to the posterior spinocerebellar tract and contains motor nerve fibers originating from the opposite cerebral hemisphere.
label: Crossed Pyramidal Tract

description: A bundle of neuronal fibers originating in the lumbosacral spinal cord that ascend to the ipsilateral cerebellum conveying proprioceptive information for the lower limbs and joints.
label: Direct Cerebellar Tract

description: A small bundle of ipsilateral neuronal fibers originating in the motor region of the cerebral cortex that descend down the spinal cord.
label: Direct Pyramidal Tract

description: The lateral white column of the spinal cord between the lines of exit and entrance of the anterior and posterior nerve roots.
label: Anterolateral Spinal Cord Column

description: Spinal white matter located in the dorsal portion of the spinal column, and composed of two ascending tracts: the fasciculus gracilis and fasciculus cuneatus, both of which are composed of myelinated fibers carrying proprioceptive, exteroceptive, and vibratory sensation to higher levels.
label: Posterior Spinal Cord Column

description: Small projection of the arachnoid membrane through the dura into a venous sinus.
label: Arachnoid Villus

description: A small triangular process of dura matter beginning at the internal occipital crest just beneath the tentorium and projecting forward.
label: Falx Cerebelli

description: A fold of dura mater covering the sella turcica, which forms the roof over the pituitary fossa. It has a small opening in its center, through which the pituitary stalk passes.
label: Diaphragma Sellae

description: The superficial layer of the cranial dura mater that lines the inner surface of the skull and functions as its periosteum.
label: Periosteal Layer of the Dura Mater

description: The tissue that envelops the brain or spinal cord.
label: Membrane of the Brain or Spinal Cord

description: Any one of three membranes that surround the brain and spinal cord.
label: Meninges

description: The membranes that envelop and protect the brain.
label: Cerebral Meninges

description: Connective tissue membranes that surround and support the spinal cord and cauda equina. They are continuous with cranial meninges, which surround and support the brain.
label: Spinal Meninges

description: The two innermost layers of tissue that cover the brain and spinal cord, the arachnoid mater and the pia mater.
label: Leptomeninges

description: The inner layer of the dura mater surrounding the brain. It is mostly fused with the outer layer, the endocranium that is adherent to the inner aspect of the cranial bones. These two layers form the dura mater. The latter covers and protects the brain and the spinal cord.
label: Meningeal Layer of the Dura Mater

description: The outermost, toughest, and most fibrous of the three membranes (meninges) that surround and protect the brain and spinal cord.
label: Dura Mater

description: The outermost, toughest, and most fibrous of the membranes (meninges) that surround and protect the brain.
label: Brain Dura Mater

description: Evidence of spinal cord dura mater.
label: Spinal Cord Dura Mater

description: A delicate fibrous membrane interposed between the dura mater and the pia mater of the brain and spinal cord. It is separated from the pia mater by the subarachnoid space.
label: Arachnoid Membrane

description: list()
label: Brain Arachnoid Membrane

description: list()
label: Spinal Cord Arachnoid Membrane

description: The delicate, highly vascular, innermost membrane encasing the brain and spinal cord.
label: Pia Mater

description: list()
label: Brain Pia Mater

description: list()
label: Spinal Cord Pia Mater

description: Structures that have evolved from embryonic development of the neural tube. The ependyma is a specialised epithelium lining the ventricles and central canal of the brain and spinal cord. The remnants of the central canal of the spinal cord represent modified ependyma left from embryonic development of the neural tube
label: Ependyma and Remnants of the Central Canal of the Spinal Cord

description: A thin membrane that lines the ventricles of the brain and the central canal of the spinal cord.
label: Ependyma

description: The thin epithelial membrane lining the fourth ventricle of the brain.
label: Fourth Ventricle Ependyma

description: list()
label: Lateral Ventricle Ependyma

description: Tissue located below the ependyma lining the ventricles of the brain and central canal of the spinal cord. It is a dense feltwork of glial processes and is believed to contain neural stem cells.
label: Subependymal Tissue

description: A solid strand of modified ependyma left from embryonic development of the neural tube.
label: Remnants of the Central Canal of the Spinal Cord

description: One of any of the widened areas within the subarachnoid space in the brain, which lie between the arachnoid and the pia mater, and which are filled with cerebrospinal fluid.
label: Subarachnoid Cistern

description: Any of the following subarachnoid cisterns: anterior, lateral, posterior and superior infratentorial cistern.
label: Infratentorial Cistern

description: An anterior infratentorial subarachnoid cistern.
label: Anterior Infratentorial Cistern

description: A cavity within the subarachnoid space between the two temporal lobes and in front of the pons.
label: Interpeduncular Cistern

description: An area within the subarachnoid space, located between the arachnoid mater overlying the lower clivus and the anterior surface of the medulla oblongata, that contains the vertebral arteries and their branches, and the rootlets of CN XII.
label: Premedullary Cistern

description: An area within the subarachnoid space, located between the arachnoid mater overlying the upper clivus and the anterior surface of the pons, that contains many blood vessels, including the basilar artery.
label: Prepontine Cistern

description: A lateral infratentorial subarachnoid cistern.
label: Lateral Infratentorial Cistern

description: The inferior aspect of cerebellopontine cistern.
label: Inferior Cerebellopontine Cistern

description: The dorsal portion of the subarachnoid cistern, located in the midbrain, that is continuous with the quadrigeminal cistern and connects with the interpeduncular cistern.
label: Posterior Part of the Ambient Cistern

description: The superior aspect of cerebellopontine cistern.
label: Superior Cerebellopontine Cistern

description: A posterior infratentorial subarachnoid cistern.
label: Posterior Infratentorial Cistern

description: The largest of the three principle cisterns in the subarachnoid space which is located between the cerebellum and the medulla oblongata.
label: Cisterna Magna

description: A space filled with cerebrospinal fluid located between the undersurface of the tentorium and the upper surface of the cerebellum; it blends anterosuperiorly with the quadrigeminal cistern and cisterna ambiens.
label: Superior Cerebellar Cistern

description: A superior infratentorial subarachnoid cistern.
label: Superior Infratentorial Cistern

description: A superior infratentorial cistern that is interposed between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater, inferior to the midline tentorium and the superior surface of the vermis beneath it.
label: Vermian Cistern

description: The hollow space between the medial surface of the cerebral hemisphere and the falx cerebri.
label: Hemispheric Cistern

description: A subarachnoid cistern that is located superior to the tentorium cerebelli in the brain.
label: Supratentorial Cistern

description: One of the supratentorial cisterns. It is also called parasellar supratentorial cistern.
label: Anterior Supratentorial Cistern

description: The cavity surrounding the optic chiasm.
label: Chiasmatic Cistern

description: The cavity surrounding the internal carotid artery on either side of the optic chiasm.
label: Carotid Cistern

description: A cavity within the subarachnoid space in front of the lamina terminalis.
label: Lamina Terminalis Cistern

description: A pair of microanatomical triangular shaped spaces located in the superficial part of each olfactory sulcus, which contain the olfactory nerves and the orbitofrontal branches of the anterior cerebral arteries.
label: Olfactory Cistern

description: A cerebrospinal fluid-filled subarachnoid space extending into the Sylvian fissure that separates the temporal lobe from both the frontal and the parietal lobes; it contains the middle cerebral artery and some of its branches.
label: Sylvian Cistern

description: Any of the nine supratentorial cisterns within the subarachnoid space that occur laterally.
label: Lateral Supratentorial Cistern

description: An expansion of the subarachnoid space extending forward between the corpus callosum and the thalamus; it encloses the internal cerebral veins.
label: Ambient Cistern

description: The cavity situated in front of the pons between the temporal lobes over the diencephalon base and where the arachnoid membrane crosses.
label: Crural Cistern

description: A space or aperture defined by the free edges of the tentorium cerebelli through which the brainstem passes.
label: Posterior Supratentorial Cistern

description: A subarachnoid cistern located between the splenium of the corpus collosum and the superior surface of the cerebellum, lying posterior to the brain stem and third ventricle. The great cerebral vein traverses it and the pineal gland protrudes into it.
label: Quadrigeminal Cistern

description: A supratentorial cistern of the brain that is located inferior to the splenium of the corpus collosum, between the thalamus and the fornix.
label: Velum Interpositum Cistern

description: A discrete space situated dorsal to the midbrain where the arachnoid mater and pia mater are separated, and through which a number of important vascular structures pass, including the great cerebral vein, the basal vein of Rosenthal, and the posterior cerebral artery.
label: Superior Supratentorial Cistern

description: The cavity surrounding the white matter structure within the cleft that separates the left and right cerebral hemispheres.
label: Corpus Callosum Cistern

description: A dural partition that separates the occipital lobes of the cerebrum from the cerebellum and divides the cranial cavity into supratentorial and infratentorial compartments; it helps to stabilize the brain within the cranial cavity.
label: Tentorium Cerebelli

description: Any component of the nervous system that is external to the brain and spinal cord.
label: Peripheral Nervous System Part

description: Free nerve endings are widely distributed throughout the body, and are found as branches of unmyelinated, or lightly myelinated fibres grouped in bundles beneath the epithelium. As they penetrate the epithelium, they lose their myelin, and branch among the epithelial cells. Branches of one nerve may cover a wide area and overlap the territories of other nerves. The free nerve endings detect pain, touch, pressure and temperature, and are associated with C fibres.
label: Free Nerve Ending

description: The part of the nervous system of vertebrates that controls involuntary actions of the smooth muscles and heart and glands.
label: Autonomic Nervous System

description: A cluster of nervous tissue principally composed of neuronal cell bodies external to the central nervous system (CNS).
label: Ganglion

description: Ganglion with sensory function within the vertebral column.
label: Dorsal Root Ganglion

description: A cluster of nerve cell bodies in the peripheral nervous system, which consists of large, multipolar, motor neurons. There are two types of autonomic ganglia: sympathetic ganglia lie close to the CNS in sympathetic chain, or in clusters called prevertebral ganglia, and parasympathetic ganglia occur farther from CNS, often in target organs.
label: Autonomic Ganglion

description: A cluster of nerve cell bodies located within one of two paravertebral columns comprised of bundled nerve fibers that extend from the base of the skull to the first coccygeal vertebrae, or in a subsidiary location within the sympathetic nervous system. Sympathetic ganglia play a major role in the fight or flight and other stress-mediated responses.
label: Sympathetic Ganglion

description: Any of the 11 or 12 pairs of paravertebral ganglia in the thoracic portion of the sympathetic trunk that house the nerve cell bodies for postganglionic sympathetic nerve fibers.
label: Thoracic Ganglion

description: Sympathetic ganglion that innervates most of the gastrointestinal tract.  It is located in the upper abdomen.
label: Celiac Ganglion

description: A sympathetic ganglion located at the seventh cervical vertebral level.
label: Inferior Cervical Ganglion

description: A sympathetic ganglion located at the sixth cervical vertebral level.
label: Middle Cervical Ganglion

description: A sympathetic ganglion located approximately at the first and second cervical vertebral levels.
label: Superior Cervical Ganglion

description: A sympathetic ganglion located adjacent to the spinal column.
label: Para-Spinal Ganglion

description: A usually small autonomic ganglion of the parasympathetic nervous system. The majority are located near or in the organs that they innervate.
label: Parasympathetic Ganglion

description: A cluster of nerve cell bodies that transmit sensory impulses and are located on either the dorsal root of a spinal nerve or on certain cranial nerves.
label: Sensory Ganglion

description: A cluster of cranial nerve VII cell bodies located within the petrous temporal bone at the facial genu; it contains sensory nerve cell bodies for taste (from chorda tympani) and external ear sensation (from sensory auricular branch).
label: Geniculate Ganglion

description: A cluster of nervous tissue principally composed of neuronal cell bodies within the modiolus of the cochlea.
label: Spiral Ganglion

description: The collection of afferent neurons that serve to connect the hair cells of the vestibular sensory end organs with the brain.
label: Vestibular Ganglion

description: Large sensory ganglion of the trigeminal nerve that lies adjacent to the cavernous sinus in the trigeminal cavity of the dura mater.
label: Trigeminal Ganglion

description: Any of the sympathetic ganglion of the lumbar vertebrae.
label: Lumbar Ganglion

description: Any of the sympathetic ganglia associated with the mesenteric plexus.
label: Mesenteric Ganglion

description: Either of the two types of ganglia found in the lining of the GI tract: the Myenteric (Auerbach's) plexus and the submucosal (Meissner) plexus, which are both small ganglia connected by thin, unmyelinated nerves.
label: Enteric Ganglion

description: A peripheral parasympathetic ganglion that is located anterior to the submandibular gland on the superior portion of the hypoglossus. Its postganglionic fibers supply the sublingual and submandibular glands, and its preganglionic fibers originate from the salivary nucleus.
label: Submandibular Ganglion

description: Any one of the three sympathetic ganglia of the cervical vertebrae.
label: Cervical Ganglia

description: A network of intersecting nerve fibers that link peripheral nerves with specific areas of the body.
label: Nerve Plexus

description: A small, autonomic nerve plexus located in the head that arises from the internal carotid plexus and penetrates the orbit along the ophthalmic artery.
label: Ophthalmic Plexus

description: Any one of the four networks of intersecting nerves originating from the spinal cord, which transmit motor, sensory, and autonomic signals between the spinal cord and the body.
label: Spinal Nerve Plexus

description: A nerve network originating from C5 to T1 that supplies cutaneous and muscular innervation to the arm and hand.
label: Brachial Plexus

description: A network of nerves lying within the substance of the psoas muscle that is formed by the ventral rami of L1-L4, and which provides motor and sensory contributions to the anterior and medial compartments of the leg, abdominal wall, and pelvic areas.
label: Lumbar Plexus

description: A network of nerve fibers that are derived from the anterior rami of spinal nerves L4-L5 and S1-S4, and which are part of the larger lumbosacral plexus, providing motor and sensory innervation for the posterior thigh, most of the lower leg, the entire foot, and part of the pelvis.
label: Sacral Plexus

description: A network of nerves composed of the lumbar plexus (T12-L4) and the sacral plexus (L4-S4), which innervates the pelvic girdle and the lower limb.
label: Lumbosacral Plexus

description: A series of autonomic nerves around the internal carotid artery.
label: Internal Carotid Nerve Plexus

description: A network of intersecting nerves that is derived from the superior myenteric plexus; it is located in the submucosa of the intestinal wall, and functions to both regulate gastrointestinal blood flow and control epithelial cell function.
label: Submucous Nerve Plexus

description: A network of nerves and part of the enteric nervous system located between the layers of the muscularis externa in the gastrointestinal tract that functions to regulate motility
label: Myenteric Nerve Plexus

description: Either of two (inferior or superior) hypogastric nerve plexi in the lower abdomen.
label: Hypogastric Nerve Plexus

description: A series of nerves within the pelvis formed mostly by the extension of the hypogastric plexus and branches from the second, third and fourth sacral nerves. In males the inferior hypogastric nerve plexus is located on the sides of the rectum and in the female it is located on both the rectum and vagina.
label: Inferior Hypogastric Nerve Plexus

description: A network of nerves that arises from the superior cardiac branch of the sympathetic trunk and lower superior cervical branch of the vagus which innervates the aortic arch, coronary vessels, pulmonary artery, and the heart.
label: Cardiac Nerve Plexus

description: The route in which a nerve impulse travels through a series of linked axons to connect different regions within the central nervous system or to convey information from the peripheral nervous system to the brain.
label: Neural Pathway

description: A complex tract of nerve fibers that connects the basal telencephalon, the hypothalamus, and the midbrain reticular formation. The medial forebrain bundle contains fibers involved in the reward pathway of the brain.
label: Medial Forebrain Bundle

description: The route of neural fibers originating in the entorhinal cortex that project through the hippocampal formation to granule cells of the dentate gyrus, providing the major input to the hippocampus.
label: Perforant Pathway

description: A sensory pathway that conducts impulses toward the central nervous system.
label: Afferent Pathway

description: A sensory pathway that conducts impulses away from the central nervous system.
label: Efferent Pathway

description: A set of neural connections within the central nervous system, beginning with the retina and terminating in the occipital cortex, that provides the ability to process visual images.
label: Visual Pathway

description: The Golgi Tendon Organ is located within the tendons found on each end of a muscle. It responds to increased muscle tension or contraction as exerted on the tendon, by inhibiting further muscle contraction, which protects against muscle damage. The proprioceptive sensory neuron of a Golgi tendon organ, projects to the motor neurons located within the ventral horn of the spinal cord, where the inhibition occurs. Unlike the muscle spindle, Golgi tendon organs do not indicate muscle length, but rather muscle tension.
label: Golgi Tendon Organ

description: The division of the peripheral nervous system that comprises the afferent loop of the somatic nervous system, which functions to relay somatosensory perception, including touch, heat, and cold to the spinal cord and CNS.
label: Sensory-Somatic Nervous System

description: An efferent neuron that sends impulses from the central nervous system to skeletal muscles.
label: Motor Neuron

description: A motor neuron that is located in one of the ventral horns of the spinal cord and innervates skeletal muscles of the trunk or head.
label: Anterior Horn Cell

description: A type of motor neuron, found in the ventral horn of the spinal cord, that innervates intrafusal muscle fibers of neuromuscular spindles to help regulate skeletal muscle tone.
label: Gamma Motor Neuron

description: Nerve endings encased in connective tissue capsules with myelinated or unmyelinated axons.
label: Somatosensory Receptor

description: A free nerve ending that is a receptor for painful stimuli. (Kanner)
label: Nociceptor

description: A type of somatosensory receptor that detects the mechanical displacement of nerve endings and mediates touch, pressure, vibration, proprioception, and kinesthesia.
label: Mechanoreceptor

description: A specialized bulblike nerve ending located in the subcutaneous tissue of the skin; occurs abundantly in the skin of palms and soles and joints and genitals.
label: Vater-Pacini Corpuscle

description: A specialized tactile sensory nerve ending in the epidermis, characterized by a terminal cuplike expansion of an intraepidermal axon in contact with the base of a single modified keratinocyte. SYN meniscus tactus, Merkel's corpuscle, Merkel's tactile cell, Merkel's tactile disk, tactile disk.
label: Merkel's Corpuscle

description: Mechanoreceptors located in subcutaneous tissue, which are enlarged dendritic endings with elongated capsules, and which respond to sustained pressure.
label: Ruffini Corpuscle

description: One of numerous oval bodies found in the papillae of the skin, especially those of the fingers and toes; they consist of a connective tissue capsule in which the axon fibrils terminate around and between a pile of wedge-shaped epithelioid cells. SYN corpusculum tactus, oval corpuscle, touch corpuscle.
label: Meissner Corpuscle

description: A type of somatosensory receptor located mostly in the skin that detects changes in temperature; there are two classes of thermoreceptors: cold receptors and warm receptors.
label: Thermoreceptor

description: A primary sensory neuron that acts as a receptor of the somatic afferent component of the nervous system. It is stimulated by the contraction of muscles, movements of joints, and changes in body position.
label: Proprioceptor

description: Any component of the sympathetic or parasympathetic nervous system.
label: Autonomic Nervous System Part

description: The division of the autonomic nervous system responsible for conserving and restoring energy (opposing the sympathetic nervous system), which arises from preganglionic cell bodies in the gray matter of the brain stem and the middle three segments of the sacral cord.
label: Parasympathetic Nervous System

description: The part of the autonomic nervous system comprising paired, paraspinal sympathetic trunks together with their branches, plexi, and subsidiary ganglia; it functions to mobilize the body for activity and opposes the physiological effects of the parasympathetic nervous system.
label: Sympathetic Nervous System

description: Ganglionated nerve cords that extend on either side of the thoracic portion of the vertebral column comprising primarily ascending and descending preganglionic sympathetic fibers and visceral afferent fibers.
label: Thoracic Sympathetic Nerve Trunk

description: The inferior portion of the sympathetic trunk comprising four lumbar ganglia, connected by interganglionic cords.
label: Lumbar Sympathetic Nerve Trunk

description: One of the neural pathways that transmit impulses from the eyes to the cerebral cortex.
label: Anterior Visual Pathway

description: A cluster of neural crest cells that are located adjacent to the adrenal gland, nerves, and blood vessels.
label: Paraganglion

description: A cluster of chromaffin cells located adjacent to sympathetic ganglia.
label: Chromaffin Paraganglion

description: A projection of a neuron that conducts electrical impulses away from the neuronal cell body.
label: Axon

description: An axon that projects from a nerve cell body within the central nervous system and innervates a cell within an autonomic ganglia. Preganglionic sympathetic fibers use acetylcholine as transmitters, sometimes with peptide cotransmitters.
label: Preganglionic Autonomic Fiber

description: A nerve axon that is surrounded by a layer of myelin.
label: Myelinated Nerve Fiber

description: An axon that projects from a nerve cell body within an autonomic ganglion and innervates an effector cell within a target organ.
label: Postganglionic Autonomic Fiber

description: An axon that projects from a nerve cell body within a parasympathetic ganglion and innervates an effector cell within a target organ. Postganglionic parasympathetic fibers use acetylcholine as transmitters, sometimes with peptide cotransmitters.
label: Postganglionic Parasympathetic Fiber

description: An axon that projects from a nerve cell body within a sympathetic ganglion and innervates an effector cell within a target organ. Postganglionic sympathetic fibers use norepinephrine and acetylcholine as transmitters, sometimes with peptide cotransmitters.
label: Postganglionic Sympathetic Fiber

description: An axon that is not covered with a myelin sheath; this most commonly includes group C nerve fibers (postganglionic fibers in the autonomic nervous system and nerve fibers at the dorsal roots).
label: Unmyelinated Nerve Fiber

description: list()
label: Perikaryon

description: A long, branching outgrowth or extension from a neuron, that carries electrical signals from synapses to the cell body; any structure that resembles a dendrite.
label: Dendrite

description: A granular basophilic substance, which consists of granular endoplasmic reticulum and ribosomes, found in the cell bodies of neurons and dendrites.
label: Nissl Body

description: The gaps formed between myelin sheath segments along axons of certain neurons that serve to facilitate the rapid conduction of nerve impulses.
label: Node of Ranvier

description: Sensory receptors located in the olfactory epithelium in the nasal cavity that respond to airborne chemicals.
label: Olfactory Chemoreceptor

description: The initial segment of a nerve after it has branched off from the central nervous system.
label: Nerve Root

description: Either of the two initial segments of a spinal nerve, the dorsal sensory nerve root or the ventral motor nerve root; once emerged, the two fuse to form a single spinal nerve.
label: Spinal Nerve Root

description: The collection of spinal nerve roots, arising from lumbar pairs two through five, sacral pairs one through five, and the coccygeal nerve, that branch off the conus medularis at the termination of the spinal cord, and float freely within the lumbar cistern before exiting the spinal column at the appropriate vertebra.
label: Cauda Equina

description: The initial segment of a nerve leaving the cervical spine. There are eight pairs of cervical roots, each consisting of two parts: the ventral (efferent motor) and the dorsal (afferent sensory) root which unite to form a single spinal nerve. All cervical nerves exit superiorly to their corresponding vertebrae with the exception of C8, which exits inferiorly to the C7 vertebra.
label: Cervical Spinal Nerve Root

description: The initial portion of a lumbar spinal nerve, formed by the union of a dorsal sensory root and ventral motor root, as it originates from the spinal cord; there are five lumbar nerve roots on each side of the vertebral column, which exit the column inferior to their corresponding vertebral body level.
label: Lumbar Spinal Nerve Root

description: The initial portion of any one of the five paired sacral nerves, which is formed by the union of a dorsal sensory root and ventral motor root; collectively, these roots are called the cauda equina.
label: Sacral Spinal Nerve Root

description: The initial portion of any one of the twelve-paired thoracic nerves, formed by the union of a dorsal sensory root and ventral motor root, as it exits from the spinal cord.
label: Thoracic Spinal Nerve Root

description: The location of the spinal cord where afferent sensory fibers enter the cord, and which, when joined with a ventral root forms a spinal nerve.
label: Dorsal Root of the Spinal Nerve

description: The area of mucosa in the nose lined by olfactory epithelium and containing olfactory glands.
label: Olfactory Region

description: The superior opening of the thorax whose margin comprises the upper border of the first thoracic vertebra, the first ribs, and the manubrium.
label: Superior Thoracic Aperture

description: The part of the pelvic wall that is formed by the piriformis and obturator internus muscles and contains the iliac vessels, pelvic ureters, and lateral pelvic lymph nodes.
label: Pelvic Sidewall

description: A term that refers to individual anatomic parts of the heart or the vessels.
label: Cardiovascular System Part

description: The opening of the right coronary artery at its origin.
label: Right Coronary Artery Ostium

description: The opening of the left coronary artery at its origin.
label: Left Main Coronary Artery Ostium

description: The opening of the left anterior descending coronary artery at its origin.
label: Left Anterior Descending Artery Ostium

description: The opening of the left circumflex artery at its origin.
label: Left Circumflex Artery Ostium

description: A tiny vessel that can be either a blood capillary or a lymphatic capillary.
label: Capillary

description: Tiny blood vessels that connect the arterioles with the venules.
label: Blood Capillary

description: A type of capillary that is characterized by the presence of an uninterrupted endothelium and a continuous basal lamina, and which is most commonly found in skeletal muscle, skin, and the central nervous system.
label: Continuous Capillary

description: Tiny blood vessels located within Bowman's capsule, which combine in networks to form a glomerulus.
label: Glomerular Capillary

description: A type of capillary that is characterized by the presence of circular pores that penetrate the endothelium covered with a continuous basal lamina, and is most commonly found in the intestinal mucosa, renal glomeruli, pancreas, and endocrine glands.
label: Fenestrated Capillary

description: Narrow blood vessels found in the liver, spleen and bone marrow with gaps rather than tight junctions between endothelial cells creating a highly permeable surface.
label: Discontinuous Capillary

description: Tiny vessels with porous walls that join to form the lymphatic vessels.
label: Lymphatic Capillary

description: A tubular structure through which the blood circulates in the body. Blood vessels constitute a network composed of arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins.
label: Blood Vessel

description: Any of the major arteries or veins attached to the cardiac atria or ventricles. This includes the aorta, superior and inferior vena cava and the pulmonary arteries and veins.
label: Great Blood Vessel

description: A segment of a blood vessel that is part of the arterial system.
label: Arterial Segment

description: The segment of the arterial system that includes the popliteal artery and its origin from the femoral artery.
label: Femoropopliteal Artery Segment

description: The blood vessel segment that includes the crural artery and the tibial artery.
label: Tibialcrural Artery

description: The segment of the left main coronary artery that is bounded by its ostium and bifurcation.
label: Left Main Coronary Artery Body

description: The portion of the distal end of the left main coronary artery that branches into the left anterior descending artery and the left circumflex artery.
label: Left Main Coronary Artery Bifurcation

description: An arterial trunk that contains parts of the posterior tibial artery and fibular artery.
label: Tibioperoneal Arterial Trunk

description: A segment of a carotid artery.
label: Carotid Artery Segment

description: An artery arising from the right ventricle of the heart that bifurcates into the left and right pulmonary arteries.
label: Pulmonary Trunk

description: The major arterial trunk that carries oxygenated blood from the left ventricle into the ascending aorta behind the heart, the aortic arch, through the thorax as the descending aorta and through the abdomen as the abdominal aorta; it bifurcates into the left and right common iliac arteries.
label: Aorta

description: A blood vessel that carries blood away from the heart.
label: Artery

description: The first posterolateral branch originating from the posterior atrioventricular left circumflex artery in left dominant and mixed circulations.
label: Left Atrioventricular Artery

description: A terminal branch of the brachial artery arising just below the elbow that runs along the ulna into the wrist with numerous branches supplying the forearm, wrist and hand.
label: Ulnar Artery

description: Either one of two arteries arising from the pulmonary trunk that carry deoxygenated blood to the lungs.
label: Pulmonary Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the bifurcation of the pulmonary artery that carries deoxygenated blood to the left lung.
label: Left Pulmonary Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the bifurcation of the pulmonary artery that carries deoxygenated blood to the right lung.
label: Right Pulmonary Artery

description: An artery originating at the axillary artery and branching into the radial and ulnar arteries.
label: Brachial Artery

description: One of two arteries that supply oxygenated blood to the head and neck; the left common carotid branches from the aorta and the right common carotid from the innominate (brachiocephalic artery).
label: Common Carotid Artery

description: An artery arising from the aortic arch that supplies the head and neck.
label: Left Common Carotid Artery

description: An artery arising from the bifurcation of the brachiocephalic artery that supplies the head and neck.
label: Right Common Carotid Artery

description: An artery that starts within the inguinal region and extends to the lower extremities.
label: Femoral Artery

description: A terminal branch of the popliteal artery that runs along the tibia from the lower portion of the popliteus muscle to the lower ankle with numerous branches supplying the lower leg and foot.
label: Posterior Tibial Artery

description: One of two arteries that arise from the aortic sinuses of the ascending aorta and supply blood to the myocardium
label: Coronary Artery

description: The section of the right coronary artery between the right ventricular artery and the acute marginal artery.
label: Mid-Right Coronary Artery Conduit

description: The section of the right coronary artery proximal to the origin of the right ventricular artery.
label: Proximal Right Coronary Artery Conduit

description: The right coronary artery and all of its branches, including the right posterior descending, right posterolateral and acute marginal branches.
label: Right Coronary Artery and its Branches

description: The arterial branch between the right posterior descending artery segment and the first right posterolateral segment.
label: Right Posterior Atrioventricular Artery

description: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, the arterial branch that arises from the distal right coronary artery between the acute marginal artery and the first right posterolateral segment. It supplies the inferior apex of the heart.
label: Right Posterior Descending Artery

description: The second artery arising from the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that supplies the anterolateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.
label: Second Diagonal Branch Artery

description: In an individual with a left-dominant heart, this is the second branch that arises from the circumflex artery atrioventricular groove continuation when counted from proximal to distal. It supplies the posterolateral wall.
label: Second Left Posterolateral Branch Artery

description: The second artery arising from the left circumflex artery that supplies the lateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.
label: Second Obtuse Marginal Branch Artery

description: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, this is the second branch that arises from the right coronary artery distal to the right posterior descending artery, when counted from proximal to distal.
label: Second Right Posterolateral Artery

description: The third artery arising from the left circumflex artery that supplies the lateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.
label: Third Obtuse Marginal Branch Artery

description: In an individual with a left-dominant heart, this is the third branch that arises from the circumflex artery atrioventricular groove continuation when counted from proximal to distal. It supplies the posterolateral wall.
label: Third Posterolateral Descending Artery

description: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, this is the third branch that arises from the right coronary artery distal to the right posterior descending artery, when counted from proximal to distal.
label: Third Right Posterolateral Artery

description: The arteries that arise at the junction of the proximal and mid-right coronary artery conduit segments.
label: Acute Marginal Artery

description: The section of the right coronary artery distal to the origin of the acute marginal artery.
label: Distal Right Coronary Artery Conduit

description: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, this is the first branch that arises from the right coronary artery distal to the right posterior descending artery, when counted from proximal to distal.
label: First Right Posterolateral Artery

description: A coronary artery that arises from the aorta and bifurcates into the left anterior descending artery and the left circumflex artery.
label: Left Coronary Artery

description: In an individual with a right-dominant heart, the arterial branch that arises from the distal right coronary artery in the posterior atrioventricular groove after the origin of the right posterior descending artery.
label: Posterolateral Coronary Artery

description: The second posterolateral branch originating from the posterior atrioventricular left circumflex artery in left dominant and mixed circulations.
label: Left Posterior Descending Artery

description: A coronary artery that originates above the right coronary cusp and supplies blood predominantly to the right side of the heart.
label: Right Coronary Artery

description: The branch of the right coronary artery that supplies blood to the right ventricular wall.
label: Right Ventricular Branch of Right Coronary Artery

description: Any artery arising from the left coronary artery.
label: Left Coronary Artery Branch

description: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the second obtuse marginal artery.
label: Lateral Second Obtuse Marginal Branch Artery

description: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the third diagonal artery.
label: Lateral Third Diagonal Branch Artery

description: The arteries that arise from the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that supply the interventricular septum.
label: Left Anterior Descending Septal Perforator Artery

description: In an individual with a left-dominant heart, this branch arises from the circumflex artery atrioventricular groove continuation and supplies the inferior apex of the heart.
label: Left Posterolateral Descending Artery

description: The segment of the left circumflex artery between the first and second marginal branches.
label: Mid-Circumflex Artery

description: All of the arterial branches distal to the proximal left anterior descending coronary artery.
label: Mid-Distal Left Anterior Descending Coronary Artery and All Diagonal Coronary Branches

description: The segment of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery between the first and third diagonal branches.
label: Mid-Left Anterior Descending Artery

description: The section of the left circumflex coronary artery that arises from the left main coronary artery and extends to the first marginal branch.
label: Proximal Circumflex Artery

description: The section of the left anterior descending coronary artery that arises from the left main coronary artery and extends to the first diagonal branch.
label: Proximal Left Anterior Descending Artery

description: An artery that arises from the left main coronary artery and is positioned between the left anterior descending coronary artery and the circumflex artery.
label: Ramus Intermedius Artery

description: The arteries arising from the right posterior descending artery that supply the interventricular septum.
label: Septal Perforator Artery

description: The third artery arising from the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that supplies the anterolateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.
label: Third Diagonal Branch Artery

description: The left circumflex coronary artery and all of its branches, including the obtuse marginals, left posterolateral and left posterior descending artery branches.
label: Circumflex Artery and its Branches

description: The segment of the left circumflex artery that is distal to the third marginal branch, located in the atrioventricular groove.
label: Circumflex Artery AV Groove Continuation Artery

description: The segment of the left circumflex artery that is between the second and third obtuse marginal branches.
label: Distal Circumflex Artery

description: The segment of the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that is distal to the third diagonal branch.
label: Distal Left Anterior Descending Artery

description: The first artery arising from the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that supplies the anterolateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.
label: First Diagonal Branch Artery

description: In an individual with a left-dominant heart, this is the first branch that arises from the circumflex artery atrioventricular groove continuation when counted from proximal to distal. It supplies the posterolateral wall.
label: First Left Posterolateral Branch Artery

description: The first artery arising from the left circumflex artery that supplies the lateral wall, when counted from proximal to distal.
label: First Obtuse Marginal Branch Artery

description: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the first diagonal artery.
label: Lateral First Diagonal Branch Artery

description: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the first obtuse marginal artery.
label: Lateral First Obtuse Marginal Branch Artery

description: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the ramus intermedius artery.
label: Lateral Ramus Intermedius Artery

description: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the second diagonal artery.
label: Lateral Second Diagonal Branch Artery

description: The lateral branch distal to a bifurcation of the third obtuse marginal artery.
label: Lateral Third Obtuse Marginal Branch Artery

description: An artery arising from the bifurcation of the left coronary artery that runs along the coronary grove with branches supplying the atria and ventricles.
label: Circumflex Branch of the Left Coronary Artery

description: A left coronary artery branch that descends on the anterior portion of the heart through the anterior interventricular groove.
label: Anterior Descending Coronary Artery

description: One of the arteries arising from the left anterior descending (LAD) artery that supply the anterolateral wall.
label: Diagonal Branch of the Anterior Descending Artery

description: Any of the tibial arteries including the anterior and posterior tibial arteries and the anterior and posterior recurrent tibial arteries.
label: Tibial Artery

description: An artery of the lower extremity that supplies blood to the anterior part of the leg and the foot.
label: Anterior Tibial Artery

description: The branch of the brachial artery that passes down the forearm.
label: Radial Artery

description: An artery arising from the brachial artery just below the bend of the elbow with numerous branches in the forearm, wrist and hand.
label: Radial Artery of the Upper Extremity

description: Arteries that arises from the arcuate arteries in the myometrium and supply small straight arteries to the basal layer of the endometrium and spiral arteries to the functional zone of the endometrium.
label: Radial Artery of the Endometrium

description: Arteries which have their origins within the intracranial cavity.
label: Intracranial Artery

description: An artery which directly supplies the cerebral cortex and which has deeper branches that supply the underlying white matter.
label: Cerebral Artery

description: An artery, which originates in either the internal carotid artery or the middle cerebral artery, that delivers blood to the choroid plexus.
label: Anterior Choroidal Artery

description: Any of the arteries that are part of the intracranial posterior circulation.
label: Posterior Circulation Intracranial Artery

description: An artery formed by the union of the two vertebral arteries at the posterior border of the pons then diverges at the anterior border forming the two superior and two posterior cerebral arteries.
label: Basilar Artery

description: The first branch of the subclavian artery that ascends both sides of the neck and merges at the middle line to from the basilar artery at the level of the pons.
label: Vertebral Artery

description: Any artery arising from the basilar artery.
label: Basilar Artery Branch

description: The posterior cerebral artery is formed by the bifurcation of the basilar artery; it divides into three branches.
label: Posterior Cerebral Artery

description: A basilar artery branch that supplies the anterior portion of the inferior surface of the cerebellum.
label: Anterior Inferior Cerebellar Artery

description: A blood vessel branching from the basilar artery that runs along the auditory nerve to supply the inner ear.
label: Internal Auditory Artery

description: A series of small arteries that arise from either side of the basilar artery to supply the pons.
label: Pontine Branch

description: Any artery arising from the posterior cerebral artery.
label: Posterior Cerebral Artery Branch

description: An artery that branches from the medial occipital artery that aligns with the calcarine sulcus.
label: Calcarine Artery

description: Either of two arteries (medial or lateral) that arise from the posterior cerebral artery to supply the choroidal plexus and brainstem.
label: Posterior Choroidal Artery

description: An artery that arises from the posterior cerebral artery and supplies the mid brain.
label: Mesencephalic Perforating Artery

description: An artery arising from the pericallosal artery that extends along the parieto-occipital sulcus to supply the medial and superolateral surfaces of the parietal lobe and sometimes the occipital lobe.
label: Parieto-Occipital Artery

description: An artery arising from the P1 segment of the posterior cerebral artery that runs along the quadrigeminal sulcus with branches supplying the superior and inferior colliculus.
label: Quadrigeminal Artery

description: An artery arising from the parieto-occipital artery that supplies the splenium, the posterior portion of the corpus callosum.
label: Splenial Artery

description: The arteries arising from the basilar artery that supply the upper surface of the cerebellum, pia mater, pineal gland, valve of Vieussens and velum interpositum.
label: Superior Cerebellar Artery

description: Any artery arising from the vertebral artery.
label: Vertebral Artery Branch

description: An artery arising from the vertebral artery at the level of the medulla oblongata that descends along the posterior roots of the spinal nerves on each side of the spinal cord with branches supplying the spinal cord, pia mater and medulla.
label: Posterior Spinal Artery

description: A terminal branch arising from the bifurcation of the posterior inferior cerebellar artery that supplies the biventral and inferior semilunar lobes, the tonsil, and sometimes part of the superior semilunar lobe.
label: Tonsillohemispheric Artery

description: One of two arteries (anterior and posterior choroidal artery) that supply blood to the choroid plexus, optic tract, hippocampus, globus pallidus, and other various brain regions.
label: Choroidal Artery

description: A blood vessel that is the terminal branch of the posterior inferior cerebellar artery supplying the inferior vermis.
label: Inferior Vermian Artery

description: A radicular artery extending along the dorsal or ventral root of the cervical ganglia that penetrates the vertebral bone to supply the spinal canal.
label: Medullary Artery

description: An artery arising from the vertebral artery that supplies the cerebellum, choroid plexus and the lateral medulla.
label: Posterior Inferior Cerebellar Artery

description: The small arteries arising from the pharyngeal artery that supply the dura mater and the posterior cranial fossa.
label: Posterior Meningeal Artery

description: An artery that originates from the basilar artery and distributes blood to the cerebellum.
label: Cerebellar Artery

description: An artery that branches from the axillary artery or one of its branches, and which supplies the muscles and organs of the thorax.
label: Thoracic Artery

description: An artery that arises most often as a branch of the anterior division of the internal iliac artery; it continues medially in the pelvis within the base of the broad ligament, to the exterior surface of the uterus where it branches into the descending, transverse, and ascending divisions, which further branch into the following: the helicine branches that supply the uterus; the vaginal branch, which anastomoses with the vaginal artery to supply vagina; the ovarian branch, which anastomoses with ovarian artery to supply the ovaries; and the tubal branch that supplies the fallopian tubes.
label: Uterine Artery

description: A small artery located in the abdomen that arises from the common, left, or right hepatic artery, and supplies blood to the pylorus of the stomach, the proximal duodenum, and the head of the pancreas.
label: Gastroduodenal Artery

description: Any of the arteries that supply blood to the penis, including the common penile artery, and the bulbourethral, dorsal, and cavernosal branches of the common penile artery.
label: Penile Artery

description: A type of artery that supplies blood to the fingers and toes. In the hand, the digital arteries include the common palmar digital arteries that arise from the superficial palmar arch, the proper palmar digital arteries that are branches of the common palmar digital arteries and occasionally have dorsal branches distal to the proximal interphalangeal joints, and the dorsal digital arteries that are branches of the dorsal metacarpal arteries. In the foot, the digital arteries include the plantar digital arteries that arise from the plantar arch and the dorsal digital arteries that are branches of the dorsal metatarsal arteries.
label: Digital Artery

description: A type of artery that supplies blood to the fingers and includes the common palmar digital arteries, the dorsal digital arteries of the hand, and the proper palmar digital arteries.
label: Palmar Digital Artery

description: Three arteries arising from the superficial palmar arch which run distally on the second, third and fourth lumbricals muscles to the interdigital clefts where each artery then separates into two proper palmar digital arteries.
label: Common Palmar Digital Artery

description: An artery that supplies blood to the index finger, either the radial artery of the index finger or the ulnar proper digital artery.
label: Hand Digit 2 Artery

description: An artery that supplies blood to the little finger, either the ulnar or radial proper digital artery.
label: Hand Digit 5 Artery

description: An artery that supplies blood to the middle finger, either the ulnar or radial proper digital artery.
label: Hand Digit 3 Artery

description: An artery that supplies blood to the ring finger, either the ulnar or radial proper digital artery.
label: Hand Digit 4 Artery

description: An artery that supplies blood to the thumb; either the ulnopalmar, radiopalmar, ulnodorsal, or radiodorsal digital artery to the thumb, or the princeps pollicis artery.
label: Hand Digit 1 Artery

description: A small artery that originates from the radial artery and supplies the basal layer of the endometrium.
label: Straight Artery of the Endometrium

description: An arterial segment arising from the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to the abdominal organs, other structures, genitalia and the lower limbs. The aortic branches include terminal branches called the common iliac arteries, the celiac artery, the superior mesenteric artery, the inferior mesenteric artery, the renal arteries, the suprarenal arteries, the testicular (internal spermatic) arteries, the ovarian arteries, the inferior phrenic arteries, lumbar arteries and the middle sacral artery.
label: Abdominal Aorta Branch

description: A branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to the lower trunk and the legs.
label: Iliac Artery

description: An artery arising from the bifurcation of the abdominal aorta which then bifurcates forming the internal and external iliac arteries.
label: Common Iliac Artery

description: The common iliac artery situated on the left side of the body.
label: Left Common Iliac Artery

description: The common iliac artery situated on the right side of the body.
label: Right Common Iliac Artery

description: Either of two arteries (right or left) that arise from the aorta to supply the kidneys.
label: Renal Artery

description: An additional renal artery originating from the aorta. Accessory renal arteries are found in 26-30% of humans.
label: Accessory Renal Artery

description: An artery arising from the aorta that supplies the right kidney.
label: Right Renal Artery

description: An artery arising from the abdominal aorta that supplies the left kidney.
label: Left Renal Artery

description: Either of two arteries (left gastric and right gastric) that supply blood to the stomach and lesser curvature.
label: Gastric Artery

description: An artery arising from the celiac trunk that supplies portions of the stomach, small intestines, liver and gallbladder. It branches off to form the right gastric artery and the gastroduodenal artery and continues distally as the proper hepatic artery, whose branches give rise to the cystic artery, and the left and right hepatic arteries.
label: Common Hepatic Artery

description: Any of the four or five pairs of arteries arising from the left or right side of the aorta in the lumbar region.
label: Lumbar Artery

description: Either of two arteries (left or right) that have a high degree of variability in their origin from the aorta and that give rise to numerous branches.
label: Phrenic Artery

description: Either of two arteries (right or left) that arise from the aorta to supply the corresponding ovary, ovarian ligament, uterine tube and ureter.
label: Ovarian Artery

description: An artery located in the abdomen that provides blood to the adrenal glands.
label: Suprarenal Artery

description: Either of two arteries (left and right) arising from the inferior phrenic artery that supply the corresponding adrenal gland.
label: Superior Suprarenal Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the renal artery that supplies blood to the suprarenal gland and ureter.
label: Inferior Suprarenal Artery

description: A branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies oxygenated blood to the testis.
label: Spermatic Artery

description: An artery arising from the abdominal aorta, below the renal artery, that supplies the right testicle.
label: Right Spermatic Artery

description: An artery arising from the abdominal aorta, below the renal artery, that supplies the left testicle.
label: Left Spermatic Artery

description: An artery arising from the celiac trunk with four main branches that supply the spleen, stomach and pancreas.
label: Splenic Artery
