description: A major abdominal artery that arises from the abdominal aorta below the diaphragm.  It supplies blood to the digestive organs. It has three major branches, left gastric artery, common hepatic artery, and splenic artery.
label: Celiac Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the internal iliac artery that supplies blood to the pelvic muscles and bones.
label: Iliolumbar Artery

description: A branch of the abdominal aorta that supplies blood to the intestines.
label: Mesenteric Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the aorta that supplies blood to the descending and sigmoid colon as well as the rectum.
label: Inferior Mesenteric Artery

description: An artery arising from the abdominal aorta with numerous branches that supply the intestines from the duodenum to the transverse colon and the pancreas.
label: Superior Mesenteric Artery

description: An artery that originates from the subclavian artery at the lateral margin of the first rib that supplies the brachial artery.
label: Axillary Artery

description: Any artery arising from the axillary artery.
label: Axillary Artery Branch

description: An axillary artery branch that divides in four branches (pectoral, acromial, clavicular, and deltoid branch) supplying the regions of the shoulder and upper chest.
label: Thoracoacromial Artery

description: An axillary artery branch with distribution to the humeral head and biceps muscle.
label: Anterior Circumflex Artery

description: An artery branching off of the axillary artery that supplies the shoulder joint and the teres minor and deltoid muscles.
label: Posterior Circumflex Artery

description: An artery arising from the axillary artery with branches that supply the shoulder and muscles of the scapular region.
label: Subscapular Artery

description: An artery arising from the axillary artery that supplies the muscles of the superior chest.
label: Superior Thoracic Artery

description: One of the arteries that deliver blood to the wrist. It arises from the radial artery and forms an anastomosis with the ulnar anterior carpal artery.
label: Anterior Carpal Artery

description: An anterior ethmoidal artery branch that supplies the meningeal tissues in the anterior fossa of the cranium.
label: Anterior Meningeal Artery

description: Any artery that takes its origin from the common carotid artery, most commonly the internal carotid artery and external carotid artery.
label: Common Carotid Artery Branch

description: An artery arising from the common carotid artery at the level of the upper border of the thyroid cartilage that ascends the neck forming eight different branches.
label: External Carotid Artery

description: An artery arising from the bifurcation of the common carotid artery on each side of the body at the level of the third or fourth cervical vertebrae that ascends the neck into the head with numerous branches supplying the anterior brain, eye, forehead and nose.
label: Internal Carotid Artery

description: The proximal portion of the femoral artery.
label: Common Femoral Artery Branch

description: An artery arising from the common femoral artery just below the inguinal ligament running close to the femur and ending in the lower third of the thigh with branches supplying the thigh muscles.
label: Deep Femoral Artery

description: Any artery arising from the brachial artery.
label: Brachial Artery Branch

description: A brachial artery branch with distribution to the muscles at the back of the elbow.
label: Anastomotica Magna Artery

description: A small blood vessel arising from the brachial artery in the lower portion of the upper arm that supplies blood to the head of the triceps muscle.
label: Inferior Profunda Artery

description: Any artery that supplies the inner cavity of a long bone.
label: Nutrient Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the brachial artery in the center of the upper arm that supplies blood to the triceps muscle and humerus.
label: Superior Profunda Artery

description: An arterial branch arising from the anterior tibial artery.
label: Anterior Tibial Artery Branch

description: An artery on the lateral side of the ankle arising from the anterior tibial artery.
label: External Malleolar Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the anterior tibial artery that runs along the medial side of the ankle to supply the ankle joint.
label: Internal Malleolar Artery

description: An artery originating from the aortic arch.
label: Aortic Arch Branch

description: An artery arising from the aortic arch that divides into the right common carotid and right subclavian arteries.
label: Innominate Artery

description: An artery arising from the aortic arch that supplies the left arm.
label: Left Subclavian Artery

description: An artery that can arise from the innominate (brachiocephalic) artery, aortic arch, internal mammary artery, right common carotid artery, or the subclavian artery to supply the lower portion of the thyroid gland.
label: Thyroid Ima Artery

description: Any artery arising from the common iliac artery.
label: Common Iliac Artery Branch

description: An artery arising from the bifurcation of the common iliac artery in the lower torso. The external iliac artery becomes the femoral artery and is the main blood supply for the leg.
label: External Iliac Artery

description: A short thick blood vessel arising from the bifurcation of the common iliac artery with numerous branches that supply the organs, walls and viscera of the pelvis as well as the inner thigh.
label: Internal Iliac Artery

description: Any artery arising from the external carotid artery.
label: External Carotid Artery Branch

description: An artery arising from the external carotid artery supplying blood to the surface of the face.
label: Facial Artery

description: An artery arising from the external carotid artery that branches into the auricular, arteria princeps cervicis, meningeal, muscular, and sterno-mastoid arteries.
label: Occipital Artery

description: A terminal branch of the external carotid artery that branches into the anterior and posterior temporal arteries.
label: Temporal Artery

description: An artery arising from the external carotid artery between the thyroid and facial arteries that runs under the tongue and becomes the deep lingual or ranine artery.
label: Lingual Artery

description: An artery that is the first branch of the external carotid artery that supplies the upper thyroid gland and its muscles and branches to form the crico-thyroid, hyoid, sterno-mastoid and superior laryngeal arteries.
label: Superior Thyroid Artery

description: Any artery arising from the external iliac artery.
label: External Iliac Artery Branch

description: An external iliac artery branch that supplies blood to the anterior abdominal wall.
label: Epigastric Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the external iliac artery with many smaller branches that connects to the superior epigastric artery and lower intercostal arteries.
label: Inferior Epigastric Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the external iliac artery with three branches, cremasteric, muscular and pubic, which supply oxygenated blood to the lower abdomen.
label: Deep Inferior Epigastric Artery

description: One of two (deep circumflex and superficial circumflex) iliac arteries that supply the lower abdomen, inguinal lymph nodes, sartorius, and tensor fasciae latae.
label: Circumflex Iliac Artery

description: A blood vessel that arises from the external iliac artery to supply the muscles and skin of the lower torso with oxygenated blood.
label: Deep Circumflex Iliac Artery

description: A small cutaneous artery arising from the femoral artery that divides at the ilium into two branches that supply the groin integument, superficial inguinal lymphatic glands and superficial fascia.
label: Superficial Circumflex Iliac Artery

description: An artery supplying blood to the bottom of the feet and toes that arises from the posterior tibial artery.
label: External Plantar Artery

description: Any artery arising from the deep femoral artery.
label: Deep Femoral Artery Branch

description: A blood vessel arising from the profunda artery supplying the muscles on the front of the thigh and divides into ascending, descending and transverse branches.
label: External Circumflex Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the profunda artery with one branch supplying the hip joint and two other branches supplying the adductor muscles in the upper inner thigh.
label: Internal Circumflex Artery

description: One of four arteries arising from the profunda femoris that pass through the adductor magnus muscle to supply the back of the thigh.
label: Perforating Artery of the Thigh

description: An artery arising from the profunda femoris artery with ascending and descending branches that supply the thigh muscles and hip joint.
label: Medial Circumflex Artery

description: Any artery arising from the femoral artery.
label: Femoral Artery Branch

description: An artery arising from the external iliac artery at the inguinal ligament which bifurcates forming the deep and superficial femoral arteries.
label: Common Femoral Artery

description: The portion of the femoral artery distal to the branching of the deep femoral artery that runs close to the skin.
label: Superficial Femoral Artery

description: One of two arteries (right common carotid and right subclavian) that branch off of the innominate artery.
label: Innominate Artery Branch

description: An artery arising from the bifurcation of the brachiocephalic artery that supplies the right arm and thoracic region.
label: Right Subclavian Artery

description: Either of three arteries (posterior or dorsal branch, collateral intercostal and spinal) that branch off of the intercostal artery.
label: Intercostal Artery Branch

description: A branch of the intercostal artery that supplies oxygenated blood to the spinal cord and the pia mater.
label: Spinal Artery

description: The artery that delivers blood to the anterior portion of the spinal cord.
label: Anterior Spinal Artery

description: An artery that supplies blood to the renal lobes.
label: Interlobular Artery

description: An artery of the dorsal surface of the foot, originating from the anterior tibial artery of the lower leg. The following arterial branches originate from the dorsalis pedis artery: the arcuate artery of the foot and deep plantar artery.
label: Dorsalis Pedis Artery

description: Any artery arising from the dorsalis pedis artery.
label: Dorsalis Pedis Artery Branch

description: Any of the four dorsal or four plantar arteries that arise from the dorsalis pedis artery that extend over the metatarsal bones.
label: Metatarsal Artery

description: Any of the four arteries that arise from the dorsalis pedis artery that extend on the underside of the metatarsal bones in the foot.
label: Plantar Metatarsal Artery

description: An artery arising from the dorsalis pedis artery at the navicular bone that supplies the articulations of the tarsus and the extensor brevis digitorum muscle.
label: Tarsal Artery

description: Any artery arising from the internal iliac artery.
label: Internal Iliac Artery Branch

description: An artery arising from the internal iliac artery that supplies the middle section of the rectum and anastomoses with the superior and inferior hemorrhoidal arteries.
label: Middle Hemorrhoidal Artery

description: Either of two (superior or inferior) arteries branching from the internal iliac artery in the hip joint and gluteal region.
label: Superior Gluteal Artery

description: An artery that supplies the external sex organs in both males and females.
label: Internal Pubic Artery

description: An artery arising from the anterior or posterior trunk of the internal iliac artery that supplies the ilium and pubic bones as well as the obturator and adductor muscles.
label: Obturator Artery

description: An artery that is one of the terminal branches of the internal iliac artery that also accompanies the sciatic nerve with numerous branches within and outside the pelvis.
label: Sciatic Artery

description: An artery that runs along the inside of the foot supplying those muscles as well as the toes.
label: Internal Plantar Artery

description: Either of three branches (colica sinistra, sigmoid artery, or superior hemorrhoidal artery) arising from the inferior mesenteric artery.
label: Inferior Mesenteric Artery Branch

description: The continuation of the inferior mesenteric artery with two branches that descend down either side of the rectum and anastomose with the middle and inferior hemorrhoidal arteries.
label: Superior Hemorrhoidal Artery

description: An artery arising from the inferior mesenteric artery with branches that supply the descending and sigmoid colon.
label: Sigmoid Artery

description: A continuation of the femoral artery that descends behind the knee joint before branching into the anterior and posterior tibial arteries.
label: Popliteal Artery

description: The segment of the popliteal artery that is located above the knee.
label: Popliteal Artery Above the Knee

description: The segment of the popliteal artery that is located below the knee.
label: Popliteal Artery Below the Knee

description: Any artery arising from the popliteal artery.
label: Popliteal Artery Branch

description: A small blood vessel branch arising opposite of the back of the knee joint from the popliteal artery and supplies the ligaments and synovial membrane in the interior of the articulation.
label: Azygos Articular Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the popliteal artery that supplies blood to the head of the fibula and the front of the knee joint.
label: Inferior External Articular Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the popliteal artery that supplies blood to the head of the tibia and the knee joint.
label: Inferior Internal Articular Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the popliteal artery that divides into deep and superficial branches. The deep branch supplies blood to the lower portion of the femur and knee joint while the superficial branch supplies the vastus externus.
label: Superior External Articular Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the popliteal artery that supplies blood to the hamstring muscles.
label: Superior Internal Articular Artery

description: One of four or five arteries within the calf muscle that arises from the popliteal artery.
label: Sural Artery

description: Any artery arising from the posterior tibial artery.
label: Posterior Tibial Artery Branch

description: One of many blood vessels arising from the posterior tibial artery supplying the fat and integument of the heel and Achilles tendon as well as the muscles on the inner side of the sole.
label: Internal Calcanean Artery

description: An artery arising from the posterior tibial artery that supplies the muscles on the lateral side of the lower leg.
label: Peroneal Artery

description: An artery located below the clavicle that supplies blood to the head and the arms. The right subclavian artery originates from the brachiocephalic artery and the left subclavian artery originates from the aortic arch.
label: Subclavian Artery

description: Any artery arising from the pulmonary artery.
label: Pulmonary Artery Branch

description: Any artery arising from the superior mesenteric artery.
label: Superior Mesenteric Artery Branch

description: A branch of the superior mesenteric artery that supplies blood to the terminal ileum and ascending colon.
label: Ileo-Colic Artery

description: Either of two arteries including the inferior and superior pancreatico-duodenal arteries that supply the pancreas and duodenum.
label: Pancreatico-Duodenal Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the superior mesenteric artery and connecting to the superior pancreatico-duodenal artery that supplies blood to the pancreas and duodenum.
label: Inferior Pancreatico-Duodenal Artery

description: An artery arising from the gastroduodenal artery that supplies the common bile duct, duodenum, and the head of the pancreas.
label: Superior Pancreatico-Duodenal Artery

description: Any artery arising from the ulnar artery.
label: Ulnar Artery Branch

description: An arched blood vessel arising from the terminal portion of the radial artery and the ulnar artery located on the bases of the metacarpal bones.
label: Deep Palmar Artery

description: Either of three arteries including the common interosseous artery which arises from the ulnar artery and bifurcates into the anterior and posterior interosseous arteries.
label: Interosseous Artery

description: Either of two arteries that arise from the ulnar artery or the radial artery that anastomose to form the posterior carpal arch of the hand.
label: Posterior Carpal Artery

description: An arterial anastomosis in the palm of the hand, located distal to the deep palmar arch, and fed mainly by the ulnar artery, providing the principal blood supply to the common and proper digital arteries.
label: Superficial Palmar Arch

description: An artery that originates from the radial artery and supplies the functional zone of the endometrium.
label: Spiral Artery of the Endometrium

description: Any artery arising from the thoracic aorta.
label: Thoracic Aorta Branch

description: Two series of blood vessels that supply the lungs with nutrients. The right side bronchial arteries arise from the first aortic intercostal while the left side arises from thoracic aorta.
label: Bronchial Artery

description: Any of several arteries that arise from the aorta and supply blood to the esophagus.
label: Esophageal Artery

description: The nine paired arteries arising from the aorta that supply the intercostal spaces (area between the ribs).
label: Intercostal Artery

description: The small arteries arising from the thoracic aorta that supply the pericardium.
label: Pericardiac Artery

description: The many arteries arising from the thoracic aorta that supply the lymph nodes and pleura of the posterior mediastinum.
label: Posterior Mediastinal Artery

description: An artery arising from the thoracic aorta that runs along the bottom of the twelfth rib.
label: Subcostal Artery

description: A terminal branch of the external carotid artery running from the ramus of the jaw to the pterygopalatine fossa with numerous branches supplying the deep structures of the face.
label: Maxillary Artery

description: An artery arising from the maxillary artery that supplies the deep surface of the masseter muscle.
label: Masseteric Artery

description: A small blood vessel between the internal pterygoid and the ramus of the jaw, which runs obliquely forward toward the outer surface of the buccinator.
label: Buccal Artery

description: A branch of the maxillary artery that is found in the gingiva, premolars, and molars.
label: Alveolar Artery

description: An artery that supplies oxygenated blood to the ear.
label: Auricular Artery

description: A blood vessel that supplies blood to the muscles of the neck.
label: Cervical Artery

description: An artery arising from the thyrocervical trunk with branches that supply the trapezius muscles as well as some muscles and glands in the neck.
label: Superficial Cervical Artery

description: The arteries branching from the splenic artery within the trabeculae of the spleen.
label: Splenic Trabecular Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the anterior side of the internal iliac artery that supplies the base of the bladder, prostate gland and seminal vesicles.
label: Inferior Vesical Artery

description: A blood vessel arising from the internal iliac artery that runs along the bladder with branches supplying the bladder.
label: Superior Vesical Artery

description: One of two vessels (anterior or posterior) carrying oxygenated blood to areas in the cranium, sinuses and nasal regions.
label: Ethmoidal Artery

description: A blood vessel also known as the supratrochlear artery that arises from the ophthalmic artery and ascends on the forehead.
label: Frontal Artery

description: One of two (right and left) arteries along the greater curvature of the stomach that supply blood to the greater omentum and stomach.
label: Gastroepiploic Artery

description: An artery arising from the internal pudendal artery that supplies the lower portion of the rectum and anastomoses with the superior and middle hemorrhoidal arteries.
label: Inferior Rectal Artery

description: An artery arising from the third portion of the maxillary artery at the trunk and running along the infraorbital canal with the superior maxillary nerve to supply the inferior rectus and inferior oblique muscles, lacrimal gland, the upper teeth, and parts of the nose and orbit.
label: Infraorbital Artery

description: The blood vessel that supplies the breast and the anterior chest wall with arterial blood. It is located in the chest wall.
label: Internal Mammary Artery

description: Either of two arteries (inferior or superior) that supply the lips.
label: Labial Artery

description: An artery originating from the ophthalmic artery with many branches that supply numerous areas including the lacrimal gland, eyelids and forehead.
label: Lacrimal Artery

description: An artery arising from the axillary artery that supplies the mammary gland and chest muscles.
label: Lateral Thoracic Artery

description: One of the terminal branches of the posterior tibial artery that runs along the inside of the foot to supply the muscles of the sole.
label: Medial Plantar Artery

description: Either of two arteries that arise from the dorsalis pedis artery that supply the inner margin of the foot.
label: Medial Tarsal Artery

description: An artery arising from the anterior interosseous artery in the forearm that runs parallel to the median nerve and supplies the palm of the hand.
label: Median Artery

description: The terminal branch of the inferior alveolar artery that supplies the chin.
label: Mental Artery

description: One of the four blood vessels arising from the dorsal carpal arch that runs down the posterior side of the second, third, and fourth interosseous muscles of the hand.
label: Dorsal Metacarpal Artery

description: An artery arising from the superior mesenteric artery that supplies the transverse colon.
label: Middle Colic Artery

description: A vessel arising from the ophthalmic artery that supplies the skin of the root of the nose with oxygenated blood.
label: Dorsal Nasal Artery

description: An artery arising from the internal pudendal artery that supplies the bulbocavernosus and ischiocavernosus muscles of the perineum.
label: Perineal Artery

description: An artery arising from the ophthalmic artery that supplies the retina.
label: Retinal Artery

description: An artery arising from the lingual artery that supplies the sublingual gland and surrounding muscles as well as the mucous membranes of the mouth and gums.
label: Sublingual Artery

description: An artery arising from the subscapular artery that supplies the muscles in the upper back.
label: Thoracodorsal Artery

description: A short arterial segment arising from the first segment of the subclavian artery that branches to form the inferior and superior thyroid arteries.
label: Thyroid Artery

description: One of the three branches of the thyroid axis that supplies the thyroid gland and branches to form the ascending cervical, esophageal, inferior laryngeal, muscular and tracheal arteries.
label: Inferior Thyroid Artery

description: An artery arising from the superficial temporal artery that supplies the masseter muscle and corresponding skin as well as the parotid duct and parotid gland.
label: Transverse Facial Artery

description: A small, terminal branch in the arterial system. Arterioles often connect to capillaries.
label: Arteriole

description: A blood vessel that carries blood toward the heart.
label: Vein

description: A vein that starts within the inguinal region and extends to the lower extremities.
label: Femoral Vein

description: A vein that accompanies the common femoral artery and is formed by the confluence of the femoral vein and the deep femoral vein.
label: Common Femoral Vein

description: A vein located in the upper thigh that connects, through tributaries, to the popliteal and inferior gluteal veins, and joins the superficial femoral vein at the groin to form the common femoral vein.
label: Deep Femoral Vein

description: A circumflex femoral vein that accompanies the medial circumflex femoral artery.
label: Medial Circumflex Femoral Vein

description: Any of the three veins including the common, external and internal iliac veins.
label: Iliac Vein

description: A blood vessel containing deoxygenated blood formed by the joining of the internal and external iliac veins at the pelvic brim that runs upward behind the internal iliac artery to the right side of the fifth lumbar vertebra where it joins with its counterpart from the opposite side of the body to form the inferior vena cava.
label: Common Iliac Vein

description: A vein in the lower torso accompanying the external iliac artery that connects the femoral vein with the common iliac vein.
label: External Iliac Vein

description: A blood vessel running parallel to the internal iliac artery that joins with the external iliac vein to drain blood into the common iliac vein from the pelvic organs as well as the inner thigh.
label: Internal Iliac Vein

description: Veins in the neck which drain the brain, face, and neck into the brachiocephalic or subclavian veins.
label: Jugular Vein

description: A vein arising near the hyoid bone from several veins from the submaxillary region. It terminates in the external jugular vein.
label: Anterior Jugular Vein

description: A large superficial vein in the neck that empties into the subclavian vein.
label: External Jugular Vein

description: A continuation of the sigmoid sinus of the dura mater; joins the subclavian vein to form the brachiocephalic vein.
label: Internal Jugular Vein

description: A vein that drains the superficial muscles and integument of the upper back portion of the neck into the external jugular vein.
label: Posterior External Jugular Vein

description: One of four veins that carries oxygen-rich blood from the lungs to the cardiac left atrium.
label: Pulmonary Vein

description: A vein that returns oxygenated blood from the left lung to the left atrium of the heart.
label: Left Pulmonary Vein

description: A vein that returns oxygenated blood from the right lung to the left atrium of the heart.
label: Right Pulmonary Vein

description: The vein that drains the axillary vein and joins the internal jugular vein to form the brachiocephalic vein. The subclavian vein runs parallel to the subclavian artery.
label: Subclavian Vein

description: A large vein that returns blood from the lower half of the body to the heart.
label: Inferior Vena Cava

description: The large vein that terminates in the right atrium and transports deoxygenated blood from the head, neck, arms, and chest to the heart.
label: Superior Vena Cava

description: A large vein which returns blood from the head, neck and extremities to the heart.
label: Vena Cava

description: A blood vessel in the heart which returns coronary blood to the chambers of the heart, most often the right atrium.
label: Coronary Vein

description: Any of the three cardiac veins including the small, middle and great cardiac veins.
label: Cardiac Vein

description: A vein originating at the apex of the heart that receives numerous tributaries as it ascends before draining into the left extremity of the coronary sinus.
label: Great Cardiac Vein

description: A vein originating at the apex of the heart that ascends along the posterior interventricular sulcus and drains into the coronary sinus.
label: Middle Cardiac Vein

description: A vein running parallel to the right coronary artery in the coronary sulcus that drains into the right extremity of the coronary sinus.
label: Small Cardiac Vein

description: Deep vein of the upper arm that forms at the junction of the radial and ulnar veins and ends at the inferior border of the teres major.
label: Brachial Vein

description: A segment of a blood vessel that is part of the venous system.
label: Venous Segment

description: The portion of the distal end of the main portal vein that branches into the left and right portal veins.
label: Portal Vein Bifurcation

description: Any of the superficial veins located within the muscles of the posterior lower leg, including the gastrocnemial and soleal veins.
label: Calf Muscular Vein

description: A vein that arises from the plantar veins of the foot, accompanies the peroneal artery, and travels up the back of the leg to join the anterior and posterior tibial veins in forming the popliteal vein on the posterior surface of the knee.
label: Fibular Vein

description: Either of two veins including the anterior and posterior tibial veins.
label: Tibial Vein

description: The vein that runs parallel to the anterior tibial artery and empties into the popliteal vein.
label: Anterior Tibial Vein

description: A vein in the foot that is formed by the union of the external and internal plantar veins and which becomes the popliteal vein.
label: Posterior Tibial Vein

description: A vein arising from the splenic trabecular vein in the hilum of the spleen that drains into the portal vein.
label: Splenic Vein

description: The veins which return blood from the kidneys to the vena cava.
label: Renal Vein

description: A vein that drains blood from the left kidney into the inferior vena cava.
label: Left Renal Vein

description: A vein that drains blood from the right kidney into the inferior vena cava.
label: Right Renal Vein

description: Either of two veins (left gastric and right gastric) that drain blood away from the stomach and lesser curvature.
label: Gastric Vein

description: A large blood vessel which returns blood to the heart from the lateral thorax, axilla, and upper limb. Each side of the body contains one axillary vein.
label: Axillary Vein

description: One of the moderately large superficial veins of the forearm that transports blood from the hand and the medial aspect of the forearm to the axillary vein.
label: Basilic Vein

description: A vein that it is part of the deep intracranial venous system.
label: Anterior Caudate Vein

description: A vein that extends along the ulna to the elbow joint.
label: Anterior Ulnar Vein

description: A blood vessel containing deoxygenated blood formed by the joining of the anterior and posterior ulnar veins.
label: Common Ulnar Vein

description: Any vein within the cortex of the brain.
label: Cortical Vein

description: The veins within the hepatic lobes that drain blood from the liver sinusoids into the hepatic vein.
label: Central Vein

description: A blood vessel carrying deoxygenated blood from the gallbladder and the cystic duct into the right branch of the portal vein.
label: Cystic Vein

description: The blood vessel carrying deoxygenated blood that arises from the superior epigastric vein and empties into the external iliac vein.
label: Inferior Epigastric Vein

description: The blood vessel carrying deoxygenated blood and accompanies the deep palmar artery in the hand.
label: Deep Palmar Vein

description: A blood vessel carrying deoxygenated blood far beneath the skin usually accompanying an artery.
label: Deep Vein

description: One of five superficial veins of the upper extremity, beginning at the radial aspect of the wrist area, wrapping around the forearm and emptying into the axillary vein.
label: Cephalic Vein

description: A vein in the face accompanying the facial artery that is a direct continuation of the angular vein and ultimately empties into the internal jugular vein.
label: Facial Vein

description: A vein that represents a continuation of the angular vein and lies behind the facial artery.
label: Anterior Facial Vein

description: Either of two veins including the right and left innominate vein.
label: Brachiocephalic Vein

description: A vein in the upper chest on the left side of the body that joins with the right innominate vein to form the superior vena cava.
label: Left Brachiocephalic Vein

description: A short vein in the area of the clavicle on the right side of the body that joins with the left innominate vein to form the superior vena cava.
label: Right Brachiocephalic Vein

description: A venous plexus arising from the superior hemorrhoidal and inferior mesenteric veins that surrounds the lower portion of the rectum.
label: Hemorrhoidal Plexus

description: Two veins running parallel to their corresponding internal mammary arteries that unite forming one vessel. These veins drain the chest wall into the innominate vein.
label: Internal Thoracic Vein

description: A vein that drains many branches from the pterygoid plexus in the head and face and which joins with the temporal vein to form the temporo-maxillary vein.
label: Maxillary Vein

description: A group of veins that drain the infero-internal portion of the occipital lobe into the vein of Galen.
label: Internal Occipital Vein

description: One of two deep veins (anterior or posterior) that run parallel to their corresponding artery in the forearm to drain the wrist and hand.
label: Interosseous Vein

description: The blood vessels that drain blood from the central veins of the liver into the inferior vena cava.
label: Hepatic Vein

description: The blood vessel that drains blood from the capillary beds between the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary.
label: Hypophyseal Portal Vein

description: A superficial blood vessel within the brain that drains the temporal lobe.
label: Inferior Anastomotic Vein of the Labbe

description: A vein between the biceps and pronator radii teres muscles that unites with the common ulnar vein to form the basilic vein within the forearm.
label: Median Basilic Vein

description: A vein between the biceps and supinator longus muscle in the forearm that unites with the radial vein to form the cephalic vein.
label: Median Cephalic Vein

description: A vein originating in the thumb that ascends the forearm and branches into the median basilic and median cephalic veins at the elbow.
label: Median Vein

description: A vein originating from the anterior and posterior tibial veins that ascends the popliteal space to drain blood from the calf, knee joint, and thigh. The popliteal vein ultimately becomes the femoral vein.
label: Popliteal Vein

description: A short thick trunk vein that transports blood containing the absorbed products of digestion from the intestine directly to the liver.
label: Portal Vein

description: A vein that joins with the retromandibular vein to form the external jugular vein and drains the area behind the ear.
label: Posterior Auricular Vein

description: A vein that ascends on the posterior surface of the ulnar side of the forearm to drain the palm of the hand. The posterior ulnar vein either unites with the anterior ulnar vein to form the common ulnar vein or with the median basilic vein to form the basilic vein.
label: Posterior Ulnar Vein

description: One of two (Greater, Small) superficial veins of the leg and thigh.
label: Saphenous Vein

description: A long superficial vein originating from the dorsal vein at the big toe and the dorsal venous arch of the foot and extending up the inner leg to empty into the femoral artery in the groin area.
label: Long Saphenous Vein

description: A superficial vein originating from the dorsal vein at the fifth toe and the dorsal venous arch of the foot and extends up the back of the leg to empty into the popliteal vein at the knee joint.
label: Short Saphenous Vein

description: The paired veins in the frontal lobe and along the septum pellucidum that drain into the internal cerebral veins.
label: Septal Vein

description: Any of the veins carrying deoxygenated blood from the subcutaneous tissue layers.
label: Superficial Vein

description: Any of the veins carrying deoxygenated blood in the subcutaneous tissue layers of the hand.
label: Superficial Vein of the Hand

description: A vein originating at the parietal lobe that runs along the horizontal portion of the fissure of Sylvius and opens into the cavernous sinus.
label: Superior Anastomotic Vein of Trolard

description: A vein that ascends on the radial side of the forearm to drain blood from the palm of the hand. The radial vein joins with the median cephalic vein in the elbow to form the cephalic vein.
label: Radial Vein of the Upper Extremity

description: Either of two veins (left or right) that drain the second, third, and fourth intercostal spaces. The right superior intercostal vein drains into the right azygos vein while the left superior intercostal vein drains into the left innominate vein.
label: Superior Intercostal Vein

description: A superficial vein that ascends the forehead and joins with the frontal vein to form the angular vein.
label: Supraorbital Vein

description: Any vein within the general circulation that transports blood back to the right atrium of the heart.
label: Systemic Vein

description: A vein formed by the joining of the internal maxillary vein and the temporal vein that runs along the ramus of the jaw and joins with the posterior auricular vein to form the external jugular vein and drain blood from the head and face.
label: Retromandibular Vein

description: Any blood vessel within in the head or neck that transports deoxygenated blood.
label: Vein of the Head or Neck

description: Either of two veins including the inferior and superior thalamostriate veins within the thalamus and striatum.
label: Thalamostriate Vein

description: Either of two veins including the inferior and superior epigastric veins.
label: Epigastric Vein

description: The veins that drain blood from the ileum into the superior mesenteric vein.
label: Ileal Vein

description: A blood vessel running parallel to the ileocolic artery that drains blood from the terminal ileum and ascending colon into the superior mesenteric vein.
label: Ileocolic Vein

description: A blood vessel running parallel to the iliolumbar artery connected to the deep circumflex iliac and lumbar veins that drains into the internal iliac vein.
label: Iliolumbar Vein

description: The blood vessels that drain blood from the inferior eyelid into the angular vein.
label: Inferior Palpebral Vein

description: The veins arising in the right and left testicles that join to form the spermatic plexus then diverge with the left segment draining into the left renal vein and the right into the inferior vena cava.
label: Spermatic Vein

description: A vein that forms the spermatic plexus to drain the left testis into the left renal vein.
label: Left Spermatic Vein

description: A vein that forms the spermatic plexus to drain the right testis into the inferior vena cava.
label: Right Spermatic Vein

description: The veins that drain blood from the masseter muscle into the pterygoid venous plexus.
label: Masseteric Vein

description: One of two veins (inferior or superior) that returns deoxygenated blood from the intestines.
label: Mesenteric Vein

description: A blood vessel running parallel to the inferior mesenteric artery that drains blood from the descending and sigmoid colon as well as the rectum into the splenic vein.
label: Inferior Mesenteric Vein

description: A vein that follows the path of the superior mesenteric artery and joins with the splenic vein to form the hepatic portal vein.
label: Superior Mesenteric Vein

description: A vein that drains the hip joint, obturator, and adductor muscles of the thigh into the internal iliac vein.
label: Obturator Vein

description: Either of two veins (right or left) that drains its corresponding ovary into the inferior vena cava.
label: Ovarian Vein

description: A vein that drains blood from the pancreas into the splenic and superior mesenteric veins.
label: Pancreatic Vein

description: The veins within the spleen that drain blood from the sinuses of the pulp and unite at the hilum to form the splenic vein.
label: Splenic Trabecular Vein

description: The vessels carrying deoxygenated blood on the upper side of the foot that originate from the dorsal digital vein creating the dorsal venous arch.
label: Dorsal Metatarsal Vein

description: A vein running parallel to the superior and inferior pancreatico-duodenal arteries that drains blood from the pancreas and duodenum into the superior mesenteric or portal veins.
label: Pancreatico-Duodenal Vein

description: A blood vessel running parallel to the inferior pancreatico-duodenal artery that drains blood from the pancreas and duodenum into the splenic vein.
label: Inferior Pancreatico-Duodenal Vein

description: The veins running parallel to the pericardiacophrenic arteries that drain into the brachiocephalic veins or superior vena cava.
label: Pericardiacophrenic Vein

description: The veins that run parallel to the phrenic arteries which include the two superior and two inferior phrenic veins.
label: Phrenic Vein

description: A vein that drains the retina of the eye.
label: Retinal Vein

description: Either of two veins (right or left) under the twelfth rib.
label: Subcostal Vein

description: A vein that extends along the bottom of the twelfth rib on the right side of the body.
label: Right Subcostal Vein

description: A vein that extends along the bottom of the twelfth rib on the left side of the body.
label: Left Subcostal Vein

description: A vein in the chin that is connected to the sublingual and anterior jugular veins and drains into the facial vein.
label: Submental Vein

description: A vein that returns blood to the heart from the adrenal gland.  The right adrenal vein empties directly into the inferior vena cava and the left adrenal vein empties into the left renal vein.
label: Suprarenal Vein

description: A vein that drains blood from the right adrenal gland into the inferior vena cava.
label: Right Suprarenal Vein

description: A vein that drains blood from the left adrenal gland into the left renal artery.
label: Left Suprarenal Vein

description: A vein in front of the ear that drains the head and face and joins with the internal maxillary vein to form the temporo-maxillary vein.
label: Temporal Vein

description: The blood vessels at the vertex and on either side of the head that drain deoxygenated blood into the pterygoid venous plexus.
label: Deep Temporal Vein

description: A vein on the side of the head that merges with the internal maxillary vein to form the posterior facial vein.
label: Superficial Temporal Vein

description: Either of two veins including the internal and lateral thoracic veins that drain the breasts and chest wall.
label: Thoracic Vein

description: The veins that drain blood from the thymus into the left brachiocephalic vein.
label: Thymic Vein

description: A vein originating within the occipital region that descends along the cervical vertebrae while receiving numerous tributaries to ultimately empty into the brachiocephalic vein.
label: Vertebral Vein

description: A vein that drains the auricle and acoustic meatus of the external ear.
label: Anterior Auricular Vein

description: A blood vessel which returns blood to the heart from the posterior walls of the thorax and abdomen.
label: Azygos Vein

description: The veins that drain the bronchi then form two branches where the right side drains into the right azygos vein and the left side drains into the left superior intercostal or left upper azygos vein.
label: Bronchial Vein

description: A superficial vein that is located on the cerebellum and that drains the cerebellum.
label: Cerebellar Vein

description: A vein that arises from the precentral cerebellar fissure and terminates in the great central vein.
label: Precentral Cerebellar Vein

description: Any of the external or internal veins that drain the cerebral hemispheres.
label: Cerebral Vein

description: A large blood vessel formed by the anterior and deep middle cerebral veins and small branches from the insula and cerebral peduncles which receives tributaries from the temporal horn and the medial temporal lobe and is joined by the inferior striate veins. This vessel may also receive blood from the lateral mesencephalic vein and empties into the vein of Galen.
label: Basal Cerebral Vein of Rosenthal

description: The blood vessel that receives deoxygenated blood from the insula and gyri and drains into the basal vein of Rosenthal deep in the lateral sulcus.
label: Deep Middle Cerebral Vein

description: A pair of parallel blood vessels deep within both cerebral hemispheres that are formed by the union of the choroid and terminal veins and drain into the great cerebral vein.
label: Internal Cerebral Vein

description: A vein that runs along the fissure of Sylvius to the cavernous sinus on the lateral surface of the brain and connects to the superior sagittal and transverse sinuses.
label: Superficial Middle Cerebral Vein

description: A blood vessel formed by the union of the two internal cerebral veins that drains the cerebrum and joins with the inferior sagittal sinus to form the straight sinus.
label: Great Cerebral Vein of Galen

description: A vein that drains blood from a specific area of the skin.
label: Cutaneous Vein

description: Any vein containing deoxygenated blood that is located in a finger or toe.
label: Digital Vein

description: A vein located in the ear region. It may pertain to the anterior or posterior auricular veins.
label: Auricular Vein

description: The part of the microvasculature that receives blood from the capillaries, and which then converges to form veins.
label: Venule

description: The first potion of the venous component of the microcirculation composed of endothelial cells, pericytes, and a basement membrane, which is one of the main sites for the interchange of gas and metabolite molecules between the tissues and the blood.
label: Postcapillary Venule

description: A post-capillary system of blood vessels containing thick rather than thin endothelial cells which allow for the migration of blood lymphocytes into the lymph node.
label: High Endothelial Venule

description: Any of the branches of the vessels arising from the common iliac artery or vein, located in the pelvis.
label: Iliac Vessel

description: A collection of the smallest blood vessels of the vascular system, which are involved in the exchange of gases, water, nutrients, and waste products, and which includes blood vessels from the first-order arteriole to the first-order venule.
label: Microcirculatory Bed

description: A direct linkage between an artery and a vein.
label: Arteriovenous Shunt

description: A vascular plexus comprising small arteries and veins that are located in the walls of large blood vessels.
label: Vasa Vasorum

description: Any portion of the aorta including the ascending and descending aorta, and aortic arch or a portion of the aortic orifice of the left ventricle.
label: Aortic Segment

description: The segment of the arterial system that includes the iliac artery and its origin from the aorta.
label: Aortoiliac Artery Segment

description: The portion of the abdominal aorta that lies below the kidneys.
label: Infrarenal Aortic Segment

description: The portion of the abdominal aorta superior to the renal arteries.
label: Suprarenal Aorta

description: The portion of the aorta that emerges from the left ventricle and precedes the aortic arch.
label: Ascending Aorta

description: The portion of the descending aorta that lies within the abdomen, beginning below the diaphragm and ending at its division into the right and left common iliac arteries.
label: Abdominal Aorta

description: The portion of the aorta following the aortic arch passing into the chest and abdomen creating the thoracic and abdominal segments.
label: Descending Aorta

description: The section of the aorta between the lower border of the fourth dorsal vertebrae and the aortic opening in the diaphragm.
label: Thoracic Aorta

description: A blood vessel located in the following sites: upper extremities, lower extremities, lower abdomen, head, or neck.
label: Peripheral Blood Vessel

description: The portion of the ascending aorta between the aortic annulus and the sinotubular junction.
label: Aortic Root

description: The terminus of the aortic root; the point at which the aorta attains a tubular configuration.
label: Sinotubular Junction

description: Any component of the organ which receives blood from the veins and ejects it into the arteries.
label: Heart Part

description: A fibrous membrane that attaches to, and provides support for, the aortic valve leaflets.
label: Aortic Valve Annulus

description: The paired upper chambers of the heart. The left atrium receives oxygenated blood from the pulmonary vein and pumps blood into the left ventricle. The right atrium receives venous deoxygenated blood from the entire body via the superior and inferior vena cavae and pumps blood into the right ventricle.
label: Cardiac Atrium

description: One of four chambers of the heart, which receives blood from the pulmonary veins and pumps blood through the mitral valve into the left ventricle.
label: Left Atrium

description: One of the four chambers of the heart, which is located immediately superior to the right ventricle, and which receives deoxygenated venous blood from the systemic circulation.
label: Right Atrium

description: Any of the four heart valves, including the two atrioventricular valves and the two semilunar valves, which regulate the flow of blood through the chambers of the heart.
label: Cardiac Valve

description: A valve that is located between and controls the flow of blood from the left ventricle of the heart and the aorta.
label: Aortic Valve

description: A valve that is located between and controls the flow of blood from the right ventricle of the heart and the pulmonary artery.
label: Pulmonary Valve

description: One of two valves in the heart situated between the atria and ventricles, including the mitral valve and the tricuspid valve.
label: Atrioventricular Valve

description: A dual-flap valve of the heart that regulates the flow of blood between the left atrium and the left ventricle of the heart.
label: Mitral Valve

description: A three-cusp valve of the heart that regulates the flow of blood between the right atrium and the right ventricle of the heart.
label: Tricuspid Valve

description: A thin, crescent-shaped fold of the endocardium at the orifice of the coronary sinus into the right atrium.
label: Coronary Valve

description: An embryological structure found at the junction of the inferior vena cava and the right atrium, which, during gestation, functions to direct the flow of blood from the right atrium into the left atrium via the foramen ovale.
label: Eustachian Valve

description: One of the two lower chambers of the heart that receives blood from an atrium and pumps blood to the arteries.
label: Cardiac Ventricle

description: The lower chamber of the heart located in the right side. It receives blood from the right atrium that is no longer oxygenated and it pumps it to the pulmonary artery.
label: Right Ventricle

description: The left lower chamber of the heart that receives blood from the left atrium and pumps it through the aorta to the body.
label: Left Ventricle

description: A saddle-shaped, fibrous structure that provides support to the mitral valve leaflets, and functions to contract during ventricular systole, thereby providing complete closure of the mitral valve and preventing regurgitant blood flow into the left atrium.
label: Mitral Valve Annulus

description: The portion of the mitral valve annulus that attaches to the anterior mitral valve leaflet, and also forms the mitral portion of the aortic-mitral curtain.
label: Anterior Annulus of the Mitral Valve

description: The cusp of the mitral valve that is anchored to the aortic-mitral curtain.
label: Anterior Cusp of the Mitral Valve

description: The portion of the mitral valve annulus that attaches to the posterior mitral valve leaflet.
label: Posterior Annulus of the Mitral Valve

description: The cusp of the mitral valave that is located posterior to the two commissures, and which has no attachement to the aortic root.
label: Posterior Cusp of the Mitral Valve

description: The layer of endothelial cells and connective tissue lining the chambers of the heart.
label: Endocardium

description: The innermost layer of endothelial cells and connective tissue that lines the right atrium.
label: Right Atrial Endocardium

description: The innermost layer of endothelial cells and connective tissue that lines the right ventricle.
label: Right Ventricular Endocardium

description: The ear-shaped, muscular pouch of the left atrium.
label: Left Atrial Appendage

description: The funnel-shaped structure through which blood flows from the left ventricle into the aortic root.
label: Left Ventricular Outflow Tract

description: The wall of the left ventricle, comprising anterior, inferior, lateral, apical, basal wall; and excluding the interventricular septum.
label: Left Ventricular Wall

description: The ear-shaped, muscular pouch of the right atrium.
label: Right Atrial Appendage

description: The lateral segment of the right ventricular wall, excluding the anterior and inferior right ventricular wall.
label: Right Ventricular Free Wall

description: The funnel-shaped structure through which blood flows from the right ventricle into the pulmonary trunk.
label: Right Ventricular Outflow Tract

description: The wall of the right ventricle, comprising anterior, inferior, and lateral walls; and excluding the interventricular septum.
label: Right Ventricular Wall

description: The apical cap division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Apex Segment

description: The anterior portion of the apical division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Apical Anterior Segment

description: The inferior portion of the apical division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Apical Inferior Segment

description: The lateral portion of the apical division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Apical Lateral Segment

description: The septal portion of the apical division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Apical Septal Segment

description: The anterior portion of the basal division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Basal Anterior Segment

description: The anterolateral portion of the basal division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Basal Anterolateral Segment

description: The anteroseptal portion of the basal division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Basal Anteroseptal Segment

description: The inferior portion of the basal division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Basal Inferior Segment

description: The inferolateral portion of the basal division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Basal Inferolateral Segment

description: The inferoseptal portion of the basal division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Basal Inferoseptal Segment

description: The anterior portion of the mid-cavity division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Mid Anterior Segment

description: The anterolateral portion of the mid-cavity division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Mid Anterolateral Segment

description: The anteroseptal portion of the mid-cavity division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Mid Anteroseptal Segment

description: The inferior portion of the mid-cavity division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Mid Inferior Segment

description: The inferolateral portion of the mid-cavity division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Mid Inferolateral Segment

description: The inferoseptal portion of the mid-cavity division of the left ventricular myocardium as determined using the AHA 17-Segment Model (Cerqueira et al., 2002).
label: Left Ventricular Mid Inferoseptal Segment

description: The wall of the pericardium, comprising the following tissue layers: the fibrous pericardium; the parietal and visceral layers of the serous pericardium.
label: Pericardial Wall

description: A fibrous membrane that attaches to, and provides support for, the tricuspid valve leaflets.
label: Tricuspid Valve Annulus

description: The portion of the tricuspid valve annulus that attaches to both the posterior and lateral tricuspid valve leaflets.
label: Posterior Annulus of the Tricuspid Valve

description: The outer membranous connective tissue layer of the heart tissue.
label: Epicardium

description: The outermost layer of cardiac tissue lining of the left ventricle.
label: Left Ventricular Epicardium

description: All of the tissue that comprises the solid, outer structure of the heart, including the epicardium, the myocardium, and the endocardium.
label: Cardiac Wall

description: The anatomical space of the cardiac ventricle.
label: Heart, Ventricular Chamber

description: The inferior portion of the right ventricle of the heart.
label: Base of the Right Ventricle

description: The central portion of the right ventricle of the heart.
label: Mid Level Right Ventricle

description: The lowest superficial part of the heart which is situated behind the left 5th intercostal space.
label: Apex of the Heart

description: A bundle of specialized heart muscle fibers that conducts impulses from the atrioventricular node to the ventricles.
label: Atrioventricular Bundle

description: A small mass of specialized cardiac muscle fibers, located near the ostium of the coronary sinus and giving rise to the atrioventricular bundle of the conduction system of the heart.
label: Atrioventricular Node

description: Tendons that connect the papillary muscles to the tricuspid valve and mitral valve.
label: Chordae Tendineae

description: The coronary vein that terminates in the right atrium and transports deoxygenated blood from the coronary circulation.
label: Coronary Sinus

description: The hole in the right atrium where the inferior vena cava enters.
label: Inferior Vena Cava Opening

description: The intercellular structures including the fascia adherens, gap junctions and macula adherens that connect single cardiac muscle cells to allow for synchronized contractions.
label: Intercalated Disc

description: The hole in the left atrium of the heart where the pulmonary vein enters.
label: Opening of the Pulmonary Vein

description: One of three layers of the endocardium comprising a layer of loose connective tissue continuous with the myocardium. The impulse-conducting system (Purkinje fibers) is located within this layer.
label: Subendocardial Layer

description: A specialized cardiac muscle fiber found in the subendocardium that relays cardiac impulses from the AV node to the ventricular cells.
label: Purkinje Fiber

description: The site of the opening (non-valve) at which the superior vena cava enters the right atrium.
label: Superior Vena Cava Opening

description: A cluster of specialized cells located in the upper area of the right atrium. These cells generate the electrical impulses that result in the normal sinus rhythm.
label: Sinoatrial Node

description: Any one of the three normal anatomical dilatations of the aortic wall, which are located behind each of the cusps of the aortic valve.
label: Sinus of Valsalva

description: A valvule or leaflet that comprises a heart valve.
label: Cardiac Valve Cusp

description: The cusp of the aortic valve that overlies the left coronary ostium.
label: Left Coronary Cusp of the Aortic Valve

description: The cusp of the aortic valve that is positioned posteriorly relative to the other two aortic cusps.
label: Non-Coronary Cusp of the Aortic Valve

description: The cusp of the aortic valve that overlies the right coronary ostium.
label: Right Coronary Cusp of the Aortic Valve

description: The cusp of the pulmonic valve that has no attachment to the cardiac septum.
label: Anterior Cusp of the Pulmonary Valve

description: The cusp of the pulmonic valve attached to the left side of the cardiac septum.
label: Left Cusp of the Pulmonary Valve

description: The cusp of the pulmonic valve attached to the right side of the cardiac septum.
label: Right Cusp of the Pulmonary Valve

description: The cusp of the tricuspid valve that is located between the atrioventricular orifice and the conus arteriosus.
label: Anterior Cusp of the Tricuspid Valve

description: The cusp of the tricuspid valve that is located posterior and on the margin of the right ventricle.
label: Posterior Cusp of the Tricuspid Valve

description: The cusp of the tricuspid valve that is attached to the right and left fibrous trigones and the atrial and ventricular septa.
label: Septal Cusp of the Tricuspid Valve

description: The superior portion of the heart located opposite to the apical portion. It is formed mainly by the left atrium.
label: Base of the Heart

description: The tissue in the heart that separates the two atria (atrial septum) and the two ventricles (ventricular septum).
label: Heart Septum

description: The junction where the tissue of the atrial septum and the ventricular septum meet.
label: Atrioventricular Septum

description: The tissue that separates the right atrium from the left atrium in the heart.
label: Interatrial Septum

description: The wall that separates the left and right ventricles of the heart.
label: Interventricular Septum

description: The site of confluence of the superior sagittal sinus, the left and right transverse sinuses, and the straight sinus, which is located near the internal occipital protuberance.
label: Torcular Herophili

description: A tubule that carries lymph throughout the body.
label: Lymphatic Vessel

description: The tubules that carry lymph throughout the body that are in the interior of the body or limbs.
label: Deep Lymphatic Vessel

description: A lymphatic vessel that is formed by efferent lymphatic vessels and empties lymph into the lymphatic ducts.
label: Lymph Trunk

description: The tubules that carry lymph throughout the body that are just beneath the surface of the skin.
label: Superficial Lymphatic Vessel

description: The largest lymphatic vessel in the body, originating at the cisternal chyli and emptying into the junction of the left internal jugular and subclavian veins. It receives lymph from the entire body, with the exception of the right upper limb, the right side of the head and neck, and the right upper thorax.
label: Thoracic Duct

description: A dural venous sinus located along the posteroinferior ridge of the lesser wing of the sphenoid bone, which drains into the cavernous sinus and receives tributaries from the superficial middle cerebral vein, veins from the temporal lobe, the anterior temporal diploic vein, and, sometimes, the frontal ramus of the middle meningeal vein.
label: Sphenoparietal Sinus

description: The cardiovascular and lymphatic systems, collectively.
label: Vascular System

description: A term referring to the brain area that is supplied by both the right and the left internal carotid arteries and their arterial branches.
label: Intracranial Anterior Circulation

description: Any artery arising from the internal carotid artery.
label: Internal Carotid Artery Branch

description: One of the two arteries arising from the internal carotid artery and being part of the Circle of Willis. Both left and right anterior cerebral arteries are connected by the anterior communicating artery.
label: Anterior Cerebral Artery

description: The largest terminal branch of the internal carotid artery that runs along the fissure of Sylvius with branches supplying parts of the fontal, parietal and temporal lobes as well as the basal ganglia and internal capsule.
label: Middle Cerebral Artery

description: Any artery arising from the middle cerebral artery.
label: Middle Cerebral Artery Branch

description: A cortical branch of the middle cerebral artery supplying the ascending frontal convolution.
label: Ascending Frontal Artery

description: Terminal branch of the facial artery with distribution to the side of the nose.
label: Angular Artery

description: The artery that delivers blood to the anterior portion of the parietal lobe.
label: Anterior Parietal Artery

description: A branch of the middle cerebral artery that supplies blood to the anterior part of the temporal lobe.
label: Anterior Temporal Artery

description: A branch off of the terminal section of the middle cerebral artery running through the cortex on both sides of the central sulcus.
label: Central Artery

description: The arteries branching off of the horizontal or M1 segment of the middle cerebral artery in both hemispheres that supply the caudate nucleus and lentiform nucleus.
label: Lateral Lenticulostriate Artery

description: An artery branching from the extremity of the middle cerebral artery that supplies the lateral cortex and inferior frontal lobe.
label: Lateral Orbitofrontal Artery

description: The arteries branching off of the proximal middle cerebral artery that supply the medial region of the putamen and the globus pallidus.
label: Medial Lenticulostriate Artery

description: An intracranial artery that supplies the posterior part of the parietal lobe.
label: Posterior Parietal Artery

description: An artery arising from the insular section of the middle cerebral artery that supplies the posterior temporal lobe.
label: Posterior Temporal Artery

description: An artery arising from the terminal portion of the middle cerebral artery that runs along either side of the precentral sulcus to supply the cortex.
label: Precentral Artery

description: An arterial branch arising from the anterior cerebral artery. It includes the callosomarginal artery, frontopolar artery, medial orbitofrontal artery, pericallosal artery, and recurrent artery of Heubner.
label: Anterior Cerebral Artery Branch

description: An artery arising from the distal A1 or proximal A1 segment of the anterior cerebral artery that supplies the anteromedial caudate nucleus.
label: Recurrent Artery of Heubner

description: The second branch arising from the pericallosal artery within the cingulate sulcus that has branches supplying the medial and superolateral surfaces of each cerebral hemisphere.
label: Callosomarginal Artery

description: An artery arising from the A2 segment of the anterior cerebral artery that supplies the corpus callosum.
label: Frontopolar Artery

description: A terminal branch of the anterior cerebral artery that runs in the pericallosal sulcus and branches to form the inferior and superior internal parietal arteries and precuneal artery supplying the cerebral cortex.
label: Pericallosal Artery

description: An artery branching from the anterior cerebral artery that supplies the medial portions of the frontal and superior parietal lobes.
label: Medial Orbitofrontal Artery

description: An artery arising from the cavernous portion of the internal carotid artery that supplies the posterior pituitary gland.
label: Inferior Hypophyseal Artery

description: An artery arising from the internal carotid artery that branches into two groups of vessels; the orbital group that supplies the orbit and surrounding parts and the ocular group that supplies the globe and muscles of the eye.
label: Ophthalmic Artery

description: An artery arising from the cerebral portion of the internal carotid artery that supplies the infundibulum of the pituitary, median eminence and the pars tuberalis.
label: Superior Hypophyseal Artery

description: An artery that connects two larger arteries.
label: Communicating Artery

description: An artery that joins the two anterior cerebral arteries.
label: Anterior Communicating Artery

description: An artery on the left and right side of the base of the brain that forms part of the Circle of Willis by connecting to the internal carotid artery, anterior cerebral artery, and middle cerebral artery, anteriorly and the posterior cerebral artery, posteriorly.
label: Posterior Communicating Artery

description: A series of the vessels that transport deoxygenated blood.
label: Venous System

description: Two groups of blood vessels, deep and superficial intracranial veins, that drain deoxygenated blood from the brain.
label: Intracranial Venous System

description: The group of blood vessels within the interior of the brain carrying deoxygenated blood including the vena corporis striati and the choroid vein that unite to form the vena magna Galeni.
label: Deep Intracranial Venous System

description: A group of blood vessels at the surface of the brain carrying deoxygenated blood which include the superior, median, and inferior cerebral veins.
label: Superficial Intracranial Venous System

description: A system of vessels in which blood, after passing through one capillary bed, is conveyed through a second set of capillaries before it returns to the systemic circulation. It pertains especially to the hepatic portal system.
label: Portal Venous System

description: A system of vessels between the hypothalamus and anterior pituitary in which blood, after passing through one capillary bed, is conveyed through a second set of capillaries before it returns to the systemic circulation.
label: Hypothalamohypophyseal Portal System

description: A cluster of cells that function as chemo-receptors, located at the bifurcation of the carotid artery. Its main purpose is to detect changes in the composition of arterial blood.
label: Carotid Body

description: A small mass that is located in the inferior surface of the aortic arch. It functions as a peripheral chemoreceptor and is composed of glomus cells.
label: Aortic Body

description: A term that refers to any anatomic structure that is part of the digestive system.
label: Digestive System Part

description: A portion of the large intestine that includes the sigmoid colon and rectum.
label: Rectosigmoid Colon

description: Either one of two openings from the pancreatic ducts into the duodenum. The major duodenal papilla opens from the pancreatic duct into the duodenum. The minor duodenal papilla opens from the accessory pancreatic duct into the descending second section of the duodenum.
label: Duodenal Papilla

description: The terminal portion of the gastrointestinal tract, extending from the rectosigmoid junction to the anal canal.
label: Rectum

description: A blind pouch-like commencement of the colon in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen at the end of the small intestine and the start of the large intestine.
label: Cecum

description: The bend of the colon at the juncture of its ascending and transverse portions.
label: Hepatic Flexure

description: The bend at the junction of the transverse and descending colon.
label: Splenic Flexure

description: The area around the esophagogastric mucosal junction where the esophageal mucosa transitions into the gastric mucosa.
label: Gastric Cardia

description: The portion of the stomach that lies above the cardiac notch. It allows for the accumulation of gases produced by chemical digestion.
label: Fundus of the Stomach

description: The fourth portion of the large intestine (colon) that communicates with the transverse colon in the left-upper quadrant of the abdomen and the rectum below.
label: Descending Colon

description: The main section of the digestive tube that connects the esophagus to the small intestine. The body proper excludes the upper and lower sections of the fundus and pyloric portion respectively.
label: Body of Stomach

description: The initial part of the pyloric canal of the stomach. This site contains endocrine cells that produce gastrin and somatostatin.
label: Antrum Pylori

description: The lower part of the stomach that connects to the duodenum.
label: Pylorus

description: The right border of the stomach.  It is concave in shape and extends from the cardiac orifice to the pyloric orifice.
label: Lesser Curvature of the Stomach

description: The lateral and inferior border of the stomach. Attached to it is the greater omentum.
label: Greater Curvature of the Stomach

description: A jointed tube 25-30 cm long that connects the stomach to the jejunum.
label: Duodenum

description: The first part of the colon (large intestine) that starts in the right lower quadrant of the abdomen and ends at the transverse colon in the right upper quadrant of the abdomen.
label: Ascending Colon

description: The part of the large intestine measured from the cecum to the rectum consisting of ascending, transverse, descending and sigmoid portions. The purpose of the colon is to remove water from digested food prior to excretion.
label: Colon

description: The proximal segment of the large intestine that is located in the right side of the abdominal cavity. It includes the cecum (with the attached appendix) and the ascending colon.
label: Right Colon

description: The terminal section of the alimentary canal, which extends from the anorectal junction and ends at the anal opening.
label: Anal Canal

description: The portion of the colon that connects to the descending colon above and the rectum below.
label: Sigmoid Colon

description: The third division of the colon (large intestine). It communicates with the ascending colon in the upper right-hand quadrant of the abdomen and the descending colon in the upper left-hand quadrant.
label: Transverse Colon

description: A muscular tube that extends from the end of the small intestine to the anus.
label: Large Intestine

description: The section of the intestines between the pylorus and cecum. The small intestine is approximately 20 feet long and consists of the duodenum, the jejunum, and the ileum. Its main function is to absorb nutrients from food as the food is transported to the large intestine.
label: Small Intestine

description: The final section of the small intestine.
label: Ileum

description: Small tissue projection existing as a cecal diverticulum with a questionable history of vestigial versus specialized organ.
label: Appendix

description: The portion of the small intestine that extends from the duodenum to the ileum.
label: Jejunum

description: The junction of the common bile and main pancreatic ducts, which protrudes into the medial aspect of the descending duodenum at the major duodenal papilla. The flow of bile and pancreatic juices into the duodenum through the Ampulla of Vater is controlled by the sphincter of Oddi.
label: Ampulla of Vater

description: Any component of the organ behind the lower part of the stomach that is fish-shaped and is a compound gland composed of both exocrine and endocrine tissues that make and secrete insulin and enzymes that help the body digest food.
label: Pancreas Part

description: That portion of the pancreas lying in the concavity of the duodenum.
label: Head of the Pancreas

description: The part of the pancreas from the point where it crosses the portal vein to the point where it enters the lienorenal ligament.
label: Body of the Pancreas

description: The left extremity of the pancreas within the lienorenal ligament.
label: Tail of the Pancreas

description: The portion of the pancreas that is the junction of the head and body of the pancreas; the portion of the pancreas that lies anterior to the aorta.
label: Neck of the Pancreas

description: A portion of the pancreas that extends behind the superior mesenteric artery and superior mesenteric vein.
label: Uncinate Process of Pancreas

description: The valve between the ileum of the small intestine and the cecum of the large intestine.
label: Ileocecal Valve

description: The proximal portion of the stomach.
label: Proximal Stomach

description: A system that includes the pancreas and biliary tract.
label: Pancreatobiliary System

description: The multiple layers of specialized tissue that surround the cavity of the gastrointestinal tract, including the mucosa, submucosa, muscular layers, and serosa.
label: Gastrointestinal Tract Wall

description: The portion of the gastrointestinal tract wall that surrounds the cavities of the esophagus and stomach. The proximal duodenum is also sometimes considered part of the upper gastrointestinal tract.
label: Upper Gastrointestinal Tract Wall

description: The tissue that forms the wall of the stomach. It consists of mucosa, submucosa, muscular coat, and serosal surface.
label: Stomach Wall

description: The portion of the gastrointestinal tract wall that surrounds the cavities of the duodenum, jejunum, ileum, colon, rectum, and anus.
label: Lower Gastrointestinal Tract Wall

description: The portion of the gastrointestinal tract wall that surrounds the cavity of the colon and contains teniae coli, haustra, and epiploic appendages.
label: Colon Wall

description: The portion of the gastrointestinal tract wall that surrounds the cavity of the ileum and contains collections of lymphatic tissue called Peyer patches, as well as receptors for bile salts and vitamin B12.
label: Ileum Wall

description: The segment of the gastrointestinal tract where the terminal ileum transitions to the cecum, and where the ileocecal sphincter regulates the movement of chyme from the small intestine into the large intestine.
label: Ileocecal Junction

description: Transitional area involving the terminal ileum, cecum and beginning of the colon.
label: Ileocecocolic Region

description: The distal portion of the gastrointestinal tract that includes the anal canal and rectum.
label: Anorectum

description: The portion of the thoracic esophagus from midway between the tracheal bifurcation and gastroesophageal junction to gastroesophageal junction, including abdominal esophagus. (SEER)
label: Lower Thoracic Esophagus

description: The portion of the thoracic esophagus from the tracheal bifurcation midway to the gastroesophageal junction. (SEER)
label: Middle Thoracic Esophagus

description: The portion of the thoracic esophagus from the thoracic inlet to the level of the tracheal bifurcation. (SEER)
label: Upper Thoracic Esophagus

description: The part of colon that includes the cecum, ascending colon, and hepatic flexure.
label: Proximal Colon

description: The part of colon that includes the splenic flexure, descending colon, and sigmoid colon.
label: Distal Colon

description: The digestive system component that includes the esophagus and gastroesophageal junction.
