label: Esophagus and Gastroesophageal Junction

description: One of three or four semi-lunar horizontal folds of the rectal wall that serve to support the bulk of fecal matter.
label: Transverse Rectal Fold

description: A finger-like projection of the plasma membrane found in epithelial cells that increases the surface area of the apical domain of the epithelium. It is comprised of plasma membrane that is supported by longitudinal actin filaments that are crosslinked by fimbrin and villin.
label: Microvillus

description: The middle portion of the gallbladder which is distal to the gallbladder neck and proximal to the gallbladder fundus.
label: Gallbladder Body

description: The largest portion of the gallbladder which is furthest from the cystic duct.
label: Gallbladder Fundus

description: The narrowest portion of the gallbladder and distal to the cystic duct.
label: Gallbladder Neck

description: The small indentations in the stomach mucosa where the gastric glands open to the stomach lumen.
label: Gastric Pit

description: The creases or folds in the gastric mucosa that increase the stomach surface area and allow for an increase in volume without an increase in pressure.
label: Gastric Rugae

description: The anatomical location where the esophagus joins to the stomach.
label: Gastroesophageal Junction

description: Any sphincter in the gastrointestinal tract.
label: Gastrointestinal Sphincter

description: The muscle fibres around the opening of the common bile duct (ductus choledochus) into the duodenum at the papilla of Vater.
label: Sphincter of Oddi

description: The internal and external muscles surrounding the anus that maintain continence.
label: Anal Sphincter

description: A ring of striated muscular fibers surrounding the anus on the outside of the internal anal sphincter.
label: External Anal Sphincter

description: A ring of smooth muscle surrounding the anus on the inside of the external anal sphincter.
label: Internal Anal Sphincter

description: A group of muscles between the esophagus and stomach that actively prevents food from rising up out of the stomach.
label: Lower Esophageal Sphincter

description: The muscular structure at the distal portion of the stomach, opening into the duodenum.
label: Pyloric Sphincter

description: A valve that is composed of muscles in the upper portion of the esophagus.
label: Upper Esophageal Sphincter

description: The longitudinal folds present in the upper part of the anal canal.
label: Anal Column

description: The lower third segment of the anal canal.  It is covered with stratified squamous epithelium.
label: Anal Squamous Zone

description: The middle segment of the anal canal between the colorectal and squamous zones.
label: Anal Transitional Zone

description: A thin tube within the liver that collect bile secreted by hepatocytes. Many canaliculi come together to form bile ductules that ultimately form the common hepatic duct.
label: Bile Canaliculus

description: The anterior surface of the liver tissue.  It consists of the right and left lobes.
label: Anterior Surface of the Liver

description: The distal portion of the rectum that converges with the anal canal.
label: Colorectal Zone of the Anal Canal

description: The anterior aspect of the stomach.
label: Anterior Surface of the Stomach

description: Small vessels between the bile canaliculi and the interlobular bile ducts.
label: Canal of Hering

description: The region distal to the z-line of the gastroesophageal junctions, the area where the esophagus attaches to the stomach.
label: Cardia Orifice

description: The tube-like glands in the mucosal lining of the small and large intestines which secrete various enzymes that aid in digestion.
label: Crypt of Lieberkuhn

description: The tube-like glands in the mucosal lining of the large intestines which secrete various enzymes that aid in digestion.
label: Large Intestinal Crypt of Lieberkuhn

description: The tube-like glands in the mucosal lining of the small intestines which secrete various enzymes that aid in digestion.
label: Small Intestinal Crypt of Lieberkuhn

description: A thin layer of strong fibroareolar tissue beneath the serous coat covering the entire surface of the liver.
label: Fibrous Coat of the Liver

description: The proximal portion of the duodenum, the first section of the small intestines connected to the stomach.
label: First Portion of the Duodenum

description: The ascending portion of the duodenum between the aorta and the ligament of Treitz. This portion continues into the jejunum.
label: Fourth Portion of the Duodenum

description: An area of hepatocytes that are closest to an arteriole. Because of their close proximity to oxygenated blood, the cells in this zone carry out oxidative processes such as beta-oxidation, cholesterol synthesis and gluconeogenesis.
label: Liver Acinus Zone 1

description: An area of hepatocytes between zone 1 and 3 in which the cells display properties intermediate to both neighboring zones.
label: Liver Acinus Zone 2

description: An area of hepatocytes that are closest to a central vein. These cells receive the least amount of oxygenated blood and are thus more prone to ischemia and store fat.
label: Liver Acinus Zone 3

description: Any of the clefts or grooves on the surface of the liver.
label: Liver Fissure

description: A transverse fissure on the visceral surface of the liver between the caudate and quadrate lobes, lodging the portal vein, hepatic artery, hepatic nerve plexus, hepatic ducts, and lymphatic vessels.
label: Transverse Fissure

description: The posterior portion of the longitudinal fissure on the surface of the liver which separates the left lobe from the lobe of Spigelius and lodges the ductus venosus in the fetus.
label: Fissure of the Ductus Venosus

description: A groove or cleft on the surface of the gallbladder extending from the right portal vein to the gallbladder fossa.
label: Fissure of the Gallbladder

description: A short deep groove extending upwards from the lobus caudatus in the liver and lodges the vena cava.
label: Fissure of the Inferior Vena Cava

description: A groove that is located on the inferior surface of the liver.  It holds the round ligament.
label: Umbilical Fissure

description: The lower part of the gastrointestinal tract that includes the jejunum and ileum of the small intestine and the large intestine.
label: Lower Gastrointestinal Tract

description: The lateral aspect of the liver.
label: Lateral Surface of the Liver

description: The posterior aspect of the liver.
label: Posterior Surface of the Liver

description: The posterior aspect of the stomach.
label: Posterior Surface of the Stomach

description: The descending portion of the duodenum between the neck of the gallbladder and the inferior duodenal flexure.
label: Second Portion of the Duodenum

description: A dense covering of uniform microvilli located on the apical surface of certain epithelial cells, including the lining of the small intestine, which serve to increase the surface area of the cell, thereby facilitating absorption.
label: Striated Border

description: The opening from the stomach into the duodenum that is located at the end of the pyloric canal, and which is surrounded by the pyloric sphincter.
label: Pyloric Orifice

description: The superior aspect of the liver.
label: Superior Surface of the Liver

description: The curving part of the colon that is in continuity with the rectum.
label: Sigmoid Flexure

description: The perilobular lymph space located at the periphery of the hepatic lobule.
label: Space of Mall

description: The upper part of the gastrointestinal tract that includes the esophagus, stomach, and duodenum.
label: Upper Gastrointestinal Tract

description: Circularly arranged folds of the mucosa and submucosa of the small intestine, which extend into the lumen, and which function to increase the absorptive surface area. They are most prominent in the jejunum and proximal ileum, and are generally absent in the proximal duodenum and distal ileum.
label: Valve of Kerckring

description: The most distal section of the ileum that is continuous with the cecum.
label: Terminal Ileum

description: The serous membrane that covers the surface of the liver.
label: Visceral Surface of the Liver

description: The horizontal portion of the duodenum between the inferior duodenal flexure and the aorta.
label: Third Portion of the Duodenum

description: The portion of the large intestine that includes the descending and sigmoid colon.
label: Left Colon

description: The upper gastrointestinal (GI) tract is comprised of mouth, pharynx, esophagus and stomach while the lower GI tract consists of intestines and anus. The primary function of the GI tract is to ingest, digest, absorb and ultimately excrete food stuff.
label: Gastrointestinal Tract

description: The lower opening of the digestive tract, lying in the cleft between the buttocks, through which fecal matter is extruded.
label: Anus

description: The liver, gallbladder, and associated ducts, considered collectively.
label: Hepatobiliary System

description: Any of the four large divisions of the liver.
label: Liver Lobe

description: An oblong shaped area of the liver that is situated inferior to the right lobe, bounded by the anterior margin of the liver and the porta hepatis.
label: Quadrate Lobe of Liver

description: The smaller lobe of the liver extending into the left side of the body.
label: Left Lobe of the Liver

description: Couinaud segment I, located on the posterior surface of the liver between the sulcus for the vena cava and the ligamentum venosum.
label: Caudate Lobe

description: The larger lobe of the liver extending into the right side of the body.
label: Right Lobe of the Liver

description: Any of the eight liver segments that has its own vascular inflow, outflow, and biliary drainage, thus defined as functionally independent.
label: Couinaud Liver Segment

description: The medial segment of the left lobe of the liver.
label: Left Medial Segment of Liver

description: Couinaud segment II, corresponding to the lateral segment of the left lobe of the liver, located to the left of the superior portion of the falciform ligament and the fissure for the ligamentum venosum.
label: Left Posterolateral Segment

description: Couinaud segment III, corresponding to the lateral segment of the left lobe of the liver, located to the left of the inferior portion of the falciform ligament, anteriorly overlapping the stomach.
label: Left Anterolateral Segment

description: Couinaud segment IVa, corresponding to the medial segment of the left lobe of the liver, located superiorly.
label: Left Superomedial Segment

description: Couinaud segment IVb, corresponding to the medial segment of the left lobe of the liver, located inferiorly.
label: Left Inferomedial Segment

description: Couinaud segment V, corresponding to the anterior segment of the right lobe of the liver, located inferiorly.
label: Right Anteroinferior Segment

description: Couinaud segment VI, corresponding to the posterior segment of the right lobe of the liver, located inferiorly.
label: Right Posteroinferior Segment

description: Couinaud segment VII, corresponding to the posterior segment of the right lobe of the liver, located superiorly.
label: Right Posterosuperior Segment

description: Couinaud segment VIII, corresponding to the anterior segment of the right lobe of the liver, located superiorly.
label: Right Anterosuperior Segment

description: A finger-like projection of the plasma membrane found in the epithelial cells lining the intestinal tract that increase the lumen surface area.
label: Intestinal Villus

description: The distal end of a villus.
label: Villus Tip

description: The distal end of the appendix.
label: Appendiceal Tip

description: Any component of the system of muscles, tendons, ligaments, bones, joints and associated tissues that move the body and maintain its form.
label: Musculoskeletal System Part

description: The collection of bones and tissues, including ligaments and cartilage, that compose the rigid internal framework of the human body, and which serves a multitude of functions, including structural support, movement, protection, production of blood cells, storage of ions, and endocrine regulation.
label: Skeletal System

description: The bones, joints, ligaments and cartilage found in the limbs (extremities).
label: Limb Skeletal System

description: Band of fibrous tissue connecting bone to bone or cartilage to bone thereby supporting or strengthening a joint.
label: Ligament

description: Any of the round ligaments including the round ligament of the liver and the round ligament of the uterus.
label: Round Ligament

description: A fibrous tissue comprised of the remnants of the fetal umbilical vein that separates the medial and lateral sections of the left lobe of the liver.
label: Round Ligament of the Liver

description: A fibrous band extending from the uterine horn to the labium majora via the inguinal canal that maintains the uterus in an anteverted position.
label: Round Ligament of the Uterus

description: The portion of the lesser omentum between the liver and the duodenum, containing the hepatic artery, the common bile duct, the portal vein, lymphatic vessels, and the hepatic plexus of nerves.
label: Hepatoduodenal Ligament

description: A flat fibrous band extending from the apex and margins of the patella to the tubercle of the tibia.
label: Patellar Ligament

description: A major portion of the greater omentum between the stomach and the transverse colon.
label: Gastrocolic Ligament

description: A ligament present in the wrist and the ankle. In the wrist it is located over the carpus and in the ankle across the front of the leg and over the joint.
label: Anterior Annular Ligament

description: A major stabilizing ligament in the knee that attaches the surfaces of the femur and tibia.
label: Anterior Cruciate Ligament

description: A ligament running the length of the anterior surface of the spinal column and thereby interconnects all the vertebral bodies.
label: Anterior Longitudinal Ligament

description: A ligament located in the lamina propria of the marginal gingiva that encircles the tooth.
label: Circular Ligament of the Tooth

description: A ligament consisting of three distinct fasciculi including the anterior, middle and posterior fasciculi.
label: External Lateral Ligament of the Ankle

description: The portion of the greater omentum between the greater curvature of the stomach and the inferior surface of the diaphragm.
label: Gastrophrenic Ligament

description: The portion of the greater omentum between the greater curvature of the stomach and the hilum of the spleen.
label: Gastrosplenic Ligament

description: A flat, triangular fibrous tissue connected to the inner malleolus, navicular bone and ligament, os calcis and astragalus.
label: Internal Lateral Ligament of the Ankle

description: The fibrous tissues connecting the laminae of neighboring vertebrae beginning at C2 and ending at S1.
label: Ligamentum Flavum

description: The portion of the lesser omentum between the liver and the lesser curvature of the stomach.
label: Hepatogastric Ligament

description: Any of the ligaments associated with the liver.
label: Liver Ligament

description: A duel-layered fibrous band linking the posterior surface of the liver to the diaphragm.
label: Coronary Ligament

description: A broad, thin, crescent-shaped fold consisting of two layers of peritoneum extending from the notch of the anterior margin of the liver to the anterior abdominal wall and diaphragm.
label: Falciform Ligament

description: Either of the two triangular ligaments (left or right) extending from the diaphragm to the liver.
label: Lateral Ligament

description: Any of the ligaments associated with the larynx.
label: Laryngeal Ligament

description: A fibrous band linking the thyroid and cricoid cartilages anteriorly at the midline.
label: Cricothyroid Ligament

description: A fibrous band at the midline linking the first ring of the trachea with the cricoid cartilage.
label: Cricotracheal Ligament

description: The thicker sections of the fibrous membrane of the articular capsule surrounding synovial joints.
label: Capsular Ligament

description: A short elastic band that unites the epiglottis to the upper border of the hyoid bone.
label: Hyoepiglottic Ligament

description: A fibrous band extending from the cricoid to the inner, posterior border of the arytenoid cartilage.
label: Posterior Cricoarytenoid Ligament

description: A fibro-elastic band connecting the apex of the epiglottis to the thyroid cartilage just below the median thyroid notch.
label: Thyroepiglottic Ligament

description: Either of the two thyrohyoid ligaments (middle or lateral) that extend between the thyroid and the hyoid.
label: Thyrohyoid Ligament

description: A broad, fibro-elastic membrane extending from the upper border of the thyroid cartilage to the greater cornu and posterior border of the hyoid bone.
label: Middle Thyrohyoid Ligament

description: An elastic, fibrous tissue connecting the superior horn of the thyroid cartilage and the tip of the greater horn of the hyoid cartilage.
label: Lateral Thyrohyoid Ligament

description: The flat, broad band of fibrous tissue located posteriorly on the inner side of the knee, extending from the medial epicondyle of the femur to the medial margin and surface of the tibia to prevent the knee from moving medially.
label: Medial Collateral Ligament of the Knee

description: A ligament that surrounds the head of the radius.
label: Posterior Annular Ligament

description: A fibrous band extending between the posterior intercondyloid fossa of the tibia and the anterior lateral region of the medial condyle on the femur to prevent the knee from moving posteriorly.
label: Posterior Cruciate Ligament

description: A long fibrous band extending along the vertebral canal from C2 to the sacrum that interconnects the posterior surface of the vertebrae. The ligament narrows as it passes between the pedicle and widens at the intervertebral disc space to blend with the intervertebral fibrocartilage.
label: Posterior Longitudinal Ligament

description: The pelvic layer separating the deep perineal space from the upper pelvis.
label: Triangular Ligament

description: A fibrous band located on the eyelid that connects the medial ends of the tarsal plates with the maxilla at the medial edge of the orbit.
label: Medial Palpebral Ligament

description: Any of the eight ligaments pertaining to the uterus including the anterior, posterior, lateral, sacro-uterine and round ligaments.
label: Uterine Ligament

description: A wide fold of peritoneum that connects the uterus to the lateral walls and floor of the pelvis, and contains the ovaries, fallopian tubes, ovarian ligaments, round ligament of the uterus, and ovarian and uterine arteries.
label: Broad Ligament

description: The peritoneal fold that covers and attaches the ovary to the broad ligament.
label: Mesovarium

description: One of the contractile organs of the body.
label: Muscle

description: The portion of the quadriceps femoris muscle group that extends medially from the intertrochanteric line of the femur to the medial aspects of the quadriceps femoris tendon and patella.
label: Vastus Medialis Muscle

description: The portion of the quadriceps femoris muscle group that is underneath the Rectus Femoris muscle, spans and covers the upper two-thirds of the anterior and lateral surfaces of the femur, and inserts into the lateral border of the patella.
label: Vastus Intermedius Muscle

description: A small muscle that courses along the posterior aspect of the leg as part of the posterosuperficial compartment of the calf. This muscle originates from the lateral supracondylar line of the femur superior and medial to the lateral head of the gastrocnemius muscle as well as from the oblique popliteal ligament in the posterior aspect of the knee.
label: Plantaris Muscle

description: A long muscle of the neck that extends from the manubrium sterni to the mandible and branches at the middle of the neck, forming the ventral border of the jugular groove.
label: Sternocephalicus Muscle

description: Fibromuscular tissue that separates the thoracic from the abdominal cavity. It increases the volume of the thoracic cavity through contractions, thus facilitating respiration.
label: Diaphragm

description: list()
label: Dorsal Hand Interosseus Muscle

description: A dorsal interosseous muscle of the hand that originates on the proximal half of the lateral border of the index metacarpal and the full length of the medial border of the thumb metacarpal, and inserts into the lateral side of the index finger.
label: First Dorsal Interosseous Muscle of the Hand

description: A muscle that originates from the proximal two-thirds of the lateral supracondylar ridge of the humerus and inserts into the styloid process of the radius; it enables flexion of the elbow and assists with pronation and supination of the forearm.
label: Brachioradialis Muscle

description: A muscle that originates in the humeroulnar and radial heads of the forearm and inserts in the middle phalanges of the second through fifth digits of the hand; it is primarily involved in the flexion of the fingers at the proximal interphalangeal joints and is supplied by the median nerve and the ulnar artery.
label: Flexor Digitorum Superficialis Muscle

description: A muscle that originates on the anterior surface of the radius and interosseous membrane and inserts into the palmar aspect of the base of the distal phalanx of the thumb; It is involved in flexion of the thumb and is supplied by the anterior interosseous branch of the median nerve and the radial and anterior interosseous arteries.
label: Flexor Pollicis Longus Muscle

description: One of a group of four short muscles in the hand that originate on the radial and ulnar sides of the tendons of the flexor digitorum profundus and insert in the radial lateral band of the extensor expansion tendon; they are involved in the extension of the proximal and distal interphalangeal joints, and are supplied by the median and ulnar nerves and the palmar metacarpal arteries.
label: Lumbrical Muscle

description: A muscle that originates on the distal border of the flexor retinaculum and the tubercles of the scaphoid and trapezium, and inserts into the lateral aspect of the first metacarpal; it is involved in the rotation and flexion of the thumb and is supplied by the recurrent branch of the medial nerve and the superficial palmar branch of the radial artery.
label: Opponens Pollicis Muscle

description: A muscle that originates on the distal anteriomedial surface of the ulna and inserts in the distal anteriolateral surface of the radius; it is involved in the pronation of the forearm and is supplied by the anterior interosseous nerve and artery.
label: Pronator Quadratus Muscle

description: A muscle in the foot that flexes and abducts the fifth toe at the metatarsophalangeal joint and supports the lateral arch. It originates in the medial and lateral processes of the posterior calcaneal tuberosity and inserts into the lateral side of the base of the proximal phalanx of the fifth toe and the fifth metatarsal. It is innervated by the lateral planter nerve and is supplied by the lateral planter artery.
label: Abductor Digiti Minimi Muscle

description: A muscle in the foot that abducts and flexes the great toe at metatarsophalangeal joint. It originates in the medial process of the posterior calcaneal tuberosity and the flexor retinaculum and inserts into the medial side of the base of the proximal phalanx of the great toe. It is innervated by the medial plantar nerve and is supplied by the medial plantar artery.
label: Abductor Hallucis Muscle

description: A muscle in the lower extremity that adducts, flexes, and helps to rotate the thigh. It originates on the external surface of body of pubis and the anterior surface of the inferior pubic ramus and inserts in the pectineal line and the medial lip of the linea aspera. It is innervated by the anterior or posterior division of the obturator nerve and is supplied by the obturator and medial circumflex femoral arteries.
label: Adductor Brevis Muscle

description: A muscle located in the medial compartment of the thigh that adducts and medially rotates the thigh. It originates on the external surface of the pubis body and inserts into the middle third of the linea aspera. It is innervated by the obturator nerve and branches of the sciatica nerve and supplied by the obturator and medial circumflex femoral arteries.
label: Adductor Longus Muscle

description: A muscle located in the medial compartment of the thigh that adducts, flexes, extends, and medially rotates the thigh at the hip joint. It originates on the ischiopubic ramus and ischial tuberosity, and inserts into the gluteal tuberosity of the femur, medial lip of the linea aspera, medial supracondylar ridge, and adductor tubercle. It is innervated by the obturator and tibial nerves and supplied by branches of the deep femoral and popliteal arteries, and the inferior gluteal and obturator arteries.
label: Adductor Magnus Muscle

description: Two muscles located in the upper extremity, the triceps brachii and anconeus, that allow for straightening of the arm at the elbow joint.
label: Elbow Extensors

description: A group of three muscles located in the upper extremity, the brachialis, biceps brachii, and the brachioradialis, that allow for bending of the arm at the elbow joint.
label: Elbow Flexors

description: A muscle on the dorsal side of the foot that helps to extend the second, third and fourth toes. It originates on the superolateral surface of the anterior calcaneus and inserts into the lateral sides of the tendons of extensor digitorum longus on the second, third and fourth toes. It is innervated by the deep peroneal nerve and supplied by the dorsalis pedis artery.
label: Extensor Digitorum Brevis Muscle

description: A muscle on the dorsal side of the foot that helps to extend the big toe. It originates on the superior surface of the anterior calcaneus and inserts into the dorsal surface of the base of the proximal phalanx of the big toe. It is innervated by the deep fibular nerve and supplied by the dorsalis pedis artery.
label: Extensor Hallucis Brevis Muscle

description: A group of muscles that originate on the bones on the posterior side of the forearm and insert into the bones of the phalanges through long tendons. The finger extensors, including the abductor pollicis longus, extensor pollicis brevis, extensor pollicis longus, extensor indicis, extensor digitorum, and extensor digiti minimi muscles, allow for straightening of the fingers to open the hand.
label: Finger Extensors

description: A group of muscles that originate on the bones on the palmar side of the arm and forearm and insert into the bones of the phalanges of the hand through long tendons; the finger flexors, including the flexor digitorum superficialis, flexor digitorum profundus, and flexor pollicis longus muscles, allow for bending of the fingers.
label: Finger Flexors

description: A muscle in the foot that allows flexion of the four lateral toes and supports the medial and lateral longitudinal arches. It originates on the medial process of the posterior calcaneal tuberosity and inserts as tendons into the borders of the middle phalanx of the four lateral toes. It is innervated by the medial plantar nerve and supplied by the medial and lateral plantar arteries.
label: Flexor Digitorum Brevis Muscle

description: A muscle of the hand, in general extending from the pisiform bone, the pisohamate ligament, and the flexor retinaculum to the ulnopalmar margin of the proximal phalanx. Primary function is abduction of the little finger and flexion of the phalanx nearest the hand.
label: Abductor Digiti Minimi Muscle of the Hand

description: A muscle of the hand, in general extending from the flexor retinaculum and the tubercles of the scaphoid and trapezium bones to the outer side of the base of the proximal phalanx of the thumb. Primary function is abduction of the thumb away from the palm.
label: Abductor Pollicis Brevis Muscle

description: A muscle in the foot that is involved in the flexion of the first toe and the support of the medial longitudinal arch. It originates on the plantar surface of the cuboid bone and inserts into the medial and lateral sesamoid bones at the base of the proximal phalanx of the first toe. It is innervated by the medial plantar nerve and supplied by the medial plantar artery.
label: Flexor Hallucis Brevis Muscle

description: A group of muscles located in the posterior compartment of the forearm that allow dorsiflexion of the wrist, as well as other movements of the wrist and fingers. The wrist extensors, including the extensor carpi radialis longus, extensor carpi radialis brevis, extensor digitorum, extensor digiti minimi, extensor carpi ulnaris, extensor indicis, extensor pollicis longus, extensor pollicis brevis, and abductor pollicis longus muscles, originate on the posterior ulna and radius, and the distal humerus, and insert into the backs of the carpals, metacarpals and phalanges.
label: Wrist Joint Extensor Muscles

description: A group of muscles located in the anterior compartment of the forearm that allow plantar flexion of the wrist, as well as other movements of the wrist and fingers. The wrist flexors, including the flexor carpi radialis, palmaris longus, flexor carpi ulnaris, flexor digitorum superficialis, flexor digitorum profundus, and flexor pollicis longus muscles, originate on the medial distal humerus or anterior ulna and radius, and insert into the anterior surfaces of the carpals, metacarpals and phalanges.
label: Wrist Joint Flexor Muscles

description: A group of muscles that function to extend the ankle, flexing the foot downward toward the sole, and includes the gastrocnemius, soleus, plantaris, tibialis posterior, flexor hallucis longus, and flexor digitorum longus muscles.
label: Plantar Flexor Muscles

description: A muscle in the back that originates from the spinous processes of the second to fifth thoracic vertebrae and attaches to the medial border of the scapula; along with the rhomboid minor muscle, it functions to stabilize and retract the scapula.
label: Rhomboid Major Muscle

description: A muscle in the back that originates from the nuchal ligament and spinal processes of the seventh cervical and first thoracic vertebrae and attaches to the medial border of the scapula; along with the rhomboid major muscle, it functions to stabilize and retract the scapula.
label: Rhomboid Minor Muscle

description: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the posterior proximal shaft of ulna and the lateral epicondyle of humerus and attaches to the proximal third of the radius on the anterolateral and posterior surface; it functions to supinate the forearm.
label: Supinator Muscle

description: A muscle of the hand that extends from the capitate and bases of the second and third metacarpals for the oblique head, and the anterior surface of body of the third metacarpal for the transverse head, to the base of proximal phalanx and extensor hood of the thumb; primary function is to draw the first metacarpal laterally to oppose the thumb toward the center of palm and rotate it medially.
label: Adductor Pollicis Muscle

description: A small muscle in the posterior elbow that originates from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and attaches to the lateral surface of the olecranon of the ulna; it functions to extend the forearm and stabilize the elbow joint.
label: Anconeus Muscle

description: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and attaches to the extensor expansion of the fifth digit; it functions to extend the fifth digit at the metacarpophalangeal joint.
label: Extensor Digiti Minimi Muscle

description: A muscle in the lower extremity that originates from the middle third of the medial surface of the fibula and the adjacent interosseous membrane and attaches to the base and dorsal center of the distal phalanx of the great toe; it functions to extend the big toe and dorsiflex the ankle.
label: Extensor Hallucis Longus Muscle

description: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the posterior surface of the ulna and attaches to the base of the second proximal phalanx and the tendon of the extensor digitorum muscle; it functions to extend the second digit at metacarpophalangeal and interphalangeal joints.
label: Extensor Indicis Proprius Muscle

description: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the posterior surface of distal third of radius and the adjacent interosseous membrane and attaches to the posterior surface of the base of the proximal phalanx of the thumb; it functions to extend the thumb at the carpometacarpal and metacarpophalangeal joints.
label: Extensor Pollicis Brevis Muscle

description: A muscle in the posterior forearm that originates from the posterior surface of the middle third of the ulna and the adjacent interosseous membrane and attaches to the posterior surface of the base of distal phalanx of the thumb; it functions to extend the thumb at the metacarpophalangeal and interphalangeal joints and extend and abduct the wrist joint.
label: Extensor Pollicis Longus Muscle

description: A muscle in the hand that has a superficial head that originates from the flexor retinaculum and tubercle of the trapezium bone and a deep head that originates from the trapezoid and capitate bones; it attaches to the lateral side of the base of the proximal phalanx of the thumb and functions to flex the thumb at the metacarpophalangeal joint.
label: Flexor Pollicis Brevis Muscle

description: A group of muscles that function to rotate the forearm so that the palm faces downward when the arm is extended at a right angle to the body, including the brachioradialis, pronator teres, pronator quadratus, and flexor carpi radialis.
label: Forearm Pronator Muscles

description: A group of muscles that function to move the leg or knee towards the torso and assist with bending at the waist, including the psoas major, iliacus, rectus femoris, pectineus, and sartorius.
label: Hip Flexor Muscles

description: A group of muscles that function to flex the knee, including the sartorius, popliteus, gastrocnemius, gracilis, semi-tendinosis, semi-membranosis, and bicep femoris muscles.
label: Knee Flexor Muscles

description: A group muscles in the sole of the foot that originate from the tendons of the flexor digitorum longus muscle and attach to the medial bases of the proximal phalanges and the extensor expansion of the second through fifth digits; they function to flex and adduct the lateral four toes at the metatarsophalangeal joints and extend them at the interphalangeal joints.
label: Lumbrical Muscles of the Foot

description: A short muscle in the lateral compartment of the lower leg that originates on the distal two-thirds of the lateral surface of the fibula and the anterior intermuscular septum, attaches to the tuberosity of the fifth metatarsal bone, and functions to plantar flex and evert the foot.
label: Peroneus Brevis Muscle

description: A muscle group in the hand that controls radial extension and abduction or deviation of the wrist; either the extensor carpi radialis brevis muscle, which originates at the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and inserts at the third metacarpal bone, or the extensor carpi radialis longus muscle, which originates at the lateral supracondylar ridge of the humerus and inserts at the back base of the second metacarpal bone.
label: Extensor Carpi Radialis Muscles

description: A group of muscles in the shoulder, the supraspinatus, deltoid, trapezius, and serratus anterior muscles; primary function is to abduct the shoulder.
label: Shoulder Abductor Muscles

description: A group of muscles in the knee, the rectus femoris, vastus lateralis, vastus medius, and vastus intermedius muscles; primary function is to extend the knee.
label: Knee Extensor Muscles

description: A group of muscles in the hip, the gluteus medius, gluteus minimus, tensor fasciae latae, piriformis, sartorius, and gluteus maximus muscles; primary function is to abduct the hip.
label: Hip Abductor Muscles

description: A group of muscles in the hip, the gracilis, obturator externus, adductor brevis, adductor longus and adductor magnus muscles; primary function is to adduct the hip.
label: Hip Adductor Muscles

description: A group of muscles in the neck, the trapezius, splenius capitis, splenius cervicis, semispinalis capitis, and semispinalis cervicis muscles; primary function is to extend the neck.
label: Neck Extensor Muscles

description: A group of muscles in the shoulder, the infraspinatus, supraspinatus, subscapularis, and teres minor muscles; primary function is to externally rotate the shoulder.
label: Shoulder External Rotator Muscles

description: A group of muscles in the hip, the gluteus maximus, adductor magnus, semitendinosus, semimembranosus, and the biceps femoris muscles; primary function is to extend the hip.
label: Hip Extensor Muscles

description: A group of muscles in the ankle, the tibialis anterior and extensor hallucis longus muscles; primary function is to dorsiflex the ankle.
label: Ankle Dorsiflexor Muscles

description: A thin layer of fibrous tissue of the anterior abdominal wall between the inner surface of the transversus abdominis muscle and the parietal peritoneum.
label: Transversalis

description: One of a pair of flat, large, triangular muscles that extend from the external occipital protuberance and the medial third of the superior nuchal line of the occipital bone to the middle of the back. The trapezius muscle is involved in moving the shoulder and arm.
label: Trapezius Muscle

description: Muscles of the upper chest. The term may refer to one of two muscles, the pectoralis major and pectoralis minor. The former is a thick muscle in the anterior portion of the chest. Its action involves flexion, medial rotation, and adduction of the humerus. The latter is a thin muscle located beneath the pectoralis major. Its action involves lowering the scapula and raising the ribs.
label: Pectoralis Muscle

description: Either of two large, bilateral muscles overlying the upper, anterior chest wall, which has two heads: the clavicular head, which originates on the medial half of the clavicle, and the sternal head, which originates on the sternum and the first six costal cartilages; the muscles insert onto the lateral lip of the intertubercular groove of the humerus and the crest of the greater tubercle of the humerus respectively, and function to flex, adduct, and medially rotate the shoulder joint.
label: Pectoralis Major

description: Either of two small, triangular, bilateral muscles located inferior the pectoralis major muscle, which originate from the third to fifth ribs near their costal cartilages and inserting on the medial border and superior surface of the coracoid process of the scapula, and which function to stabilize the scapula against the thoracic wall.
label: Pectoralis Minor

description: A large muscle in the back of the lower leg. Its action involves the plantar flexion of the foot.
label: Gastrocnemius Muscle

description: A muscle that inserts directly onto the capsule of a joint, acting to retract the capsule in certain movements.
label: Articular Muscle

description: A circular band of muscle that functions to regulate the size of an orifice in the body.
label: Sphincter

description: A smooth muscle of the eye encircling the iris; it is one of two intrinsic pupillary muscles that work in concert to control the size of the pupil.
label: Sphincter Pupillae Muscle

description: A muscle surrounding the cloacal membrane in the developing embryo; the posterior part forms the external anal sphincter.
label: Cloacal Sphincter

description: Any of the muscles of the abdomen that comprise the abdominal wall; these muscles include the rectus abdominis, the external and internal oblique muscles, the transversus abdominis, and the quadratus abdominis.
label: Abdominal Muscle

description: The group of muscles in the torso that are closest to the spine and furthest from the skin such as the psoas muscle and the quadratus lumborum.
label: Deep Abdominal Muscle

description: A triangular muscle within the iliac fossa that flexes the thigh and rotates the leg medially.
label: Iliacus

description: Muscles of the lower back whose actions involve the flexion of the hips and lumbar spine. The term may refer to psoas major muscle and psoas minor muscle, both located in the lower back.
label: Psoas Muscle

description: A striated muscle located in the iliac region that originates both on the transverse processes of the twelfth thoracic through fifth lumbar vertebrae and the lateral aspects of the discs between them, and inserts on the lesser trochanter of the femur; it functions to flex the hip joint.
label: Psoas Major Muscle

description: A long, thin striated muscle located in the iliac region anterior to the psoas major muscle that originates from the twelfth thoracic and first lumbar vertebrae, and inserts on the pectineal line and ileopubic eminence; it acts as a weak flexor of the trunk.
label: Psoas Minor Muscle

description: A rectangular-shaped muscle of the posterior abdominal wall that takes its origin from the iliac crest and iliolumbar ligament, and inserts on the last rib and transverse processes of the first four lumbar vertebrae; it functions to flex the vertebral column, and also acts as a muscle of inspiration.
label: Quadratus Lumborum Muscle

description: The muscles, composed of the levator ani and the coccygeus muscles, that create a division between the pelvic cavity and the perineal region.
label: Pelvic Floor Muscle

description: A muscle of the pelvic diaphragm located posterior the levator ani muscle, which arises from the ischial spine and inserts into the coccyx and lowest area of the sacrum, and functions to raise and support the pelvic floor.
label: Coccygeal Muscle

description: A broad, thin muscle originating form the posterior side of the pubis body, spine of the ischium, and pelvic fascia between the pubis and ischium on either side of the pelvis. Both muscles unite and insert at the apex of the coccyx to form the pelvic floor supporting the pelvic viscera and aiding in defecation.
label: Levator Ani

description: Any one of the anterior or anterolateral abdominal wall muscles, including the cremaster muscle, pyramidalis muscle, external oblique, internal oblique, transversus abdominis, and rectus abdominis muscles.
label: Superficial Abdominal Muscle

description: A thin skeletal muscle enveloping the testis and the spermatic cord, which originates from the internal oblique and inguinal ligament, inserts into the cremasteric fascia and pubic tubercle, and functions to raise and lower the testes.
label: Cremaster Muscle

description: An opening in the aponeurosis of the external oblique muscle of the abdominal wall through which the spermatic cord (males), round ligament (females), ilioinguinal nerve, and genitofemoral nerve's genital branch pass.
label: External Abdominal Ring

description: The largest and most superficial muscle on the lateral side of the anterior abdomen which compresses the abdomen and pulls the chest downward.
label: External Oblique Muscle

description: An opening in the transversalis fascia midway between the anterior superior iliac spine and pubic tubercle through which the spermatic cord (males) or round ligament (females) pass.
label: Internal Abdominal Ring

description: A large thin muscle beneath the external oblique that stretches from the iliac crest to the inferior borders of the tenth to twelfth ribs and the abdominal midline which act to bend the upper trunk forward.
label: Internal Oblique Muscle

description: A small, triangular-shaped muscle that is enclosed in the rectus sheath anterior to the rectus abdominis; it takes its origin from the pubic symphysis and pubic crest, inserts on the linea alba, and functions to tense the linea alba.
label: Pyramidalis Muscle

description: Two vertically parallel muscles located on the anterior abdominal wall, which originate on the pubic crest and insert on the coastal cartilages of ribs five through seven and the xyphoid process; both muscles function to flex the lumbar spine.
label: Rectus Abdominis Muscle

description: An anterolateral muscle of the abdomen which attaches to the thoracolumbar fascia, iliac crest, inguinal ligament, and the costal cartilages of the lower ribs, and which continues anteriorly as the transverse abdominis aponeurosis, which inserts into the linea alba, the pubic crest, and the pectineal line.
label: Transversus Abdominis Muscle

description: A muscle located in the anterior aspect of the abdominal wall.
label: Anterior Abdominal Wall Muscle

description: A muscle in the upper arm. Its action involves the rotation of the arm and the flexing of the elbow.
label: Biceps Brachii

description: A ring of smooth muscle consisting of circular and radiating fibers within the middle layer of the eye. The ciliary muscle is innervated by both the parasympathetic and sympathetic nervous systems and acts to control the flow of aqueous humour into Schlemm's canal and changes the shape of the eye lens.
label: Ciliary Muscle

description: list()
label: Cutaneous Muscle

description: The small bundles of smooth muscle connected to hair follicles that cause the hair to stand straight creating 'goose bumps.'
label: Erector Muscle of the Hair

description: The muscle that creates the rounded contour of the shoulder which originates from the lateral third of the clavicle, the superior surface of the acromion process, and the posterior border of the spine of the scapula and inserts on the lateral side of the shaft of the humerus. The deltoid muscle is innervated by the brachial plexus arising from the fifth and sixth cervical nerves and controls abduction, extension, flexion, and rotation of the arm.
label: Deltoid

description: The muscle that creates the rounded contour of the shoulder which originates from the lateral third of the clavicle, the superior surface of the acromion process, and the posterior border of the spine of the scapula and inserts on the lateral side of the shaft of the humerus. The deltoid muscle is innervated by the brachial plexus arising from the fifth and sixth cervical nerves and controls abduction, extension, flexion, and rotation of the arm. This is the deltoid on the left side of the body.
label: Left Deltoid

description: The muscle that creates the rounded contour of the shoulder which originates from the lateral third of the clavicle, the superior surface of the acromion process, and the posterior border of the spine of the scapula and inserts on the lateral side of the shaft of the humerus. The deltoid muscle is innervated by the brachial plexus arising from the fifth and sixth cervical nerves and controls abduction, extension, flexion, and rotation of the arm. This is the deltoid on the right side of the body.
label: Right Deltoid

description: A muscle located between two ribs.
label: Intercostal Muscle

description: The most superficial of the three intercostal muscles (external, internal, innermost) found in the intercostal space, which aid in both active and passive inhalation.
label: External Intercostal Muscle

description: Eleven pairs of skeletal muscle located between the ribs, which occupy the middle layer in the intercostal space, and function to move the ribs inferiorly.
label: Internal Intercostal Muscle

description: A muscle located on the posterior aspect of the trunk.
label: Dorsal Muscle of the Back

description: Any skeletal muscled located in the head or neck.
label: Head and Neck Muscle

description: A skeletal muscle located under the skin of the face that is supplied by the facial nerve and controls facial expression.
label: Facial Muscle

description: One of two small facial muscles that are located behind the occipitofrontalis and orbicularis oculis muscles, with which they blend, and allow movement of the eyebrows. They originate in the medial superciliary arch and insert into the skin above the middle of the supraorbital margins. They are innervated by the temporal branch of the facial nerve and supplied by branches from the superficial temporal and ophthalmic arteries.
label: Corrugator Supercilii Muscle

description: A pyramid-shaped muscle in the face that allows movement of the skin between the eyebrows. It originates on the lower part of the nasal bone and inserts into the frontalis muscle in the forehead. It is innervated by branches of the facial nerve and supplied by the facial artery.
label: Procerus Muscle

description: A muscle of facial expression that originates on the zygomatic arch and inserts into the fibers of the modiolus of the mouth, with innervation by the facial nerve, specifically the buccal and zygomatic branches, which functions to draw the angle of the mouth superiorly and posteriorly, allowing an individual to smile.
label: Zygomaticus Major Muscle

description: A muscle of facial expression that originates on the malar bone and inserts into the skin and muscle of the upper lip, with innervation by the facial nerve, which functions to elevate and evert the upper lip.
label: Zygomaticus Minor Muscle

description: The muscles that form the walls of the pharynx, including the inferior, middle, and superior constrictors, salpingopharyngeus, and stylopharyngeus.
label: Pharyngeal Muscles

description: A pharyngeal muscle located in the neck between the superior and inferior pharyngeal constrictor muscles, which originates on the hyoid bone, inserts on the pharyngeal raphe, and assists in the act of swallowing.
label: Middle Constrictor Muscle

description: A muscle originating from the outer sides of the thyroid and cricoid cartilages that is inserted into the pharyngeal raphe in the posterior portion of the wall of the pharynx and is innervated by the pharyngeal plexus. The cricopharyngeus muscle aids in swallowing by narrowing the lower part of the pharynx to move a bolus into the esophagus.
label: Cricopharyngeus Muscle

description: A pharyngeal levator muscle, which arises from the cartilage of the pharyngotympanic tube and passes inferiorly within the salpingopharyngeal fold to join with the palatopharyngeus muscle; it functions to elevate the pharyngeal walls.
label: Salpingopharyngeus Muscle

description: A long, thin pharyngeal muscle, which originates on the styloid process with some fibers attaching to the constrictors and the lateral glossoepiglottic fold, while others attach to the thyroid cartilage; it functions to elevate the pharynx and larynx.
label: Stylopharyngeus Muscle

description: The uppermost of the three constrictor muscles of the pharynx.  It receives nerve supply from the pharyngeal plexus.
label: Superior Constrictor Muscle

description: Paired muscles on both sides of the face (Zygomaticus major and Zygomaticus minor) extending from the zygomatic bone to the corners of the mouth/upper lip; primary function is to draw the lip superiorly, posteriorly and laterally.
label: Zygomaticus Muscle

description: A muscle in the forehead that originates from the galea aponeurotica at the top of the skull and attaches to the skin around the eyebrows and the top of the nose; it functions to raise the eyebrows and wrinkle the forehead.
label: Frontalis Muscle

description: A paired facial muscle that originates from the incisive fossa of the mandible and extends upward to attach to the skin of the lower lip; it functions to elevate and protrude the lower lip and elevate and wrinkle the skin of the chin.
label: Mentalis Muscle

description: A smooth muscle of the eye encircling the iris, which is one of two intrinsic pupillary muscles that work together to control the size of the pupil.
label: Dilator Pupillae Muscle

description: Muscles arising in the zygomatic arch that close the jaw.
label: Muscle of Mastication

description: A muscle of mastication originating from the zygomatic arch.
label: Masseter Muscle

description: A two headed (inferior and superior) muscle attached to the mandible that opens the jaw and brings it forward.
label: External Pterygoid Muscle

description: A quadrilateral muscle extending from the lateral pterygoid plate to the medial surface of the mandible that closes the jaw and aids in mastication.
label: Internal Pterygoid Muscle

description: A fan-shaped muscle of mastication that originates from and fills the temporal fossa, and inserts on the coronoid process of the mandible; it functions to elevate and retract the mandible.
label: Temporal Muscle

description: Either one of the two muscles located in the middle ear: the tensor tympani or the stapedius muscle.
label: Muscle of the Tympanum

description: One of the muscles of the middle ear, and the smallest muscle in the body, which takes its origin from the wall of the pyramidal eminence on the posterior wall of the tympanic cavity, and inserts on the posterior surface of the neck of the stapes; it functions to dampen excessive sound vibrations.
label: Stapedius Muscle

description: A small, thin muscle of the tympanum located in the middle ear that arises from the pharyngotympanic tube and attaches to the handle of the malleus; it helps to dampen sound vibrations by tensing the tympanic membrane.
label: Tensor Tympani Muscle

description: Any one of the neck or facial muscles controlling movement of the nose.
label: Nasal Muscle

description: Any skeletal muscle located in the neck.
label: Neck Muscle

description: A superficial neck muscle and a key anatomical landmark, which divides the neck into anterior and lateral regions. It originates on the manubrium and the clavicle, and inserts onto the mastoid process and the superior nuchal line. It functions to flex the neck, move the chin cranially, and assists in elevating the rib cage during inspiration.
label: Sternocleidomastoid Muscle

description: A small, striated muscle located under the mandible. It arises from the mastoid process and extends to the symphysis menti, and functions to lower the mandible and elevation of the hyoid bone.
label: Digastric Muscle

description: One of a group of neck muscles attached to the hyoid bone used in mastication and swallowing, which are classified as either suprahyoid muscles, the stylohyoid, digastric, mylohyoid, and geniohyoid, or infrahyoid muscles, the omohyoid, sternohyoid, thyrohyoid, and sternothyroid.
label: Hyoid Muscle

description: A broad, fan-shaped muscle located in the superficial fascia of the neck, extending superiorly from the inferior border of the mandible and inferiorly to the clavicle and the fascia of the anterior shoulder and thorax, that functions to depresses the mandible and wrinkle the skin of neck.
label: Platysma Myoides Muscle

description: Any one of three pairs of vertebral muscles (anterior, middle, and posterior scalenes), which attach to the transverse process of the five lower cervical vertebrae and the first two ribs, and which function to elevate the ribs during breathing and to laterally flex the neck.
label: Scalene Muscle

description: Any of the eight intrinsic muscles of the larynx; five for the vocal cords and three connecting to the epiglottis.
label: Laryngeal Muscle

description: A band of muscular fibers of the oblique arytenoid muscle that extends from the summit of the arytenoid cartilage to the side of the epiglottis and whose action constricts the laryngeal aperture.
label: Aryepiglottic Muscle

description: A muscle that arises from the arytenoid cartilage of one side of the larynx and inserts to the arytenoid cartilage of the opposite site.
label: Arytenoid Muscle

description: A pair of muscles, the lateral cricoarytenoid and the posterior cricoarytenoid, that connect the cricoid cartilage and arytenoid cartilage. The posterior cricoarytenoid is the sole abductor of the vocal folds. The lateral cricoarytenoid is the main antagonist of the posterior cricoarytenoid.
label: Cricoarytenoid Muscle

description: A muscle originating from the cricoid arch on the anterior surface in which the posterior section runs outward to the thyroid's inferior horn and the anterior section runs upward to the thyroid's ala. The cricothyroid muscle is innervated by the superior laryngeal nerve's external branch and acts to tense the vocal cords thus altering voice pitch.
label: Cricothyroid Muscle

description: An intrinsic muscle of the larynx that originates on the thyroid cartilage with insertion on the arytenoid cartilage; it functions to regulate the tension of the vocal ligaments along with other intrinsic laryngeal muscles.
label: Thyroarytenoid Muscle

description: Fibers of the thyroarytenoid muscle that are prolonged into the epiglottic margin; it functions to modify the laryngeal inlet along with other intrinsic laryngeal muscles.
label: Thyroepiglottic Muscle

description: A skeletal muscle belonging to the infrahyoid muscle group, located in the anterior part of the neck, with its origin on the thyroid cartilage and  its insertion on the hyoid bone; it functions to depress the hyoid bone and elevate the larynx during swallowing and speaking.
label: Thyrohyoid Muscle

description: A striated muscle of the scalp comprised of a frontal and occipital belly, extending from the superior nuchal line posteriorly to the skin of the eyebrows anteriorly and inserting into the epicranial aponeurosis, which functions to move the scalp and wrinkle the forehead.
label: Occipito-Frontalis Muscle

description: A group of extrinsic muscles that are responsible for moving the eye and lifting the eyelid. These include: superior rectus, inferior rectus, medial rectus, inferior oblique, and levator palpebrae superioris, all innervated by CN III (oculomotor nerve), superior oblique, innervated by CN IV (trochlear nerve), lateral rectus, innervated by CN VI (abducens nerve).
label: Extraocular Muscle

description: One of the extraoculomotor muscles, which arises from a common tendinous ring in the posterior portion of the orbit, inserts on the anterior globe, is innervated by CN III, and functions to depress and adduct the eye.
label: Inferior Rectus Muscle

description: A thin muscle attached to the bottom portions of the eye and orbit that primarily rotates the eye laterally but can also elevate and abduct the eye.
label: Inferior Oblique Muscle

description: A muscle attaching to the lateral surface of the orbit that abducts the eye.
label: Lateral Rectus Muscle

description: One of the extraoculomotor muscles arising from a common tendinous ring in the posterior part of the orbit with insertion on the medial surface of the sclera, which is innervated by the inferior division of CN III, and functions to adduct the eye.
label: Medial Rectus Muscle

description: A muscle extending from the optic canal to the upper portion of the orbit that primarily rotates the eye medially but can also depress and abduct the eye.
label: Superior Oblique Muscle

description: One of the extraoculomotor muscles, which arises from a common tendinous ring in the posterior portion of the orbit, inserts on the upper part of the sclera, is innervated by CN III, and functions to elevate, adduct, and medially rotate the eye.
label: Superior Rectus Muscle

description: A thin, flat, triangular muscle originating from the lesser wing of the sphenoid above and in front of the optic canal and inserts at the upper margin of the superior tarsal plate to elevate the upper eye lid.
label: Levator Palpebrae Superioris

description: Any of the small muscles having an origin or insertion on the soft palate or palatine aponeurosis, including the levator veli palatini, musculus uvulae, palatoglossus, palatopharyngeus, and tensor veli palatini muscle.
label: Palatal Muscle

description: Any of the intrinsic or extrinsic muscles of the tongue.
label: Tongue Muscle

description: The intrinsic muscles spanning the length of the tongue that move the tip of the tonge up and down.
label: Intrinsic Tongue Muscle Transverse Component

description: The intrinsic muscles spanning the width of the tongue that depress and flatten the tongue.
label: Intrinsic Tongue Muscle Vertical Component

description: The muscle in the orbit of the eye that lifts the upper eyelid.
label: Eyelid Muscle

description: A vestigial smooth muscle bridging the inferior orbital fissure at the posterior the orbit.
label: Orbitalis Muscle

description: A muscle extending from the hyoid bone to the side of the tongue that retracts and pulls the side of the tongue downward.
label: Hyoglossus Muscle

description: A thin, quadrilateral muscle originating at the lower margin of the orbit and attaching to the muscles of the upper lip to elevate the lip.
label: Levator Labii Superioris

description: A muscle originating from the transverse processes of the upper thoracic vertebrae and the articular processes of the lower cervical vertebrae which inserts into the mastoid process acting to keep the head upright and to move it backward or to one side.
label: Longissimus Capitis

description: A muscle originating for the transverse processes of the upper thoracic vertebrae which inserts into the transverse process of the upper and middle cervical vertebrae acting to extend the cervical spine.
label: Longissimus Cervicis

description: A palatal muscle with origin on the palatine aponeurosis and insertion on the tongue, serving to elevate the tongue and close the oropharyngeal isthmus, which aids in swallowing.
label: Palatoglossus Muscle

description: Either of the two superficial, posterior vertebral muscles located in the neck and upper thorax: the splenius capitis (cranial portion) or splenius cervicis (cervical portion). Together these muscles extend the head and neck.
label: Splenius Muscle Group

description: The lateral portion of the erector spinae muscle in the back with three subdivisions: the iliocostalis cervicis, the iliocostalis lumborum and the iliocostalis thoracis.
label: Iliocostal Muscle

description: A combination of two muscles found in the thigh, the iliacus and the psoas major, which have different sites of origin but a common insertion on the lesser trochanter of the femur.
label: Iliopsoas Muscle

description: Any of a number of muscles that attach to the coccyx, including the pubococcygeus, ileococcygeuys, coccygeus muscles.
label: Muscle of the Coccyx

description: A triangular muscle in the back, connected to the vertebral column, arm, and shoulder. Its action involves adduction, medial rotation, and extension of the arm.
label: Musculus Latissimus Dorsi

description: Any one of the of the superficial (ischiocavernosus, bulbospongiosus, superficial transverse perineal muscles) or deep (deep transverse perineal muscle, sphincter urethrae muscle) muscles located in the perineum.
label: Perineal Muscle

description: A superficial muscle located in the midline of the perineum and anterior to the anus. It covers the bulb of the penis in males and the vestibular bulb in females. The origin and insertion differs between males and females.
label: Bulbospongiosus

description: One of two muscles located in the pelvis: the obturator externus muscle or the obturator internus muscle.
label: Obturator Muscle

description: A striated muscle located on the anterior surface of the pelvis, with its origin on the obturator foramen and obturatory membrane and insertion on the trochanteric fossa of the femur, which functions to laterally rotate the femur.
label: Obturator Externus Muscle

description: A striated muscle covering the majority of the lateral wall of the pelvis, with its origin on the ischiopubic ramus and obturator membrane and insertion on the greater trochanter, which functions to externally rotate the hip.
label: Obturator Internus Muscle

description: Any one of the group of small muscles located in the ventricles of the heart that insert onto the ventricular wall and are continuous at the opposite end with the chordae tendineae, which insert onto the free edge of the atrioventricular valves, functioning to keep the valves closed during ventricular systole.
label: Papillary Muscle

description: A flat muscle located in the posterior compartment of the lower leg, which forms the floor of the lower part of the popliteal fossa, and originates on the lateral femoral epicondyle, with insertion on the posterior surface of the tibia, and which functions to rotate the tibia medially on the femur or, when the tibia is fixed, rotates the femur laterally on the tibia and provides dynamic stability to the posterolateral part of the knee.
label: Popliteus Muscle

description: A long, thin striated muscle of the anterior compartment of the thigh, which takes its origin from the anterior superior iliac spine of the pelvic bone, and inserts on the anteromedial surface of the upper tibia in the pes anserinus; it functions to flex, abduct, and laterally rotate the thigh at the hip joint, and to flex the leg at the knee joint.
label: Sartorius Muscle

description: A large muscle of the axial skeleton, with origin from the first through the eighth or ninth rib, and insertion on the scapula, which is responsible for multiple arm movements, including anteversion of the arm, protraction of the scapula, and stabilization of the scapula against the thoracic wall.
label: Serratus Anterior Muscle

description: A small muscle located between the clavicle and the first rib, which arises from the first rib and has its insertion onto the subclavian groove of the clavicle; it functions to move the clavicle inferiorly.
label: Subclavius Muscle

description: A group of four powerful muscles in the front of the thigh. Their actions involve the extension of the knee joint.
label: Quadriceps Muscle of the Thigh

description: One of the four quadriceps muscles, located in the middle of the front of the thigh. Its actions involve the extension of the knee joint and flexion of the hip.
label: Rectus Femoris

description: A skeletal muscle of the limb comprised of three muscular bundles called the heads that originate seperately and join together.
label: Triceps

description: A pair of muscles in the posterior compartment of the lower leg comprising the soleus and the gastrocnemius muscles, the main function of which is plantar flexion of the foot. The soleus arises from the posterior tibia, whilst the gastrocnemius arises from the distal femur; both muscles insert into the calcaneus via the calcaneal tendon (Achilles).
label: Triceps Surae Muscle

description: The muscle of the upper arm that extends the forearm.
label: Triceps Brachii

description: Any one of three cylindrical shaped muscles located in the upper limb: pronator teres, teres major, and teres minor.
label: Teres Muscle

description: A thick scapulohumeral muscle of the upper limb arising from the inferior angle of the scapula with insertion on the medial lip of the intertubercular sulcus of the humerus; it functions to medially rotate the humerus.
label: Teres Major Muscle

description: One of four rotator cuff muscles that form a musculotendinous cuff around the glenohumeral joint, which provides muscular support to the shoulder; it arises from the lateral border of the scapula with insertion on the greater tubercle of the humerus, and functions to laterally rotate the humerus.
label: Teres Minor Muscle

description: A muscle of the superficial flexor compartment of the forearm, which originates on both the humeral and ulnar heads and inserts on the body of the radius, that functions to pronate the arm and flex the elbow.
label: Pronator Teres Muscle

description: A skeletal muscle belonging to the infrahyoid muscle group, located in the anterior part of the neck, with its origin on the sternum and its insertion on the hyoid bone; it functions to depress the hyoid bone and larynx during swallowing and speaking.
label: Sternohyoid Muscle

description: The thin layer of smooth muscle surrounding the scrotum which contracts or expands the scrotal skin to regulate testicular temperature.
label: Dartoic Muscle

description: Three small muscles, located on the second, fourth, and fifth fingers, on the palmar surfaces of the metacarpal bones facilitating the adduction, flexion and extension of the fingers.
label: Palmar Hand Interosseus Muscle

description: list()
label: Urethralis

description: A ring-like band of skeletal muscle on the palpebrae, temple, cheeks, and surrounding the orbit, which originates on the frontal bone, medial palpebral ligament, and lacrimal bone with insertion on the lateral palpebral raphe, that functions to close the eyelid.
label: Orbicularis Oculi Muscle

description: A skeletal muscle of the forearm originating from the posterior surfaces of the ulna and radius and the interosseous membrane.
label: Abductor Pollicis Longus

description: The thin skeletal muscle within the subcutaneous tissue.
label: Cutaneous Trunci

description: list()
label: Sternooccipital

description: A skeletal muscle belonging to the infrahyoid muscle group, located in the anterior part of the neck, with its origin on the sternum and its insertion on the thyroid cartilage; it functions to depress the hyoid bone and larynx during swallowing and speaking.
label: Sternothyroid Muscle

description: A small muscle of the tongue, which originates from the styloid process and inserts on to the side of the tongue; it functions to elevate and retract the tongue.
label: Styloglossus Muscle

description: A muscle of the gluteal region that arises from the iliac crest and inserts into the iliotibial tract of the fascia lata; it functions to stabilize the knee in extension and in hip flexion.
label: Tensor Fasciae Lata

description: The largest muscle in the quadriceps femoris that is responsible for extending and stabilizing the knee.
label: Vastus Lateralis

description: The largest muscle in the quadriceps femoris that is responsible for extending and stabilizing the knee located on the left side of the body.
label: Left Vastus Lateralis

description: The largest muscle in the quadriceps femoris that is responsible for extending and stabilizing the knee located on the right side of the body.
label: Right Vastus Lateralis

description: A muscle located in the back of the lower leg beneath the gastrocnemius muscle. Its actions involve the flexion of the ankle joint and standing.
label: Soleus

description: Referencing either the anterior tibialis muscle or the posterior tibialis muscle, which are muscles of the lower leg.
label: Tibialis Muscle

description: A muscle that originates from the lateral condyle of tibia, spans the upper two-thirds of the lateral surface of the tibia, and is attached to the first cuneiform and metatarsal bones of the foot. It is a dorsiflexor of the ankle and invertor of the foot.
label: Tibialis Anterior Muscle

description: A muscle of the lower leg that is located in the deep posterior compartment, originating on the inner posterior borders of the tibia and fibula, with further attachments to the interosseous membrane; the tendon of the posterior tibialis muscle, the posterior tibial tendon, terminates by dividing into plantar, main and recurring components, all of which have terminal insertions: plantar portion inserts into the bases of the second, third and fourth metatarsals; the intermediate and lateral cuneiforms, and the cuboid; the main portion inserts into the tuberosity of the navicular and the plantar surface of the medial cuneiform; the recurrent portion inserts into the sustentaculum tali of he calcaneus. The muscle functions to stabilize the ankle, as well as invert and plantar flex the foot at the ankle.
label: Posterior Tibialis Muscle

description: A group of three muscles (iliocostalis, longissimus, and spinalis) that originate at the sacrum, ilium, and lumbar vertebrae spines and insert into the ribs and vertebra in order to extend the vertebral column.
label: Erector Spinae

description: A muscle originating at the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and inserted at the third metacarpal bone that controls the radial extension and abduction of the wrist.
label: Extensor Carpi Radialis Brevis

description: A muscle originating at the lateral supracondylar ridge of the humerus and inserted at the back base of the second metacarpal bone that controls the radial extension and deviation of the wrist.
label: Extensor Carpi Radialis Longus

description: A muscle originating at the humeral and ulnar heads and inserted at the base of the fifth metacarpal bone that controls the extension and abduction of the wrist toward the ulna.
label: Extensor Carpi Ulnaris

description: A muscle originating at the lateral epicondyle of the humerus and inserted at the base of the proximal and middle phalanges as well as the base of the distal phalanges which controls the extension of the fingers.
label: Extensor Digitorum Communis

description: A muscle originating at the lateral condyle of the tibia and the upper portion of the anterior margin of the fibula and inserted at the dorsal surface of the proximal, middle and distal phalanges of the second, third, fourth, and fifth toes which controls their extension.
label: Extensor Digitorum Longus

description: A muscle in the lower leg and foot beginning at the tibia and ending with four tendons proceeding to the second, third, fourth, and fifth toes acting to curl the toes into the foot.
label: Flexor Digitorum Longus

description: A muscle in the forearm beginning at the head of the ulna and ending with four tendons projecting to the second, third, fourth, and fifth fingers which flexes the midcarpal, metacarpophalangeal and interphalangeal joints.
label: Flexor Digitorum Profundus

description: A muscle in the lower leg and foot beginning at the fibula and ending with a tendon attaching to the distal surface of the great toe phalanx in order to flex the toe.
label: Flexor Hallucis Longus

description: A fan shaped muscle running from the underside of the tongue to the mandible which depresses and protrudes the tongue.
label: Genioglossus

description: A muscle extending from the chin to the hyoid bone that brings the hyoid bone forward when swallowing and depresses the mandible.
label: Geniohyoid

description: The most superficial muscle extending vertically downward along the inner thigh which adducts the thigh, rotates the leg medially and flexes the knee.
label: Gracilis

description: A muscle of the perineum extending from the ischium to the corpus cavernosum penis in males and the clitoral glands in women which compresses the crus penis and regulates blood flow to the erect organ by compressing the veins.
label: Ischiocavernosus

description: A muscle in the back of the thigh. Its action involves the knee flexion and hip extension.
label: Biceps Femoris

description: A muscle that originates from the lower two-thirds of the anterior surface of the humerus that flexes the elbow.
label: Brachialis

description: A thin, broad, quadrilateral muscle that lies within the interval between the jaw (maxilla and mandible) on the side of the face.
label: Buccinator

description: A muscle arising from the coracoid process of the scapula, inserted in the medial border of the humerus, and acts to adduct and flex the arm.
label: Coracobrachialis

description: A muscle that lowers the bottom lip originating at the mandible and inserting at the skin of the lip.
label: Depressor Labii Inferioris

description: A muscle in the forearm running from the head of the humerus to the radial side of the wrist that flexes and radially abducts the hand.
label: Flexor Carpi Radialis

description: A muscle in the forearm running from the humeral and ulnar heads to the ulnar side of the wrist that flexes and abducts the hand toward the ulna.
label: Flexor Carpi Ulnaris

description: A muscle originating from the anterior tubercle of the transverse processes of cervical vertebrae three through six that inserts at the basilar process of the occipital bone acting to turn the neck anteriorly.
label: Longus Capitis

description: A muscle extending along the anterior spine between the atlas and the third thoracic vertebrae with three portions; superior oblique, vertical oblique and inferior oblique.
label: Longus Colli

description: One of the suprahyoid muscles located superior to the anterior belly of the digastric muscle that has its origin on the mandible, its insertion on the hyoid bone, and functions to elevate the hyoid, the tongue, and the floor of the mouth.
label: Mylohyoid Muscle

description: A skeletal muscle belonging to the infrahydoid muscle group, located in the anterior part of the neck with its origin on the upper border of the scapula and insertion on the hyoid bone; it functions to depress the hyoid bone.
label: Omohyoid Muscle

description: list()
label: Omotransverse

description: list()
label: Parotidoauricular

description: A skeletal muscle located in the anterior and medial region of the thigh, with origin on the pubic bone and insertion on the femur, which functions to flex and adduct the thigh.
label: Pectineus

description: The smallest and most deeply seated of the three scalene muscles, which functions to elevate the ribs during breathing and to laterally flex the neck.
label: Scalenus Dorsalis

description: The largest and longest of the three scalene muscles, which attaches to the transverse process of the six lower cervical vertebrae and the first rib, and which functions to bend the cervical part of the vertebral column to the ipsilateral side and to elevate the first rib.
label: Scalenus Medius

description: One of the three muscles that compose the hamstring muscles (semitendinosus, semimembranosus, bicepsfemoris); it is located in the posterior compartment of the thigh, and originates from the ischial tuberosity, inserts on the medial tibial condyle, and functions, in conjunction with the other muscles of the hamstring group, to extend the leg at the hip and to flex the leg at the knee.
label: Semimembranosus Muscle

description: One of the transversospinales group of muscles, located in the superior portion of the neck and covering the semispinalis cervicis. It takes its origin from the medial tissue between the superior and inferior nuchal lines of the occipital bone, and inserts into the superior articular processes of the lower four cervical vertebrae and the tips of the transverse processes of the upper six or seven thoracic vertebrae; it functions to extend the neck.
label: Semispinalis Capitis

description: One of the transversospinales group of muscles that arises from the spinous processes of the second to fifth cervical vertebrae and inserts into the posterior surfaces of the upper five or six thoracic transverse processes; it functions to extend the vertebrae from which it arises.
label: Semispinalis Cervicis

description: One of the transversospinales group of muscles that arises from C6-C7 cervical and T1-T4 spinous processes, and inserts into the transverse processes of the T6-T10 vertebrae; it functions to extend the spine and rotate it toward the contralateral side.
label: Semispinalis Thoracis

description: list()
label: Sphincter Colli Superficialis
