description: The synovial joints uniting the base of each arytenoid cartilage to the lamina of the cricoid cartilage.
label: Cricoarytenoid Joint

description: The synovial joint connecting the thyroid cartilage at the inferior horn to the side of the cricoid cartilage.
label: Cricothyroid Joint

description: A joint formed between carpal bones.
label: Carpal Joint

description: The synovial joints between the carpal and metacarpal bones in the hand.
label: Carpometacarpal Joint

description: A saddle-shaped synovial joint between the metacarpal of the thumb and the trapezium.
label: Carpometacarpal Joint 1

description: A plane joint primarily between the second metacarpal and the trapezoid, which also connects with the trapezium and capitate.
label: Carpometacarpal Joint 2

description: A plane joint between the third metacarpal and the capitate.
label: Carpometacarpal Joint 3

description: A plane joint between the fourth metacarpal and the hamate.
label: Carpometacarpal Joint 4

description: A plane joint between the fifth metacarpal and the pisiform.
label: Carpometacarpal Joint 5

description: A synovial joint between two adjacent vertebrae. The facet joint links the articular process of one vertebra and the inferior articular process of the adjacent vertebra.
label: Facet Joint

description: A ball-and-socket joint between the head of the femur and the acetabulum.
label: Hip Joint

description: The joint between the head of the lower mandible and the temporal bone.
label: Jaw Joint

description: Any of the joints within the pelvic girdle.
label: Joint of the Pelvic Girdle

description: Two cup shaped areas, one each on the lateral side of the lower pelvis that house the head of the femur to form the ball and socket joint of the hip.
label: Acetabulum

description: The joint between the left and right pubic bones at the front of the pelvis.
label: Pubic Symphysis

description: A joint connecting the lower part of the femur with the upper part of the tibia. The lower part of the femur and the upper part of the tibia are attached to each other by ligaments. Other structures of the knee joint include the upper part of the fibula, located below and parallel to the tibia, and the patella which moves as the knee bends.
label: Knee Joint

description: The amphiarthrodial joint between the sacrum and coccyx.
label: Sacrococcygeal Joint

description: The joint located between the sacrum and the ilium.
label: Sacroiliac Joint

description: The plane synovial joint between the talus and calcaneus bones of the foot.
label: Subtalar Joint

description: A ball-and-socket joint at the upper end of the humerus, located at the junction of humerus and scapula.
label: Shoulder Joint

description: The synovial joints between the tarsal bones of the foot.
label: Tarsal Joint

description: A combination of syndesmosis and synovial joints formed by the articulation of the talus with the navicular and the calcaneus with the cuboid.
label: Transverse Tarsal Joint

description: A joint between the distal end of the radius and the proximal row of carpal bones.
label: Wrist Joint

description: A condyloid synovial joint within the wrist connecting the scaphoid bone to the capitate bone.
label: Scaphoid-Capitate Joint

description: A condyloid synovial joint within the wrist connecting the scaphoid, lunate, and capitate bones.
label: Scaphoid-Lunate-Capitate Joint

description: A condyloid synovial joint within the wrist connecting the scaphoid bone to the trapezium bone.
label: Scaphoid-Trapezium Joint

description: The articulation of the capitate and hamate bones in the wrist.
label: Capitate-Hamate Joint

description: The articulation of the capitate and lunate bones in the wrist.
label: Capitate-Lunate Joint

description: The articulation between the hamate and the triquetral bones in the wrist.
label: Triangular-Hamate Joint

description: The articulation between the lunate and the triquetral bones in the wrist.
label: Lunotriquetral Joint

description: The articulation of the radius and the lunate bone in the wrist.
label: Radius-Lunate Joint

description: The articulation of the scaphoid and lunate bones in the wrist.
label: Scaphoid-Lunate Joint

description: The articulation of the radius and the scaphoid bone in the wrist.
label: Scaphoid-Radius Joint

description: The articulation of the scaphoid and trapezoid bones in the wrist.
label: Scaphoid-Trapezoid Joint

description: The articulation of the trapezium and trapezoid bones in the wrist.
label: Trapezium-Trapezoid Joint

description: The articulation of the trapezoid and capitate bones in the wrist.
label: Trapezoid-Capitate Joint

description: Any of the joints between the ribs and the vertebral bodies, sternum, transverse processes or with each other.
label: Rib Joint

description: Any of the joints associated with the vertebral column.
label: Vertebral Joint

description: Immovable articulation by close union, as in sutures.
label: Synarthrosis

description: Either of the two notches on the dorsal border of each side of the pelvis that when closed off by the sacrospinous and sacrotuberous ligaments form the corresponding sciatic foramina.
label: Sciatic Notch

description: Any of the openings between the vertebrae, through which pass the spinal nerve roots.
label: Neural Foramen

description: A bony projection from the anterior region of the iliac crest that functions as the site of attachment for the sartorius and tensor fascia latae muscles and the inguinal ligament.
label: Anterior Superior Iliac Spine

description: A bony projection from the posterior region of the iliac crest that lies over the sacroiliac joint and functions as the site of attachment for the thoracolumbar fascia and the posterior sacroiliac and sacrotuberous ligaments.
label: Posterior Superior Iliac Spine

description: An opening in the sphenoid bone at the base of the skull where several nerves, arteries, and veins exit the skull.
label: Foramen Ovale of the Skull

description: The constriction on the proximal end of the humerus just below the tuberosities of the humerus.
label: Neck of the Humerus, Surgical

description: A roughened surface on the superior portion of the posterior half of the calcaneus, where the calcaneal (Achilles) tendon inserts.
label: Calcaneal Tuberosity

description: The portion of the maxilla that contains the sockets of the teeth.
label: Maxillary Alveolar Process

description: The portion of the mandible that contains the sockets of the teeth.
label: Mandibular Alveolar Process

description: A layer of cartilage located in the metaphysis of long bones in children and adolescents that is the site of longitudinal bone growth until skeletal maturity.
label: Epiphyseal Plate

description: A layer of cartilaginous tissue located in the tibia of children and adolescents that separates the epiphysis from the metaphysis and is the site of longitudinal bone growth until skeletal maturity.
label: Tibial Growth Plate

description: An ossification site that is situated farthest from a point of attachment or origin.
label: Distal Ossification Site

description: An ossification site that is situated in the proximal region of the bone.
label: Proximal Ossification Site

description: A shallow groove in the shaft of the humerus through which the radial nerve and deep brachial artery course.
label: Radial Sulcus

description: A normal anteroinferior concavity of the sacrum and coccygeal vertebrae, extending from the lumbosacral junction to the apex of the coccyx.
label: Pelvic Curve

description: The posterior projection from the body of a vertebra that encloses the vertebral foramen; it consists of paired pedicles and laminae; the spinous, transverse, and articular processes arise from the arch. In aggregate, the venous arches-and the ligamenta flava that unite them-form the posterior wall of the vertebral (spinal) canal.
label: Arch of the Vertebra

description: The upper distal process of the scapula.
label: Acromion

description: The part of the skeleton that includes the skull and spinal column and sternum and ribs.
label: Axial Skeleton

description: The round end of the long bones.
label: Epiphysis of the Bone

description: The bony prominence on the outside of the ankle formed by the distal end of the fibula.
label: External Malleolus

description: The natural bend in the spine at the neck.
label: Cervical Curve

description: The shaft of a long bone, located between the two epiphyses; it is cylindrical in shape, with walls of compact bone enclosing a central marrow cavity.
label: Diaphysis of the Bone

description: A spinal curve that originates at the middle of the second thoracic vertebra and terminates at the middle of the last thoracic vertebra.
label: Dorsal Curve

description: The back or upper side of an animal.
label: Dorsum

description: A rounded convex section on the outer side of the head of the humerus where the supraspinatus, infraspinatus and teres minor tendons attach.
label: Greater Tuberosity

description: The highest portion of the femoral bone that articulates with the acetabulum.
label: Head of the Femur

description: The highest portion of the fibula that articulates with the patella.
label: Head of the Fibula

description: The upper rounded part of the humerus that fits into the glenoid cavity of the scapula.
label: Head of the Humerus

description: The superior portion of the tibia that joins with the fibula, femur and patella at the knee joint.
label: Head of the Tibia

description: The anterior tubercle on the humerus neck where the subscapularis tendon inserts.
label: Lesser Tuberosity

description: The natural bend in the spine in the lower back.
label: Lumbar Curve

description: The constriction on the proximal end of the humerus between the head and the greater tubercle.
label: Neck of the Humerus, Anatomical

description: The basin-shaped skeletal structure that is formed by the sacrum and the ilium, ischium, and pubis of each side that supports the trunk and to which the lower extremities attach.
label: Pelvic Girdle

description: A prominence at the proximal end of the ulna. It forms the tip of the elbow.
label: Olecranon

description: A bony protrusion on the femoral bone to which muscles are attached.
label: Trochanter

description: A large, irregular, quadrilateral area of bone found at the neck of the femur.
label: Great Trochanter

description: A cone-shaped projection in the shaft of the femur in which the iliopsoas muscle is attached.
label: Lesser Trochanter

description: The space formed by the series of vertebral foramina that courses the length of the vertebral column, and which houses the spinal cord and meninges.
label: Vertebral Canal

description: A thin, paired or unpaired, trapezoidal bone of the skull located in the floor of the nasal cavity. The vomer forms the posterior and inferior parts of the nasal septum.
label: Vomer

description: The cartilage just below the sternal body.
label: Xiphoid Process

description: A prominence on the sphenoid bone, which separates the sella turcica from the chiasmatic sulcus.
label: Tuberculum Sellae

description: The dorsal portion of the large, oval orifice located in the base of the skull, which serves as the exit point from the cranial cavity for the spinal cord.
label: Posterior Foramen Magnum

description: The bones of the skull that frame the mouth and serve to open it; the bones that hold the teeth.
label: Jaw Bone

description: The part of the skeleton that includes the bones of the upper and lower limbs.
label: Appendicular Skeleton

description: One of three (Inferior, Middle, Superior) paired bony shelves located within the nasal cavity through which inhaled air is taken into the nasopharynx. It is lined with ciliated, pseudostratified columnar epithelium and functions to humidify, heat, and filter incoming air, as well as protecting the olfactory bulb and sinuses from incorrectly pressurized incoming air.
label: Nasal Turbinate

description: The medial margin of the thorax created by the seventh to tenth rib.
label: Costal Arch

description: An area of a long bone located at the junction of the diaphysis and epiphysis, which harbors the epiphyseal plate in immature bones.
label: Metaphysis

description: The portion of the rib located at the posterior vertebral end, which is marked by a kidney-shaped articular surface.
label: Rib Head

description: The long, curved portion of the rib, which contains the intercostal vein, artery, and nerve in a groove found in the inferior margin.
label: Rib Shaft

description: A bony prominence located at the junction of the neck and the body of a rib, which articulates with the transverse processes of the adjacent thoracic vertebrae, ribs eleven and twelve excepted.
label: Rib Tubercle

description: The upper segment of the sternum, quadrangular in shape, as well as wider superiorly and narrower inferiorly. The sternal manubrium articulates with the clavicle and first two ribs.
label: Sternal Manubrium

description: The short, constricted portion of the thigh bone between the femur head and the trochanter.
label: Femoral Neck

description: The sphenoidal portion of the clivus, which is located inferior to cranial nerves five and six and superior to the pituitary fossa; it includes the dorsum sellae and the posterior clinoid processes.
label: Upper Clivus

description: The pyramidal shaped part of the temporal bone located at the base of the skull between the sphenoid and occipital bones.
label: Petrous Apex

description: The anterior aspect of the foramen magnum formed by the basilar part of the occipital bone.
label: Anterior Foramen Magnum

description: A bone prominence to which ligaments and tendons of the joints are attached.
label: Epicondyle

description: A bone prominence at the distal end of the humerus to which ligaments and tendons of the joints are attached.
label: Humeral Epicondyle

description: A bone prominence at the distal end of the humerus to which the radial collateral ligament of the elbow joint, the anconeus and supinator muscles, and the common extensor tendon are attached.
label: Lateral Humeral Epicondyle

description: The set of vertebrae immediately caudal to the skull.
label: Cervical Spine

description: Those vertebrae between the ribs and the pelvis, L1-L5 in man.
label: Lumbar Spine

description: The vertebrae of the thoracic spine, numbered one through twelve in man.
label: Thoracic Spine

description: An opening in the hip bone formed by the public bone and the ischium and closed by the obturator membrane.
label: Obturator Foramen

description: The roof or dome of the skull.
label: Skullcap

description: A rounded bony projection at the end of the bone.
label: Condyle

description: A rounded bony projection at the distal end of the femur.
label: Femoral Condyle

description: A rounded bony projection on the inner side of the distal end of the femur to which the medial collateral and the posterior cruciate ligaments are attached.
label: Medial Femoral Condyle

description: A bony tooth-like process projecting from the second cervical vertebra. It serves as the structure that supports the rotation of the first cervical vertebra.
label: Odontoid Process

description: Any of the bone cavities of the mandible or maxilla in which the roots of the teeth are anchored.
label: Tooth Socket

description: The cylindrical body of the femur.
label: Femoral Shaft

description: A thick process on either side of the vertebral body that connects the latter to the vertebral arch.
label: Pedicle of Vertebral Arch

description: Any component of the fibromuscular tissue that separates the thoracic from the abdominal cavity.
label: Diaphragm Part

description: The opening in the diaphragm that allows for passage of the descending aorta.
label: Aortic Opening

description: The angled junction where the diaphragm meets the chest wall.
label: Costophrenic Angle

description: A hole in the right crus of the diaphragm through which the esophagus and vagus nerve pass.
label: Esophageal Opening

description: The portion of the diaphragm in the left side of the body.
label: Left Portion of the Diaphragm

description: The orifices through which the superior and inferior vena cava drain blood into the right atrium.
label: Opening of the Vena Cava

description: The portion of the diaphragm in the right side of the body.
label: Right Portion of the Diaphragm

description: Space between the dura mater and the walls of the vertebral canal.
label: Epidural Spinal Canal Space

description: An area within the dura sheath but outside of the spinal cord.
label: Intradural Extramedullary Spinal Canal Space

description: Spongy discs located between the vertebrae of the spinal column; composed of the outer annulus fibrosus and inner nucleus pulposus.
label: Intervertebral Disc

description: The basic unit of contractility in a muscle fiber.
label: Sarcomere

description: A sheath that envelops a tendon.
label: Tendon Sheath

description: A fold of peritoneum originating at the stomach and supporting the viscera.
label: Omentum

description: A large fold of peritoneum that hangs down from the stomach, and extends from the stomach to the posterior abdominal wall after associating with the transverse colon.
label: Greater Omentum

description: The double layer of peritoneum that extends from the lesser curvature of the stomach and the start of the duodenum to the liver.
label: Lesser Omentum

description: A double layer of peritoneum that attaches to the back wall of the abdominal cavity and supports the small intestines.
label: Mesentery

description: The origin of the mesentery arising from the parietal peritoneum.
label: Mesenteric Root

description: A recess, cavity, or channel.
label: Sinus

description: A blind-ending, epithelial-lined tract that is located less than 5 mm from the anal verge.
label: Coccygeal Sinus

description: Any one of the air-filled spaces within the ethmoid, frontal, maxillary, or sphenoid bones, which communicate with the nasal cavity.
label: Paranasal Sinus

description: Either of the paired paranasal sinuses, located in the anterior part of the body of the sphenoid bone and communicating with the superior meatus of the nasal cavity on the same side.
label: Sphenoid Sinus

description: A pyramidal-shaped, thin-walled, air-filled cavity located in the maxilla. It is lined by mucus membrane and periosteum (mucoperiosteum) which contains cilia. It is adjacent to the nasal cavity and communicates with the middle meatus of the nose. It is the largest paranasal sinus and is composed of three recesses: alveolar, zygomatic, and infraorbital.
label: Maxillary Sinus

description: A sinus of the meatuses of the nasal cavity.
label: Ethmoid Sinus

description: The paired, mucosal lined air spaces located above the orbit and communicating with the nasal passages.
label: Frontal Sinus

description: Furrows, with pouchlike recesses at the lower end, separating the rectal columns.
label: Anal Sinus

description: A pear-shaped fossa in the wall of the laryngeal pharynx lateral to the arytenoid cartilage and medial to the lamina of the thyroid cartilage.
label: Pyriform Sinus

description: A concavity in a surface, especially an anatomical depression.
label: Fossa

description: A diamond-shaped depression located in the back of the knee joint.
label: Popliteal Fossa

description: A triangular space on the anterior side of the elbow joint. Three main veins of the arm, the brachial artery, the medial nerve and the tendon of the biceps pass through this space.
label: Antecubital Fossa

description: The large smooth and concave surface of the ilium.
label: Iliac Fossa

description: A tetrahedral region of adipose tissue located in the ischiorectal region with its base between the tuberosity of the ischium and the lower end of the rectum and its apex at the point where the obturator fascia and the Levator ani membrane divide.
label: Ischiorectal Fossa

description: The usual retroperitoneal location of the kidney in the dorsolumbar region of the body.
label: Renal Fossa

description: A depression found at the base of the neck that is bounded thusly: superiorly by the posterior belly of the omohyoid muscle; inferiorly by the clavicle; and medially by the sternocleidomastoid muscle.
label: Supraclavicular Fossa

description: A depression of the skull base lying posterior and inferior to the anterior cranial fossa and separated from the posterior cranial fossa by the clivus and the petrous crest. It supports the temporal lobes of the cerebrum and the pituitary gland.
label: Middle Cranial Fossa

description: The internal area of the skull that holds the frontal lobes.
label: Anterior Cranial Fossa

description: The trough in the head of the scapula that receives the head of the humerus to form the shoulder joint.
label: Glenoid Fossa

description: A depression on the surface of the medial aspect of the helix of the outer portion of the ear.
label: Fossa of the Antihelix

description: A depression on the surface of the curled rim of the most lateral border of the outer portion of the ear.
label: Fossa of the Helix

description: The infratentorial compartment of the cranial cavity. Its boundaries are formed by the sphenoid bone, temporal bone, and parietal bone, and it contains the cerebellum and brain stem.
label: Posterior Cranial Fossa

description: A small, pyramidal space located between the pterygoid process, the maxilla, and the palatine bone.
label: Sphenomaxillary Fossa

description: A fan-shaped depression on the lateral surface of the skull, under the superior temporal line and above the zygomatic arch, that houses the temporal muscle.
label: Temporal Fossa

description: An irregularly shaped cavity situated on the inner surface of the zygoma.
label: Zygomatic Fossa

description: The cavity just below the bladder where the prostate gland is located.
label: Prostate Bed

description: The external portion of any anatomic structure.
label: Anatomic Surface

description: The lingual or upper surface of the epiglottis.
label: Anterior Surface of the Epiglottis

description: The external portion of the prostate including the anterior, inferolateral, lateral and posterior surfaces.
label: Surface of the Prostate

description: The flattened aspect of the prostate with a slight furrow facing the rectum and anus.
label: Posterior Surface of the Prostate

description: The aspect of the prostate facing the pubic symphysis.
label: Anterior Surface of the Prostate

description: The aspect of the prostate facing the pelvic diaphragm and pubis.
label: Inferolateral Surface of the Prostate

description: The aspect of the prostate facing the anterior portions of the Levatores ani muscles.
label: Lateral Surface of the Prostate

description: Pertaining to the lower portion of the surface on the opposite side of the joint when it bends.
label: Lower Extensor Surface

description: Pertaining to the lower portion of the surface on the same side of the joint when it bends.
label: Lower Flexor Surface

description: Pertaining to the upper portion of the surface on the opposite side of the joint when it bends.
label: Upper Extensor Surface

description: Pertaining to the upper portion of the surface on the same side of the joint when it bends.
label: Upper Flexor Surface

description: The outer layer of the serous membrane that lines the abdominal cavity.
label: Peritoneal Surface

description: The surface of the epiglottis that is oriented toward the larynx.
label: Laryngeal Surface of the Epiglottis

description: The side of the tongue.
label: Lateral Surface of the Tongue

description: list()
label: Gastric Serosal Surface

description: The surface of an external body region.
label: Body Surface

description: The anterior surface of the lens of the eye.
label: Anterior Surface of the Lens

description: list()
label: Bladder Serosal Surface

description: The exterior part of the bone.
label: Bone Surface

description: The bone surface in a joint.
label: Articular Bone Surface

description: Any surface area on a bone that makes contact with soft tissues, like muscles and connective tissues, rather than forming a joint with another bone.
label: Non-Articular Bone Surface

description: The surface of the vagina that is in relation with the bladder and the urethra.
label: Anterior Surface of the Vagina

description: The membrane lining the external walls of the distal portion of the digestive tract from the small intestine to the anus. It consists of mesothelium on a connective tissue layer and it secretes a watery exudate.
label: Large Intestinal Serosal Surface

description: The serosal surface of the uterus.
label: Perimetrium

description: The posterior aspect of the vagina.
label: Posterior Surface of the Vagina

description: The membrane lining the external surface of the liver.
label: Serosal Surface of the Liver

description: The thin outermost layer of loose connective tissue covering the outer surface of the small intestine. It is derived from the peritoneum.
label: Small Intestinal Serosal Surface

description: The surface of the tooth facing or in direct contact with the oral mucosa of the cheek.
label: Buccal Surface

description: That side of the tooth facing the midline.
label: Mesial Surface

description: The biting surfaces of the premolar and molar teeth.
label: Occlusal Surface

description: Any component of the group of organs surrounded by loose connective tissue, separating the two pleural sacs, between the sternum anteriorly and the vertebral column posteriorly as well as from the thoracic inlet superiorly to the diaphragm inferiorly.
label: Mediastinum Part

description: The broadest part of the lower portion of the mediastinum. It contains the heart and the great vessels.
label: Middle Mediastinum

description: The area between the lungs; it contains the thymus, some lymph nodes, and vessels and branches of the internal thoracic artery.
label: Anterior Mediastinum

description: The part of the lower portion of the mediastinum that is located behind the pericardium.
label: Posterior Mediastinum

description: The part of the mediastinum that is located between the upper part of the sternum in the front and the upper thoracic vertebrae in the back.
label: Superior Mediastinum

description: The external membranous envelope, typically comprising dense, irregular connective tissue, that encapsulates some organs.
label: Organ Capsule

description: The membrane the surrounds the prostate gland.
label: Prostate Capsule

description: The fibrous lining that surrounds the left and right lobes of the thyroid gland.
label: Thyroid Gland Capsule

description: The thin fibrous tissue that surrounds the adrenal gland.
label: Adrenal Gland Capsule

description: A transparent, elastic membrane that encloses the lens of the eye.
label: Lens Capsule

description: The thin fibrous lining that divides the parathyroid gland into lobules.
label: Parathyroid Gland Capsule

description: A dense, fibrous, irregularly arranged connective tissue that surrounds each lobe of the thymus gland from which septae extend to partially subdivide it into interconnecting lobules.
label: Thymic Capsule

description: A thick connective tissue, called the tunica albuginea, which encapsulates each ovary.
label: Ovarian Capsule

description: A thick, fibrous, partial capsule of dense connective tissue on the outer aspect of the palatine tonsil that anteroinferiorly adheres to the side of the tongue and forms its lateral boundary with the oropharyngeal wall.
label: Tonsillar Capsule

description: Any component of the male or female organs and tissues involved in the production and maturation of gametes and in their union and subsequent development as offspring.
label: Reproductive System Part

description: Any component of the male organs and tissues involved in the production and maturation of gametes and in their union and subsequent development as offspring.
label: Male Reproductive System Part

description: The most proximal portion of the penis located between the descending portion of the pubic bone and the body of the penis.
label: Radix Penis

description: The most distal portion of the penis covered by the foreskin.
label: Glans Penis

description: The portion of the penis that extends from the site of attachment to the glans, and which is covered by skin. It is formed by the joining of the two proximal free parts of the corpora cavernosa and the related free part of the corpus spongiosum.
label: Body of the Penis

description: The anterior, often oval-shaped, part of a mature spermatozoon, which contains haploid male nuclear material.
label: Head of the Spermatozoon

description: The lowest part of the prostate gland adjacent to the superior fascia of the urogenital diaphragm.
label: Apex of the Prostate

description: The uppermost part of the prostate gland adjacent to the bladder wall.
label: Base of the Prostate

description: A layer of epithelium comprising both columnar and small cuboidal cells.
label: Wall of Prostatic Duct

description: A network of tubules that convey sperm from the seminiferous tubules within the testicles to the efferent ducts.
label: Rete Testis

description: The middle part of the epididymis, a crescent-like structure located in the upper and posterior surfaces of the testis, that extends downward from the head to the tail.
label: Body of the Epididymis

description: A part of a sperm cell, also known as the middle piece, between the head and the tail consisting of the neck and connection piece. This area contains a large number of mitochondria that produce energy to power the tail.
label: Body of the Spermatozoon

description: One of 12 to 14 small seminal ducts leading from the testis to the head of the epididymis.
label: Efferent Duct

description: One of two chambers along the shaft of the penis containing spongy erectile tissue, which, combined with the Corpus Spongiosum, fill with blood to create a penile erection.
label: Corpora Cavernosa

description: A mass of spongy erectile tissue surrounding the male urethra, and which, combined with the corpora cavernosa, fill with blood to create a penile erection.
label: Corpus Spongiosum

description: The rectangular crystalline-like structures comprised of proteins found in the cytoplasm of Leydig cells within the testes.
label: Crystal of Reinke

description: The first region of the epididymis distal to the testis.
label: Head of the Epididymis

description: A fold of skin covering the tip of the penis.
label: Male Prepuce

description: The dense whitish fibrous tissue that covers the testis.
label: Tunica Albuginea

description: Serous membrane that covers the testicles.
label: Tunica Vaginalis

description: The deepest of the three layers of the testis, consisting of blood vessels embedded in a loose connective tissue extending over the internal aspect of the tunica albuginea.
label: Tunica Vasculosa

description: The lower part of the epididymis.
label: Tail of the Epididymis

description: The part of the sperm called the flagellum; it functions to propel the sperm towards the egg.
label: Tail of the Spermatozoon

description: The part of the prostate gland that is lateral and posterior.
label: Posterolateral Part of the Prostate

description: Any one of the four lobes of the prostate gland including the anterior, lateral, median and posterior lobes.
label: Prostate Gland Lobe

description: The prostate gland lobe that is located on the posterior side of the organ.
label: Posterior Lobe of the Prostate

description: The upper, smaller part of the prostate between the ejaculatory ducts and the urethra.
label: Middle Lobe of the Prostate

description: The prostate gland lobe that is located on the lateral side of the organ.
label: Lateral Lobe of the Prostate

description: A term that indicates involvement of multiple zones of prostate.
label: Overlapping/Multiple Zones of Prostate

description: A small indentation located in the prostatic urethra, at the apex of the urethral crest, on the seminal colliculus, laterally flanked by openings of the ejaculatory ducts.
label: Prostatic Utricle

description: Any component of the female organs and tissues involved in the production and maturation of gametes and in their union and subsequent development as offspring.
label: Female Reproductive System Part

description: The erectile tissue in the vulva. It is composed of the corpora cavernosa and the glans clitoris.
label: Clitoris

description: The portion of the cervix which is lined by single columnar epithelium (mucosa).
label: Endocervix

description: The portion of the cervix that extends into the vaginal vault, and is lined with stratified squamous epithelium.
label: Ectocervix

description: The lower part of the uterus occupying the region between the isthmus of the uterus and the vagina. It is divided into supravaginal and vaginal portions.
label: Cervix Uteri

description: An elongated constriction of the lower part of the uterus, located at the junction of the body of the uterus and the cervix, that is composed principally of smooth muscle.
label: Isthmus Uteri

description: The accessory structures of the uterus, including the ovaries, fallopian tubes, broad ligament, and the ovarian and uterine ligaments.
label: Appendage of the Uterus

description: One of a pair of tubes that extend from the uterus to each of the ovaries. Following ovulation the egg travels down the fallopian tube to the uterus where fertilization may or may not occur.
label: Fallopian Tube

description: The fallopian tube that extends from the uterus to the ovary in the left side of the pelvic cavity.
label: Left Fallopian Tube

description: The fallopian tube that extends from the uterus to the ovary in the right side of the pelvic cavity.
label: Right Fallopian Tube

description: One of the paired female reproductive glands containing the ova or germ cells; the ovary's stroma is a vascular connective tissue containing numbers of ovarian follicles enclosing the ova.
label: Ovary

description: The ovary that is located in the left side of the pelvis.
label: Left Ovary

description: The ovary that is located in the right side of the pelvis.
label: Right Ovary

description: The upper, rounded portion of the uterus which is opposite from the cervix.
label: Fundus Uteri

description: The Corpus uteri, or body of uterus, is the part of the uterus above the isthmus, comprising about two thirds of the non-pregnant organ.
label: Corpus Uteri

description: The part of the endometrium that is located in the anterior uterine wall.
label: Anterior Endometrium

description: The part of the endometrium that is located in the posterior uterine wall.
label: Posterior Endometrium

description: The tissue layers that enclose the vaginal canal.
label: Vaginal Wall

description: The portion of the reproductive tract that connects the fallopian tubes to the uterus. The prominence of the uterine horns are variable across species and may be the location at which embryo implantation occurs in some species.
label: Uterine Horn

description: The outer edge of the hymen or hymenal remnants.
label: Hymenal Ring

description: A group of cells that remain of the Graafian follicle following ovulation. This structure is composed of endocrine tissue and produces progesterone. This is needed to prepare the uterine lining for implantation by the fertilized egg.
label: Corpus Luteum

description: The middle segment of the fallopian tube.
label: Ampullary Segment of the Fallopian Tube

description: A layer occurring in the endometrial lining of the uterus which is adjacent to the myometrium and below the functional layer.
label: Basal Layer of the Endometrium

description: The cervical opening on the side of the vagina.
label: Ectocervical Os

description: A space inside the uterus lined by a layer of mucus membranes called the endometrium.
label: Endometrial Cavity

description: The layer of connective tissue comprised of the endometrial lining of the uterus which fluctuates in thickness throughout the menstrual cycle.
label: Endometrial Stroma

description: The epithelial tissue of the endometrium.
label: Decidua

description: The endometrial layer that develops around the embryo then slowly regresses until the fourth month of pregnancy when the membrane presses against the decidua parietalis and begins to rapidly degenerate.
label: Decidua Capsularis

description: The altered uterine lining that forms during a pregnancy covering the uterine wall excluding the embryo implantation site.
label: Decidua Parietalis

description: The external structure of the clitoris covered by the clitoral hood.
label: Glans Clitoris

description: A fold of skin covering the tip of the clitoris.
label: Female Prepuce

description: The fringed end of the fallopian tube.
label: Fimbriated End of the Fallopian Tube

description: The funnel shaped portion of the fallopian tube proximal to the fimbrial segment and most distal to the uterus.
label: Infundibular Segment of the Fallopian Tube

description: The very narrow portion of the fallopian tube passing through the uterine wall into the uterine cavity.
label: Interstitial Segment of the Fallopian Tube

description: Thin membranous tissue that surrounds the vaginal opening.
label: Hymen

description: The muscular portion of the fallopian tube that continues to narrow as it connects to the uterus.
label: Isthmic Segment of the Fallopian Tube

description: The highly vascularized outer layer of the endometrium facing the uterine cavity which develops over the course of the proliferative and secretory phases then degenerates and sloughs off during menstruation.
label: Functional Layer of the Endometrium

description: A rounded prominence of adipose tissue overlying the pubic symphysis and adjacent pubic bone.
label: Mons Pubis

description: A space between the zona pellucida and the oolemma that changes both in size and composition during preimplantation development.
label: Perivitelline Space

description: A spherical aggregation of cells found in the ovaries that contains a single oocyte.
label: Ovarian Follicle

description: An ovarian follicle that contains more than one oocyte.
label: Polyovular Follicle

description: Any of the fluid-filled vesicles in the mammalian ovary containing a maturing ovum.
label: Graafian Follicle

description: An ovarian follicle undergoing maturation.
label: Growing Follicle

description: A primary oocyte surrounded by follicular epithelial cells arrested in the last stage of prophase until; further development will not happen until female sexual maturity is reached.
label: Primordial Follicle

description: A form of stroma, similar to medullary stroma, comprising a very cellular connective tissue arranged in characteristic whorls that contain embedded ovarian follicles.
label: Stroma of the Ovarian Cortex

description: Mucus gland in the endometrium.
label: Uterine Gland

description: Any one of the four small recessed areas (anterior, posterior, and two lateral) that are formed between the margin of the cervix and the vaginal wall.
label: Vaginal Fornix

description: A thick layer of glycoprotein that surrounds the plasma membrane of the oocytes of mammals, and functions to protect the oocyte during growth and transport, assist with fertilization and spermatozoa binding, preventing polyspermy, facilitate blastocyst development, and prevent ectopic pregnancy.
label: Zona Pellucida

description: Wall of body of uterus is composed of three layers: endometrium, myometrium, and perimetrium. Endometrium is the inner mucosal layer lining and is covered with columnar epithelium and tubular glands. Myometrium is a thick, muscular layer, consisting largely of bundles of smooth muscle fibers arranged in longitudinal, circular, and spiral patterns, and interlaced with connective tissue. Perimetrium is the outer layer composed of the peritoneal layer of the broad ligament that covers the body of the uterus and part of the cervix.
label: Wall of Body of Uterus

description: A part of the external female genitalia consisting of the labia majora and the labia minora.
label: Labium

description: One of the two longitudinal folds of skin that form the lateral boundary of the vulva. It extends from the mons pubis to the perineum.
label: Labium Majus

description: One of the two longitudinal folds of skin located between the labia majora.
label: Labium Minus

description: A depression in the ovary where the ovarian ligament attaches and blood vessels and nerves enter or leave the ovary.
label: Ovarian Hilus

description: A transient network of tubules and gonadal cords near the ovarian hilus that is formed from the primary sex cords in the developing ovary. It is homologous to the rete testes in males.
label: Rete Ovarii

description: The border between the squamous epithelium that lines the ectocervix and the columnar epithelium that lines the endocervix.
label: Squamocolumnar Junction

description: The external sex organs.
label: Genitalia

description: The external male sexual organs.
label: Male Genitalia

description: The external female sexual organs.
label: Female Genitalia

description: The components of the cell.
label: Cell Part

description: Specialized depressions on the cell surface involved in receptor-mediated endocytosis; the visible proteinaceous layer on the cytosolic side of the depression provides the coated appearance.
label: Coated Pit

description: The region within a cell nucleus where ribosomal DNA is clustered, ribosomal RNA is synthesized and ribosomes are assembled.
label: Nucleolus

description: The nonstaining primary constriction of a chromosome which is the point of attachment of the spindle fiber; provides the mechanism of chromosome movement during cell division; the centromere divides the chromosome into two arms, and its position is constant for a specific chromosome: near one end (acrocentric), near the center (metacentric), or between (submetacentric).
label: Centromere

description: One of the two side by side replicas produced by chromosome replication in mitosis or meiosis. Subunit of a chromosome after replication and prior to anaphase of meiosis II or mitosis. At anaphase of meiosis II or mitosis when the centromeres divide and the sister chromatids separate each chromatid becomes a chromosome. (Biology-Text.com)
label: Chromatid

description: Sister chromatids are the two newly synthesized daughter chromatids derived from the same chromosome parent.  During chromosomal pairing in meiosis, recombination occurs exclusively between non-sister chromatids.
label: Sister Chromatid

description: The genetic material of the nucleus, consisting of deoxyribonucleoprotein, which occurs in two forms during the phase between mitotic divisions: 1) as heterochromatin, seen as condensed, readily stainable clumps; 2) as euchromatin, dispersed lightly staining or nonstaining material. During mitotic division the chromatin condenses into chromosomes.
label: Chromatin

description: A tightly packed area of chromatin that may function to protect chromosome integrity and regulate gene expression.
label: Heterochromatin

description: A cluster of highly aggregated chromatin.
label: Karyosome

description: Heterochromatin found in the nucleus near the interior face of the inner nuclear membrane.
label: Marginal Chromatin

description: Heterochromatin that is associated with the nucleolus.
label: Nucleolar-Associated Chromatin

description: Euchromatin. The parts of chromosomes that, during interphase, are uncoiled dispersed threads and not stained by ordinary dyes; metabolically active, in contrast to the inert heterochromatin.
label: Euchromatin

description: An octagonal opening, about 70 nm across, where the inner and outer membranes of the nuclear envelope are continuous.
label: Nuclear Pore

description: A DNA packaging complex comprised of approximately 200 base pairs of DNA wound around a protein core, which is formed by an octomer of histones. The histone octomer includes two dimers of histones H2A and H2B that surround a tetramer consisting of two molecules of histone H3 and two molecules of histone H4.
label: Nucleosome

description: A subcellular feature in the cytoplasm of a cell with a definite structure and a specific role in the function of the cell.
label: Cytoplasmic Organelle

description: A functional area or structure in a cell that is not enclosed in a membrane.
label: Nonmembranous Cytoplasmic Organelle

description: The protein scaffolding (the network of filaments microfilaments, microtubules, intermediate filaments, and their associated proteins) that gives shape, structure, and organization to the cytoplasm and a cell its shape.
label: Cytoskeleton

description: Ribosomes are small organelles composed of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) and 80 some different proteins. rRNA is synthesized in the nucleolus and the ribosomal subunits are assembled there from rRNA and imported cytoplasmic made proteins. Once assembled, the subunits pass through the nuclear pores to the cytoplasm where they take part in protein synthesis. Some ribosomes are free in the cytoplasm and can be recruited to a polyribosomal structure when a messenger RNA (mRNA) strand is to be translated into a cytoplasmic protein. Other ribosomes are attached to the endoplasmic reticulum where the protein is formed within the interior to the endoplasmic reticulum. These proteins are destined for secretion, storage or incorporation into membranes.
label: Ribosome

description: A ribosome that is not associated with the membrane of the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
label: Free Ribosome

description: A cluster of ribosomes that is associated with the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
label: Membrane-Attached Polyribosome

description: A ribosome that is associated with the membrane of the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
label: Membrane-Attached Ribosome

description: A centriole-containing organelle that serves as the base and nucleation site for microtubules that form cilia or flagella.
label: Basal Body

description: One of two small cylindrical cell organelles composed of 9 triplet microtubules.
label: Centriole

description: An immature form of a centriole or basal body.
label: Procentriole

description: An mature centriole or basal body.
label: Mature Centriole

description: A functional area or structure in a cell that is bounded by a lipid-containing membrane.
label: Membranous Cytoplasmic Organelle

description: Semiautonomous, self-reproducing organelles that occur in the cytoplasm of all cells of most, but not all, eukaryotes. Mitochondria contain distinctive ribosomes, transfer RNAs, amino acyl t-RNA synthetases, and elongation and termination factors. Mitochondria depend upon genes within the nucleus for many essential messenger RNAs. Mitochondria consist of two sets of membranes, a smooth continuous outer coat and an inner membrane arranged in tubules or more often in folds that form platelike double membranes (cristae). Mitochondria are the principal energy source of the cell and contains the cytochrome enzymes of terminal electron transport and the enzymes of the citric acid cycle, fatty acid oxidation, and oxidative phosphorylation. Mitochondria are the sites of the reactions of oxidative phosphorylation, which result in the formation of ATP.
label: Mitochondrion

description: Mitochondria with a polymorphic and condensed matrix and reduced volume but an increased density. The inner membrane displays an irregular folding pattern and the volume of both the outer compartment and intracristal space is increased.
label: Condensed Configuration of the Mitochondrion

description: A basic architectural plan of a mitochondrion that exhibits a prominent matrix and narrow cristae, with the inner and outer compartment-intracristal space volumetrically decreased, and which is linked to inactive oxidase phosphorylation.
label: Orthodox Configuration of the Mitochondrion

description: A stack of flattened vesicles located between the nucleus and the secretory pole or surface of a cell. Functions in posttranslational processing and sorting of proteins, receiving them from the rough endoplasmic reticulum and directing them to secretory vesicles, lysosomes, or the cell membrane. The movement of proteins takes place by transfer vesicles that bud off from the rough endoplasmic reticulum or golgi apparatus and fuse with the golgi, lysosomes or cell membrane.
label: Golgi Apparatus

description: The endoplasmic reticulum is a network of tubular membranes within the cytoplasm of the cell, occurring either with a smooth surface (smooth endoplasmic reticulum) or studded with ribosomes (rough endoplasmic reticulum), involved in the transport of materials. (Infoplease Dictionary)
label: Endoplasmic Reticulum

description: Membrane organelle of eukaryotes that forms sheets and tubules. Contains the receptor for the signal receptor particle and binds ribosomes engaged in translating mRNA for secreted proteins and the majority of transmembrane proteins. Also a site of membrane lipid synthesis. The membrane is very similar to the nuclear outer membrane. The lumen contains a number of proteins that possess the C terminal signal KDEL.
label: Rough Endoplasmic Reticulum

description: An internal membrane structure of the eukaryotic cell. Biochemically similar to the rough endoplasmic reticulum, but lacks the ribosome binding function. Tends to be tubular rather than sheet like, may be separate from the rough endoplasmic reticulum or may be an extension of it. Abundant in cells concerned with lipid metabolism and proliferates in hepatocytes when animals are challenged with lipophilic drugs.
label: Smooth Endoplasmic Reticulum

description: The endoplasmic reticulum of striated muscle, specialised for the sequestration of calcium ions that are released upon receipt of a signal relayed by the T tubules from the neuromuscular junction.
label: Sarcoplasmic Reticulum

description: A class of morphologically heterogeneous cytoplasmic membrane-bound vesicle in animal and plant tissues characterized by their content of a wide variety of glycoprotein hydrolytic enzymes active at an acid pH and the structure-linked latency of these enzymes. The intracellular functions of lysosomes depend on their lytic potential. The single unit membrane of the lysosome acts as a barrier between the enzymes enclosed in the lysosome and the external substrate. The activity of the enzymes contained in lysosomes is limited or nil unless the vesicle in which they are enclosed is ruptured. Such rupture serves to digest exogenous material, such as bacteria, as well as effete organelles of the cells and is supposed to be under metabolic (hormonal) control.
label: Lysosome

description: An organelle formed by the fusion of an autophagosome with the lysosome, where the contents of the autophagosome are degraded.
label: Autophagolysosome

description: An organelle formed by the fusion of a phagosome with the lysosome, where the contents of the phagosome are degraded.
label: Phagolysosome

description: Intracytoplasmic phagolysosomes that are strongly basophilic. These structures are usually seen within the tubular epithelium and glomeruli of the kidney in response to antisense oligonucleotides.
label: Basophilic Phagolysosome

description: Subcellular respiratory organelles containing catalase and hydrogen peroxide-producing flavin oxidases among its enzymatic constituents, which carry out an essentially oxidative type of metabolism
label: Peroxisome

description: Any membrane-enclosed spaces or cavities within a cell.
label: Vacuole

description: The semipermeable membrane that encloses the cytoplasm of a cell.
label: Plasma Membrane

description: The specialized plasma membrane of an oocyte.
label: Oolemma

description: The cell membrane of a muscle cell. It is comprised of a plasma membrane coated with collagen fibers embedded in a layer of polysaccharides.
label: Sarcolemma

description: A vesicle that can move between organelles to deliver molecules to target locations.
label: Transport Vesicle

description: A vesicle that transports molecules that are targeted for cellular excretion.
label: Secretory Vesicle

description: A secretory vesicle between 30 and 90 nm in diameter that can play a role in receptor recycling, plasma membrane protein shedding, and the secretion of proteins and RNA.
label: Exosome

description: Usually a protein, it is produced in the granular endoplasmic reticulum and the Golgi complex.  Morphologically, it is defined as a membrane-bound particle.
label: Secretory Granule

description: A cytoplasmic vesicle that is coated with proteins which stabilize its structure and facilitate targeting.
label: Coated Vesicle

description: A membrane-bound vesicle that is involved in transport of extracellular factors into a cell.
label: Endocytotic Vesicle

description: A vesicle formed by the fusion of the plasma membrane around large particles during phagocytosis.
label: Phagosome

description: An organelle with a double membrane that sequesters proteins and other organelles which may be targeted for degradation.
label: Autophagosome

description: A vesicle formed by the fusion of the plasma membrane, which captures extracellular fluids and solutes during pinocytosis.
label: Pinocytotic Vesicle

description: A membrane bound cytoplasmic compartment that drives molecular traffic between the plasma membrane and lysosome.
label: Endosome

description: The endosomal compartment that fuses with endocytic vesicles and sorts the plasma membrane components from any internalized molecules that are targeted for lysosomal degradation.
label: Early Endosome

description: A multivesicular body that can fuse with the lysosome to target extracellular factors for degradation.
label: Late Endosome

description: A membrane-bound vesicle that encompasses several smaller membrane-bound vesicles.
label: Multivesicular Body

description: A small pocket, vesicle, cave, or recess communicating with the outside of a cell and extending inward, indenting the cytoplasm and the cell membrane. Such caveolae may be pinched off to form free vesicles within the cytoplasm. They are considered to be sites of uptake of materials into the cell, expulsion of materials from the cell, or sites of addition or removal of cell (unit) membrane to or from the cell surface.
label: Caveola

description: The physical volume occupied by a specific chromosome in the interphase nucleus.  The territories from distinct chromosomes do not appear to overlap, preventing an intermingling of the decondensed chromatin.  Relative to a nuclear landmark (e.g. nucleolus), chromosome territories appear to differ from cell to cell.
label: Chromosome Territory

description: The nuclear lamina is a proteinaceous filamentous meshwork of lamin proteins interacting with integral proteins of the inner nuclear membrane, including emerin, and is thought to play a role in nuclear stability, chromatin structure, and gene expression. Lamins are highly conserved in evolution and members of the intermediate filament protein family. Mammalian lamins are classified into two major types, A and B, with two subspecies of each: lamins A and C for the A type and B1 and B2 for the B type. Lamins A and C arise from one gene by alternative splicing. Pre-lamin A contains a carboxyl CAAX box that can be modified by farnesylation. During mitosis, the lamina meshwork is reversibly disassembled in parallel with phosphorylation of the lamins.
label: Nuclear Lamina

description: The nuclear contents other than the nucleolus.
label: Nucleoplasm

description: Signal-mediated nuclear import and export proceed through the nuclear pore complex (NPC). NPC is comprised of approximately 50 unique proteins collectively known as nucleoporins. NPC functions in the nuclear transport of protein and RNA. (NCI)
label: Nuclear Pore Complex

description: Cell junction is the specialized focal contact between cell-cell or cell-matrix in all tissues.  Cell junctions have various functions either communication, anchoring or organization.  There are specific protein associated with subtype of cell junctions and most of the junctions are too small to be resolved by light microscope.
label: Cell Junction

description: A cell-cell junction between a neuron and another neuron or a cell in a target organ. At this interface, the presynaptic neuron can transmit chemical (neurotransmitter) or electical signals (nerve impulses) to the postsynaptic target.
label: Synapse

description: A synapse in which an action potential causes the exocytosis of neurotransmitter from the presynaptic cell, which diffuses across the synaptic cleft and binds to ligand gated ion channels on the post synaptic cell. These ion channels then affect the resting potential of the post synaptic cell.
label: Chemical Synapse

description: A synapse in which the firing of the presynaptic cell increases the probability of firing of the postsynaptic cell.
label: Excitatory Synapse

description: A synapse in which the firing of the presynaptic cell reduces the probability of firing of the postsynaptic cell.
label: Inhibitory Synapse

description: A synapse between the axons of two neurons.
label: Axoaxonic Synapse

description: A synapse between the axon of one neuron and the dendrite of another neuron.
label: Axodendritic Synapse

description: A synapse between the axon of one neuron and the cell body of another neuron.
label: Axosomatic Synapse

description: A synapse in which electrical connection is made directly through the cytoplasm, via gap junctions.
label: Electrical Synapse

description: A synapse between dendrites of two neurons.
label: Dendrodendritic Synapse

description: A cellular junction where cellular transmembrane integrin receptors bind to extracellular matrix proteins.
label: Focal Adhesion

description: A region of cell-cell contact between adjacent cells in an epithelial layer.
label: Epithelial Cell Junction

description: Found near the apical surface of cells in simple epithelia. Forms a sealing "gasket" around the cell by the fusion of adjacent cell membranes which encircle the apical cell surface like a belt or fence. Prevents fluid moving through the intercellular gap and the lateral diffusion of intrinsic membrane proteins between apical and basolateral domains of the plasma membrane as well as occludes the movement of solute molecules between cells. Various proteins components of this junction have been identified, but how they are linked to form the ultrastructure of the junction is not known.
label: Tight Junction

description: Intercellular connections comprised of complexes of connexin family proteins that permit the transfer of cytoplasmic ions and molecules between connected cells. Each cell contains a hemichannel made up of homo- or hetero-hexamers of connexins.
label: Gap Junction

description: Anchoring junctions typically are observed as "spot welds" between cells in many types of epithelia. Detail structures can be seen only with EM.
label: Anchoring Junction

description: Desmosomes are intercellular anchoring junctions that anchor intermediate filaments at membrane-associated plaques in adjoining cells.  Desmosomes assemble in response to cell-cell contact and raised levels of extracellular calcium. Sensitivity to calcium levels is lost as desmosomes mature.
label: Desmosome

description: Half desmosomes that occur on the basal surface of the stratum basalis of stratified squamous epithelium.
label: Hemidesmosome

description: The best understood cell-cell junction required for adhesion between cells in the epithelium. It seals adjacent epithelial cells together, preventing the passage of most dissolved molecules from one side of the epithelial sheet to the other. Adherens junctions are located most apically in insect cells and just basal to the tight junction in vertebrate cells. It is formed by the fusion of adjacent cell membranes which encircle the apical cell surface like a belt or fence based on homophilic association between molecules of the transmembrane protein E-cadherin, which is linked on its cytoplasmic side to the actin cytoskeleton via b-catenin (Drosophila Armadillo) and a-catenin. The adherens junctions and associated cytoskeleton form a continuous band (zonula adherens) around the apical circumference of each cell, thus uniting the cells of the epithelium into a coherent sheet.
label: Zonula Adherens

description: Fascia adherens, similar to a zonula adherens, is a half Z line found in the cardiac muscle as one of the three intercalated disks.  They anchor actin filaments from terminal sarcomeres and transmit contractile force between myocytes. (NCI)
label: Fascia Adherens

description: The components of the cell and how they are arranged.
label: Cell Structure

description: Any of the lipid bilayer membranes within a cell.
label: Cellular Membrane

description: A thin pliable sheet separating organelles from the protoplasm.
label: Intracellular Membrane

description: The double-layer membrane structure enclosing the nucleus in eukaryotic cells. It separates the DNA of the cell from the cytosol. For exchange of material, for example, proteins and mRNA, it is punctured with numerous nuclear pores.
label: Nuclear Membrane

description: The nuclear envelope has two membranes, each with a typical unit membrane in structure. They enclose a flattened sac and are connected at the nuclear pore sites. The inner nuclear membrane separates the perinuclear cistern of the endoplasmic reticulum from the nucleoplasm. It is attached to and supported by the lamina. A growing number of proteins that are specifically located to this membrane seem to participate in functionally organizing the nucleus. (NCI)
label: Nuclear Inner Membrane

description: The nuclear envelope has two membranes, each with the typical unit membrane structure. They enclose a flattened sac and are connected at the nuclear pore sites. The outer nuclear membrane is continuous with the rough endoplasmic reticulum (ER) and has ribosomes attached. (NCI)
label: Nuclear Outer Membrane

description: A lipid bilayer enclosing the endoplasmic reticulum.
label: Membrane of the Endoplasmic Reticulum

description: A lipid bilayer enclosing the part of the endoplasmic reticulum that has ribosomes located on the cytoplasmic-facing membrane.
label: Membrane of the Rough Endoplasmic Reticulum

description: A lipid bilayer enclosing the portion of the endoplasmic reticulum that is free of ribosomes.
label: Membrane of the Smooth Endoplasmic Reticulum

description: The double membrane structure surrounding the mitochondrion and separating it from the cell cytoplasm.  The two membranes are separated by an intermembrane space. The electron transport chain resides in the inner mitochondrial membrane.
label: Mitochondrial Membrane

description: The mitochondrial outer membrane contains the multi-subunit machinery responsible for the specific recognition and translocation of precursor proteins.
label: Outer Mitochondrial Membrane

description: The inner mitochondrial membrane encloses a fluid-filled matrix and is elaborately folded with shelf-like cristae projecting into the matrix. The components of electron transport chain are integral part of the inner membrane.
label: Inner Mitochondrial Membrane

description: The part of the inner mitochondrial membrane that folds inward to enclose the cristae.
label: Membrane of Crista

description: A lipid bilayer enclosing an endosomal compartment.
label: Membrane of the Endosome

description: A lipid bilayer enclosing a Golgi compartment.
label: Membrane of the Golgi Apparatus

description: A lipid bilayer that encloses a lysosome.
label: Membrane of the Lysosome

description: A lipid bilayer that bounds a peroxisome.
label: Membrane of the Peroxisome

description: A body within the cell, surrounded by a membrane, within which lie the chromosomes, one or more nucleoli, combined with proteins, and exhibits mitosis.
label: Nucleus

description: That portion of the cell contained within the plasma membrane but excluding the nucleus.
label: Cytoplasm

description: The specialized cytoplasm in an oocyte.
label: Ooplasm

description: The cytoplasm of striated muscle fibre.
label: Sarcoplasm

description: An anatomical element found within cells or tissues that are smaller than cells and are at or below the size that can be resolved by light microscopy.
label: Subcellular Structure

description: Any structures that are enclosed within nucleus are considered nuclear structure, including any macromolecular structures. (NCI)
label: Nuclear Structure

description: A network of fibrillar structures within cell nuclei that may play a role in chromatin organization and the localization of proteins within the nucleus.
label: Nuclear Matrix

description: The plane of the spindle approximately equidistant from the two poles along which the chromosomes are lined up during mitosis or meiosis.
label: Metaphase Plate

description: The 3-D organization of histones and other proteins on chromosomal DNA in the nucleus and allow for its form and function during cellular growth and division.
label: Chromosome Structure

description: A stretch of telomeric DNA where the normally guanine-rich (TTAGGG)n overhanging sequence has gaps while the cytosine-rich (AATCCC)n opposite strand remains intact. The resulting partially single-stranded telomere can adopt a circular confirmation.
label: C-Circle

description: A stretch of repetitive nucleotide sequences (TTAGGG repeats in humans) found at both ends of each chromatid arm that plays a role in chromosome stability during replication.
label: Telomere

description: Nucleolar organizer regions (NORs), which are loops of DNA containing ribosomal RNA genes, have been shown to correlate with cell proliferation and malignant transformation.
label: Nucleolar Organizer Region

description: A DNA sequence necessary and sufficient for initiation of DNA replication.
label: Origin of Replication

description: Under the microscope chromosomes appear as thin, thread-like structures. They all have a short arm and long arm separated by a primary constriction called the centromere. The short arm is designated as p and the long arm as q.
label: Chromosome Arm

description: The chromosomal arm that contains the beginning of the range. (BRIDG)
label: Start Chromosome Arm

description: list()
label: Cytoband Range Start Chromosome Arm

description: The chromosomal arm that contains the terminus of the range. (BRIDG)
label: End Chromosome Arm

description: list()
label: Cytoband Range End Chromosome Arm

description: The shorter arm of the chromosome based on the distance from the most distal point to the centromere.
label: Short Arm of Chromosome

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 20
label: 20p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 13
label: 13p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 14
label: 14p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 17
label: 17p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 3
label: 3p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 8
label: 8p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 15
label: 15p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 21
label: 21p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 16
label: 16p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 1
label: 1p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 11
label: 11p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 10
label: 10p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 12
label: 12p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 22
label: 22p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 4
label: 4p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 5
label: 5p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 18
label: 18p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 19
label: 19p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 6
label: 6p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 7
label: 7p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 2
label: 2p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome 9
label: 9p

description: Proximal (short) arm of chromosome X
label: Xp

description: The proximal (short) arm of chromosome Y.
label: Yp

description: The longer arm of the chromosome based on the distance from the most distal point to the centromere.
label: Long Arm of Chromosome

description: Regions of chromosomal DNA attached to structural components of metaphase (condensed) chromosomes, permitting the partitioning of DNA in the chromosomes into looped domains.  Appear to be related to similar regions denoted matrix-attachment regions that partition the chromosomal DNA in interphase chromosomes.
label: Scaffold-Associated Region

description: Heritable sensitive regions of chromosomes which show up in vitro as non-staining bands. They are associated with chromosome breakage and other aberrations. No abnormal phenotype has been definitely identified with autosomal fragile sites, but some rare autosomal recessive disorders may be due to homozygosity for fragile sites. A fragile site on the X chromosome is associated with Fragile X Syndrome. Fragile sites are designated by the letters "fra" followed by the designation for the specific chromosome and locus.
label: Chromosome Fragile Site

description: Chromosomal bands observed after staining with specific dyes.  The band pattern is the result of differential interactions between the dye and nonadjacent chromosomal regions.
label: Chromosome Band

description: Regions of chromosomal DNA attached to a structural component of the interphase nucleus termed the nuclear matrix, permitting the partitioning of DNA in the chromosomes into looped chromatin domains.
label: Matrix Attachment Region

description: The structural elements that comprise a gene or transcription unit. Gene structures include the transcription initiation site, the protein coding sequences, intervening sequences, and the transcription termination or polyadenylation sites as well as the regulatory elements (enhancers, silencers, and the promoter) that lie outside the boundaries of the transcribed unit.
label: Gene Feature

description: The sequences of a gene that are present in the final, mature, spliced messenger RNA molecule from that gene.
label: Exon

description: Non-coding, intervening sequences of DNA that are transcribed, but are removed from within the primary gene transcript and rapidly degraded during maturation of messenger RNA.
label: Intron

description: Nucleotide sequences found upstream of exons encoding the constant regions of immunoglobulin heavy chains where exon rearrangement can occur. The combination of exons selected in a B-cell determines the immunoglobulin isotype produced by that cell.
label: Immunoglobulin Switch Region

description: A consensus sequence found in the promoter region of most genes transcribed by eukaryotic RNA polymerase II. It is found about 25 nucleotides before the site of initiation of transcription and has the consensus sequence: 5' TATAAAA 3'. This sequence seems to be important in determining accurately the position at which transcription is initiated.
label: TATA Box

description: The site within the 3' untranslated region of a gene where polyadenylation of the transcribed RNA takes place.  Usually consists of the sequence AATAAA.
label: Poly-A Addition Site

description: Any DNA sequence involved in the regulation of genetic processes such as transcription and replication.
label: Regulatory Element

description: A regulatory element that is a target for a large number of transcription regulatory proteins. These DNA sequences, which play a role in the regulation of gene expression, bind to transcription factors or coregulatory proteins at a higher density than would be expected by chance.
label: High Occupancy Target Region

description: A 50-150bp DNA sequence that increases the rate of transcription of coding sequences. It may be located at various distances and in either orientation upstream from, downstream from or within a structural gene.  When bound by a specific transcription factor it increases the levels of expression of the gene, but is not sufficient alone to cause expression. Distinguished from a promoter, that is alone sufficient to cause expression of the gene when bound.
label: Enhancer

description: An enhancer which is located 3' of the gene it regulates.
label: Downstream Enhancer

description: Enhancer sequences found nearby to the gene it regulates.
label: Proximal Enhancer Element

description: Enhancer sequences found at a distance from the gene it regulates.
label: Distal Enhancer Elements

description: An enhancer which is located 5' of the gene it regulates.
label: Upstream Enhancer

description: A DNA sequence at which RNA polymerase binds and initiates transcription.
label: Promoter

description: A distal promoter element in the 5' regulatory region of the APC gene on chromosome 5.
label: APC Promoter 1B

description: A nucleotide sequence that plays a role in the expression of a nearby gene because it can be recognized by specific transcription factors or coregulatory proteins.
label: Response Element

description: A promoter sequence which interacts with CRE binding proteins to modulate gene expression in response to the level of cAMP in the cell.
label: Cyclic AMP Response Element

description: Androgen response element is the target binding element for activated androgen receptor homodimer.  The consensus sequence for this high-affinity androgen receptor-binding is the palindromic sequence GGT/AACAnnnTGTTCT, though could deviate considerably in natural promoter sequences.  The most well-characterized in this regard is the promoter of the PSA (prostate-specific antigen) gene.
label: Androgen Response Element

description: A cis-acting transcription regulatory element.  It is bound by the retinoic acid receptors.
label: Retinoic Acid Response Element

description: DNA sequences in a gene's promoter region that mediate expression during hypoxia.  Since unlike normal tissues, solid tumors frequently have regions of hypoxia, suicide genes controlled by hypoxia-responsive elements may provide a means for cancer-specific gene therapy.
label: Hypoxia-Responsive Elements

description: Internal ribosome entry site (IRES) is a translational cis-acting element that directs ribosomes to the start codon by a cap-independent mechanism.  IRESs are usually about 450 nucleotides in length and were first identified in picornavirus RNAs.  IRESs can fold into a stable secondary hairpin structure to be incompatible with efficient translation by ribosomal scanning. (NCI)
label: Internal Ribosome Entry Site

description: The sequences on a gene or messenger RNA that are translated into protein.
label: Coding Region

description: Short region of DNA in which the frequency of the CG sequence is higher than in other regions.
label: CpG Island

description: Sequences immediately preceding a point of interest.
label: 5' Region

description: Sequences on the 5' end of messenger RNAs that are not translated into protein.  5'UTR extends from the transcription start site to just before the ATG translation initiation codon.  This region contains the ribosome binding site and other transcription and translation regulating sequences.
label: 5' Untranslated Region

description: Sequences immediately following a point of interest.
label: 3' Region

description: Sequences on the 3' end of messenger RNAs that are not translated into protein. The 3'UTR is involved in many post-transcriptional regulatory pathways, including regulating translation efficiency, mRNA stability, and polyadenylation signals.
label: 3' Untranslated Region

description: A region of a messenger RNA that is not translated into protein.
label: Untranslated Region

description: A highly repetitive retrotransposon-like sequence that is 6000-8000 base pairs in length. It may contain an RNA polymerase II promoter domain, repetitive target sequences, and open reading frames encoding proteins with endonuclease and reverse transcriptase activity.
label: Long Interspersed Element

description: A long interspersed element (LINE) found in mammals. The LINE-1 element is the only active LINE in humans and is approximately 6,000 base pairs long. This nucleotide sequence consists of two non-overlapping open reading frames (ORF) flanked by a 5' untranslated region (UTR), which contains a strong RNA polymerase II promoter sequence, and target side duplications. The first ORF encodes a 500 amino acid, ~40 kDa leucine zipper-containing RNA-binding protein. The second ORF encodes an ~150 kDa protein that has endonuclease and reverse transcriptase activity. Increased LINE-1 copy number is associated with cancer and neuropathy.
label: Long Interspersed Nucleotide Element-1

description: The human Y chromosome is composed of two different parts: a pseudoautosomal region that is homologous to a region of the X chromosome and which is responsible for sex chromosome pairing and a Y-specific part that encodes the sex determining gene.  Genes within the pseudoautosomal region are not sex linked.
label: Pseudoautosomal Region

description: The position of a gene or a chromosomal marker on a chromosome; also, a stretch of DNA at a particular place on a particular chromosome. The use of locus is sometimes restricted to mean regions of DNA that are expressed.
label: Locus

description: A stretch of DNA at a particular chromosomal location that contains or is linked to genes that are associated with the expression of a variable phenotypic trait.
label: Quantitative Trait Locus

description: A stretch of DNA at a particular chromosomal location that is able to regulate the expression of a specific mRNA or protein.
label: Expression Quantitative Trait Locus

description: An intergenic gene locus on the short arm of human chromosome 9 located between the TRAF1 and C5 genes. Polymorphism in this region may be associated with increased susceptibility for rheumatoid arthritis.
label: TRAF1-C5 Locus

description: The location of the genetic or genomic sequence that is described by the test result.
label: Genetic Location

description: list()
label: Performed Genetic Observation Result Genetic Location

description: The region and position of the genetic or genomic sequence that is the focus of the test.
label: Genetic Location Of Interest

description: list()
label: Performed Genetic Observation Genetic Location Of Interest

description: The region or sub-location of the genetic or genomic sequence that is described by the test.
label: Genetic Region of Interest

description: list()
label: Performed Genetic Observation Genetic Region of Interest

description: list()
label: Performed Genetic Observation Result Genetic Region of Interest

description: The sub-region of the genetic or genomic sequence that is described by the test result.
label: Genetic Subregion

description: list()
label: Performed Genetic Observation Result Genetic Subregion

description: Nucleosome core particle consists of the 146 base pair highly protected DNA segment and its bound histone octamer (two of each histones H2A, H2B, H3 and H4). Nucleosome core particle, linker DNA and histone H1 comprise one structural unit of chromatin, nucleosome. (NCI)
label: Nucleosome Core Particle

description: It is the aggregated products of microtubules during mitosis where chromosomes line up prior to the segregation process. Many antineoplastic agents cause cytotoxicity by inducing microtubular bundle formation irreversibly. (NCI)
label: Microtubule Bundle
