description: Proteolytic complexes, proteolytic core of the proteasome system, that degrade cytosolic and nuclear proteins are implicated in ATP dependent ubiquitin protein complex degradation and in antigen processing in antigen presenting cells. The 20S proteasome (700 kD), essential in ATP ubiquitin degradation pathway, has 13-15 subunits each of which has three or four different peptidase activities. The 20S proteasome interacts with additional subunits, PA700 and PA28, to form an ATP-dependent multicatalytic proteinase complex (MPC) involved in the degradation of ubiquitinated cellular proteins and certain non-ubiquitinated proteins. 26S proteasomes may be formed in an ATP dependent fashion from a 20S proteasome and additional components, CF1 (660 kD), CF2 (250 kD) and CF3 (600 kD).
label: Proteasome

description: Ubiquitinated proteins are degraded by a 26S ATP-dependent protease complex, composed of a 20S catalytic proteasome and two 19S PA700 regulatory modules.  The multi-subunit PA700 complex binds two sites of the 20S proteasome and is composed of at least six related ATPases and approximately fifteen non-ATPase polypeptides.  Each of the ATPases, PSMC1-6, contains an AAA (ATPases associated with diverse cellular activities) domain.  A protein complex containing p42 and p50 enhances PA700 activation of the proteasome.
label: PA700 Regulatory Module

description: The 20S proteasome, as proteolytic core of the proteasome system, is essential in ATP dependent ubiquitin protein complex degradation and in antigen processing in antigen presenting cell. It has 13-15 subunits each of which has three or four different peptidase activities. 26S proteasomes may be formed in an ATP dependent fashion from a 20S proteasome and additional components, CF1 (660 kD), CF2 (250 kD) and CF3 (600 kD). The 20S proteasome interacts with additional subunits, PA700 and PA28, to form an ATP-dependent multicatalytic proteinase complex (MPC) involved in the ATP ubiquitin degradation pathway.
label: 20S Proteasome

description: Proteasomes are large multicatalytic proteolytic complexes found in all eukaryotic cells, and simpler forms have been found in archaebacteria and certain eubacteria.  In eukaryotes, the 20S proteasome also exists as the central core of the 26S (2000 kDa) proteasome complex, which catalyzes the degradation of ubiquitin-conjugated proteins and contains an additional 19S complex, composed of regulatory proteins and six ATPases.
label: 26S ATP-Dependent Proteasome

description: The spindle pole body (SPB) is the microtubule organizing center (MTOC) in the yeast Saccharomyces that plays a pivotal role in such diverse processes as mitosis, budding, and mating. (from Cell. 1997;89:1077-86)
label: Spindle Pole Body

description: Contractile system directs cell movement and is responsible for maintaining or changing cell shape. The system consists of many specialized cytoplasmic proteins, including actin, myosin, tubulin, kinesin, other cytoskeletal and contractile system proteins. (NCI)
label: Contractile System

description: Rod-shaped structures of uncertain nature in the cytoplasm of immature myeloid cells, especially myeloblasts, in acute myelocytic leukemia; may be an abnormal form of lysosomes; they contain peroxidase and acid phosphatase, and stain red by azure-eosin stains.
label: Auer Rod

description: A closed structure surrounded by a single membrane.
label: Cellular Vesicle

description: A structure or space in a prokaryotic cell.
label: Prokaryotic Cell Component

description: The part of the cell membrane that faces the exterior of the cell.
label: Cell Surface

description: The organized colloidal complex of organic and inorganic substances (as proteins and water) that constitutes the living nucleus, cytoplasm, plastids, and mitochondria of the cell. It is composed mainly of nucleic acids, proteins, lipids, carbohydrates, and inorganic salts.
label: Protoplasm

description: The aqueous part of the cytoplasm within which various particles and organelles are suspended.
label: Cytosol

description: Bilayer membrane fragments present in the blood plasma that are released by different cell types upon activation or death. Extracellular vesicles are usually classified as either exosomes (formed by the membranes of intracellular compartments, 50-100 nm in diameter) and ectosomes (also called microparticles or microvesicles, formed from plasma membrane, 100-1000 nm in diameter).
label: Extracellular Vesicle

description: A small, membrane-bound vesicle between 100 nm to 1000 nm in size found in the circulatory system. These vesicles are plasma membrane fragments shed from cells. The protein composition is similar to that of the cell that shed the particle.
label: Microparticle

description: A small, membrane bound vesicle circulating in the blood that was shed by a platelet. This is the most abundant type of microparticle in human blood. Since they contain platelet chemokines and surface proteins, these particles may modulate vascular processes, such as blood coagulation.
label: Platelet-Derived Microparticle

description: A small, membrane bound vesicle circulating in the blood that was shed by a monocyte. These particles may induce coagulation or cell apoptosis.
label: Monocyte-Derived Microparticle

description: A small, membrane bound vesicle circulating in the blood that was shed by an endothelial cell. Increased concentrations of endothelial microparticles in plasma may be a marker for cardiovascular disease.
label: Endothelial Cell-Derived Microparticle

description: A small, membrane bound vesicle circulating in the blood that was shed by a cell that expresses the coagulation protein, tissue factor (factor III). The presence of microparticles with tissue factor in the plasma of cancer patients is associated with an increased risk for venous thrombosis.
label: Tissue Factor-Derived Microparticle

description: A network of membrane components where vesicles bud off the Golgi apparatus to bring proteins, membranes and other components to the plasma membrane, secretory vesicles and endosomes.
label: Trans-Golgi Network

description: Granules found in several types of cells, especially platelets, where they are the most numerous type of granule; contain secretory proteins.
label: Alpha Granule

description: A complex comprised of gamma tubulin and other proteins that can act as a scaffold for the nucleation of microtubules.
label: Gamma-Tubulin Ring Complex

description: A functional part or structural element of a chemical synapse.
label: Chemical Synapse Component

description: The membrane of the postsynaptic cell that is enriched with neurotransmitter receptors.
label: Postsynaptic Membrane

description: An area at the end of an axon that contains neurotransmitters in synaptic vesicles.
label: Presynaptic Knob

description: The part of a desmosome that is on the cytoplasmic side of this junction, consisting of desmoplakin, plakoglobins and plakophilins, which links the cytoplasmic intermediate filaments to the transmembrane cadherin receptor proteins.
label: Attachment Plaque

description: A straight line through one of two small cylindrical cell organelles composed of 9 triplet microtubules.
label: Axis of the Centriole

description: A cytoplasmic granule found in the myelocyte lineage that can be stained with azure dyes.
label: Azurophilic Granule

description: A collection of mitochondria, germinal plasm and fragments of both the endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi that is found next to the nucleus during early stages of oocyte development.
label: Balbiani Body

description: The inactive, condensed X chromosome in a female somatic cell.
label: Barr Body

description: A rod shaped cytoplasmic organelle found in Langerhans cells of the epidermis.
label: Birbeck Granule

description: A network of membrane components where vesicles from the endoplasmic reticulum fuse with the Golgi apparatus.
label: Cis-Golgi Network

description: The space inside of an endosome.
label: Cisterna of the Endosome

description: One of the flattened membrane-bound disks of the Golgi apparatus.
label: Cisterna of the Golgi Apparatus

description: One of the flattened membrane-bound regions of the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
label: Cisterna of the Rough Endoplasmic Reticulum

description: The hydrophilic portions of the plasma membrane as seen during transmission electron microscopy. This electron density is caused by abundant staining by heavy metal-containing dyes.
label: Electron-Dense Plasma Membrane Layer

description: The hydrophobic portion of the plasma membrane as seen during transmission electron microscopy because there is little to no binding of the detection reagent.
label: Electron-Lucent Plasma Membrane Layer

description: A series of enzyme complexes in the inner mitochondrial membrane that transfer hydrogen ions into the intermembrane space. The activity of these enzymes creates an electrochemical gradient that is necessary for synthesis of adenosine triphosphate.
label: Electron-Transport Chain of the Respiratory Enzymes

description: The portion of the mitochondrial ATP synthase that is found inside the matrix. This protein complex can catalyze the conversion of adenosine diphosphate to adenosine triphosphate.
label: F1 Particle

description: A protein complex found in the membrane of the endosome that transports hydrogen ions into the lumen to increase its acidity.
label: Endosome Proton Pump

description: A protein that links cytoskeletal filaments to one another and modulates both the formation and stability of cellular structures.
label: Crosslinker

description: A stainable aggregation of protein, lipid or small molecules in the cytoplasm.
label: Cytoplasmic Inclusion

description: A ubiquitin-rich cytoplasmic inclusion encased in vimentin found near the microtubule organizing center. It is formed in response to cellular stresses that cause the production of misfolded proteins at levels that exceed the degradative capacity of the proteasome. This inclusion body is comprised of aggregated misfolded or denatured proteins that have been transported along microtubules to the pericentriolar space where they become encased in vimentin.
label: Aggresome

description: A detectable aggregation of small molecules in the cytoplasm.
label: Crystalline Inclusion

description: A stainable aggregation of glycogen in the cytoplasm.
label: Glycogen Inclusion

description: A detectable aggregation of lipids or membrane fragments in the cytoplasm.
label: Lipid Inclusion

description: A fluid cytoplasmic substance filling the interstices of the cytoskeleton.
label: Cytoplasmic Matrix

description: A small region of cytoplasm adjacent to the nucleus that contains the centrioles and serves to organize the microtubules.
label: Centrosome

description: An extracellular coating of polymeric sugars or glycoproteins.
label: Glycocalyx

description: A group of three types of polymeric protein structures that impart shape to a cell and are involved in cellular motility, organelle localization and vesicular targeting.
label: Cytoskeleton Filament

description: A class of tough protein filaments (including keratin filaments, neurofilaments, desmin, and vimentin) that measure 8-10 nm in thickness and comprise part of the cytoskeleton of the cytoplasm of most eukaryotic cells; so named because they are intermediate in thickness between actin filaments and microtubules.
label: Intermediate Filament

description: An intermediate filament that is found in the axons of neurons.
label: Neurofilament

description: A class of intermediate filaments that form a network within epithelial cells and anchor to desmosomes, thus imparting tensile strength to the tissue
label: Keratin Filament

description: An intermediate filament located in the nucleus of a cell, which plays a role in the maintenance of nuclear structure.
label: Nuclear Lamin

description: A type of intermediate filament that can form either homodimeric or heterodimeric complexes.
label: Type III Intermediate Filament

description: A type III intermediate filament protein found in striated muscle cells that provides cytoskeletal integrity and strength.
label: Paranemin

description: The finest filamentous element of the cytoskeleton, having a diameter of about 5 nm and consisting primarily of actin.
label: Actin Filament

description: The monomeric form of actin.
label: G-actin

description: A fibrillar actin polymer.
label: F-actin

description: Microtubules of the eukaryotic cytoskeleton perform essential and diverse functions and are composed of a heterodimer of alpha and beta tubulin. The genes encoding these microtubule constituents are part of the tubulin superfamily, which is composed of six distinct families. Genes from the alpha, beta and gamma tubulin families are found in all eukaryotes. The alpha and beta tubulins represent the major components of microtubules, while gamma tubulin plays a critical role in the nucleation of microtubule assembly. There are multiple alpha and beta tubulin genes and they are highly conserved among and between species. (from LocusLink)
label: Microtubule

description: A structure made of three cylindrical tubulin polymers.
label: Microtubule Triplet

description: A microtubule that is part of a cilium.
label: Cilium Microtubule

description: A complete cylindrical microtubule that is part of a microtubule doublet in cilia.
label: A-Microtubule

description: An incomplete or c-shaped microtubule that is part of a microtubule doublet in cilia.
label: B-Microtubule

description: A microtubule that has a C-shape in cross-section.
label: C-Microtubule

description: A slender projection of the plasma membrane at the leading edge of migrating cells. This protrusion contains bundles of long, crosslinked actin filaments.
label: Filopodia

description: The cytoplasmic-facing layer of the plasma membrane.
label: Inner Leaflet of the Lipid Bilayer

description: The space between the outer membrane and the inner membrane of the mitochondrion.
label: Intermembrane Space of the Mitochondrion

description: A protein complex containing one alpha tubulin and one beta tubulin.
label: Dimeric Tubulin Molecule

description: A protein complex associated with the distal end of the centriole which that is involved in centriole localization.
label: Distal Connecting Fiber

description: A portion of the interior of the centriole that is located near the plus ends of the microtubules.
label: Distal Part of the Lumen of the Centriole

description: The space bounded by the nine microtubule triplets of the centriole.
label: Internal Lumen of the Centriole

description: The faces of the lipid bilayer that are exposed to the cytoplasm and extracellular space. It is comprised of the hydrophilic heads of the lipid components, exposed surfaces and domains of transmembrane proteins, peripheral proteins and carbohydrate components.
label: Hydrophilic Portion of the Plasma Membrane

description: The inner part of the lipid bilayer that is comprised of the hydrophobic tails of the lipid components and the membrane spanning domains of transmembrane proteins.
label: Hydrophobic Portion of the Plasma Membrane

description: The area within the membrane of an endosomal compartment.
label: Lumen of the Endosome

description: The area within the membrane of a lysosome.
label: Lumen of the Lysosome

description: The area within the membrane of a peroxisome.
label: Lumen of the Peroxisome

description: The end of an actin filament that is polymerizing at a slower rate.
label: Minus End of the Actin Filament

description: The end of a microtubule where nucleation occurs.
label: Minus End of the Microtubule

description: A thin space between the outer and inner mitochondrial membranes formed by an invagination of the inner mitochondrial membrane.
label: Mitochondrial Crista

description: The area that is internal to the inner mitochondrial membrane.
label: Mitochondrial Matrix

description: A detectable particle containing phospholipids, protein and calcium found in the mitochondrial matrix.
label: Mitochondrial Matrix Granule

description: A sheet-like cellular projection that is supported by an ordered network of actin microfilaments. This structure is involved in cellular motility and can define the leading edge of a migrating cell.
label: Lamellipodia

description: A protein complex found in the membrane of the lysosome that transports hydrogen ions into the lumen to increase its acidity.
label: Lysosome Proton Pump

description: The area between the inner and outer nuclear membranes that is contiguous with the lumen of the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
label: Perinuclear Cisternal Space

description: A thread-like complex of ribosomal components including ribosomal RNA, in various stages of transcription, and associated proteins.
label: Nucleolar Fibrillar Material

description: A collection of preribosomes in the nucleolus.
label: Nucleolar Granular Material

description: The irregular network or rows of fine ribonucleoprotein granules or microfilaments forming most of the nucleolus.
label: Nucleolonema

description: A network of membrane components where both post-translational modification and sorting of proteins takes place.
label: Medial Golgi

description: The extracellular facing lipid layer of the plasma membrane.
label: Outer Leaflet of the Lipid Bilayer

description: A lipid with 2 fatty acid chains attached to a carbohydrate-containing head group that is found on the outer leaflet of the plasma membrane.
label: Plasma Membrane Glycolipid

description: The end of an actin filament that is polymerizing at a faster rate.
label: Plus End of the Actin Filament

description: The end of a microtubule where tubulin polymerization occurs.
label: Plus End of the Microtubule

description: A protein complex associated with the distal end of the centriole that is involved in centriole localization.
label: Proximal Connecting Fiber

description: A portion of the interior of the centriole that is located near the minus ends of the microtubules.
label: Proximal Part of the Lumen of the Centriole

description: An enzyme found in the mitochondrial matrix that catalyzes a reaction that is a part of the citric acid cycle, which convert the products of glycolysis into the substrates for the electron transport chain.
label: Soluble Enzyme of the Citric Acid Cycle

description: The Voltage-Dependent Anion Channel (VDAC) is a small, abundant pore-forming eukaryotic protein in the outer mitochondrial membrane thought to form the major pathway for movement of adenine nucleotides through the outer membrane and to be the mitochondrial binding site for hexokinase and glycerol kinase.
label: Voltage-Dependent Anion Channel

description: Any component associated with of the base of the skull and facial bones, sinuses, orbits, salivary glands, oral cavity, oropharynx, larynx, thyroid, facial and neck musculature and lymph nodes draining these areas.
label: Head and Neck Part

description: The space between a tooth and the surrounding gingival tissue and lined by the sulcular epithelium.
label: Gingival Sulcus

description: A groove between the base of the tongue and the palatine tonsil.
label: Glossopharyngeal Sulcus

description: The dorsal portion of the oropharyngeal cavity that is formed by the muscular pharyngeal wall comprising the superior and middle pharyngeal constrictor muscles.
label: Posterior Wall of the Oropharynx

description: The posterior one third of the tongue behind the terminal sulcus that forms the anterior aspect of the oro-pharynx responsible for swallowing and modification of the voice in speech.
label: Base of Tongue

description: The roof of the oral cavity. It separates the oral cavity from the nasal cavity.
label: Palate

description: The proximal portion of the respiratory passages on either side of the nasal septum lying between the floor of the cranium and the roof of the mouth and extending from the face to the pharynx. The nasal cavity is lined with ciliated mucosa, extending from the nares to the pharynx.
label: Nasal Cavity

description: A hollow tube that starts posterior to the mouth and nasal cavity and ends superior to the trachea and esophagus.
label: Pharynx

description: Paired, almond-shaped exocrine glands situated superior and posterior to each orbit of the eye that produce and secrete the watery serous component of tears.
label: Lacrimal Gland

description: Serous gland with distended lumen. It includes the gland of Krause in the lacrimal sac and the gland of Wolfring on the inner surface of the upper eyelid.
label: Accessory Lacrimal Gland

description: The small accessory lacrimal glands on the upper and lower eyelids that secrete tears. There are approximately 42 glands on the upper lid and 6-8 glands on the lower lid.
label: Gland of Krause

description: The larger accessory lacrimal glands on the upper and lower eyelids that secrete tears. There are approximately 2-5 glands on the upper lid and 1-3 glands on the lower lid.
label: Gland of Wolfring

description: Fleshy fold which surrounds the opening of the mouth.
label: Lip

description: The lip that covers the anterior portion of the mandible.
label: Lower Lip

description: The bony anterior part of the roof of the mouth separating the nose from the mouth.
label: Hard Palate

description: The muscular extension of the hard palate which comprises the posterior of the oral cavity and the floor of the nasal cavity.
label: Soft Palate

description: The fleshy lobe that hangs at the back of the soft palate.
label: Uvula

description: One of two visible fleshy folds that surround the orifice of the mouth.
label: External Lip

description: The external surface of the upper lip.
label: External Upper Lip

description: The external surface of the lower lip.
label: External Lower Lip

description: The roof of the nasopharynx.
label: Superior Wall of the Nasopharynx

description: The dorsal portion of the nasopharyngeal cavity that contains the pharyngeal tonsil.
label: Posterior Wall of the Nasopharynx

description: The aspect of the nasopharyngeal wall that is located on the side.  It contains the pharyngeal opening of the auditory tube.
label: Lateral Wall of the Nasopharynx

description: The anterior aspect of the nasopharynx.
label: Anterior Wall of the Nasopharynx

description: The lower part of the pharynx that connects to the esophagus.
label: Hypopharynx

description: A groove between the base of the tongue and the epiglottis.
label: Vallecula

description: The junction of the upper and lower lips at the corner of the mouth.
label: Commissure of the Lip

description: The region of the hypopharynx demarcated by a plane drawn at the level of the tip of the epiglottis to a plane at the inferior border of the cricoid.
label: Posterior Wall of the Hypopharynx

description: The aspect of the oropharyngeal wall that is located on the side.
label: Lateral Wall of the Oropharynx

description: The upper part of the larynx, including the epiglottis; the area above the vocal cords.
label: Supraglottis

description: The area of the larynx below the vocal cords down to the trachea.
label: Subglottis

description: The cartilaginous structure of the respiratory tract between the pharynx and the trachea. It contains elastic vocal cords required for sound production.
label: Larynx

description: The part of the pharynx in the back of the throat, at and above the soft palate. The nasopharynx is continuous with the nasal passages.
label: Nasopharynx

description: The hard bonelike structures in the jaws of vertebrates; primarily used for eating.
label: Tooth

description: Any of the 32 teeth that replace the deciduous teeth of early childhood.
label: Permanent Tooth

description: One of the two permanent teeth located in front of the molars and behind each cuspid. These teeth have two cusps (points) and are used to tear and grind food.
label: Bicuspid Tooth

description: A single-cusped (pointed) and usually single-rooted tooth located between the incisors and premolars.
label: Canine Tooth

description: A grinding tooth with a broad crown; located behind the premolars.
label: Molar Tooth

description: Any of the molars located in the mandible.
label: Lower Jaw Molar

description: The first, permanent, six-year molar of the lower right arch as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 30

description: The first, permanent, six-year molar of the lower left arch as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 19

description: The lower left 3rd molar, as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 17

description: The lower left 2nd molar, as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 18

description: The lower right 2nd molar, as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 31

description: The lower right 3rd molar, as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 32

description: Any of the molars located in the upper jaw.
label: Upper Jaw Molar

description: The upper right 3rd molar, as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 1

description: The upper left 2nd molar, as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 15

description: The upper left 3rd molar, as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 16

description: The upper right 2nd molar, as defined by the Universal tooth numbering system.
label: Tooth 2

description: Any one of the rearmost molars on each side of the upper and lower jaw in humans.
label: Third Molar

description: One of the teeth in front of the canines in either jaw designed for cutting or gnawing.
label: Incisor

description: Either of the incisors found in the mandible.
label: Lower Jaw Incisor

description: Either of the incisors found in the upper jaw.
label: Upper Jaw Incisor

description: Any of the teeth of the first dentition, which are usually shed and replaced by the permanent teeth.
label: Temporary Tooth

description: Any of the teeth located in the mandible.
label: Lower Jaw Tooth

description: Any of the teeth located in the upper jaw.
label: Upper Jaw Tooth

description: Refers to teeth and tissues towards the back of the mouth (distal to the canines): maxillary and mandibular premolars and molars. The designation of permanent posterior teeth in the Universal tooth numbering system include teeth 1 through 5 and 12 through 16 (maxillary), and 17 through 21 and 28 through 32 (mandibular); primary teeth in the Universal tooth numbering system are designated A, B, I, and J (maxillary) and K, L, S, and T (mandibular).
label: Posterior Tooth

description: A tooth with functioning pulpal tissue.
label: Vital Tooth

description: The tooth, teeth, or implant that supports a fixed bridge or removable prosthesis.
label: Abutment

description: A small cartilagenous flap-like valve that closes over the larynx during swallowing to prevent food entering the lungs.
label: Epiglottis

description: The space in which the vocal cords are located.
label: Glottis

description: The part of the pharynx between the soft palate and the upper portion of the epiglottis.
label: Oropharynx

description: A pair of small bands of muscle that stretch from the thyroid cartilage in front to the arytenoid cartilage in back of the larynx. The vocal cords help prevent food entering the lungs and produce sound through vibration.
label: Vocal Cord

description: One of two folds of a mucous membrane spanning the larynx. The two folds aid in breathing and preventing regurgitation to a greater extent than producing sounds.
label: False Vocal Cord

description: The lower pair of vocal folds located below the glottis, which are the primary source of phonation
label: True Vocal Cord

description: The anterior-most portion of the vocal cord, located within the larynx, that constitutes the junction of the conus elasticus and the thyroepiglottic, vestibular, and vocal ligaments.
label: Laryngeal Anterior Commissure

description: The bottom part of the palatine tonsil where it blends into the lingual tonsil tissue.
label: Glossotonsillar Sulcus

description: The walls of the swallowing passage.
label: Wall of the Pharynx

description: The walls on either side of the swallowing passage.
label: Lateral Wall of the Pharynx

description: The dorsal portion of the fibromuscular tube that extends from the skull base to the lower border of the cricoid cartilage, and acts as a conduit for both the digestive and respiratory systems.
label: Posterior Wall of the Pharynx

description: The fleshy part of the face bounded by the eyes, nose, ear, and jaw line.
label: Cheek

description: The development and arrangement of teeth in the mouth.
label: Dentition

description: A recess located behind the ostium of the eustachian tube. It is the most common site of origin for nasopharyngeal carcinoma.
label: Pharyngeal Recess

description: The flat area on either side of the head that is located posterior to the eye and forehead, anterior to the ear, and superior to the cheek bone.
label: Temple

description: The structures that surround and contact the parotid gland, forming the boundaries of the parotid space.
label: Parotid Bed

description: The area inside the mouth between the cheek or lips, and the teeth.
label: Vestibule of Mouth

description: The area of the mouth between the cheeks and the teeth of the mandible.
label: Mandibular Vestibule of the Mouth

description: The area of the mouth between the cheeks and the teeth of the maxilla.
label: Maxillary Vestibule of the Mouth

description: The outside wall of the nasal passages.
label: Lateral Wall of the Nose

description: The most anterior part of the nasal cavity, lined by squamous epithelium.
label: Nasal Vestibule

description: The portion of the parotid gland that is superficial to the facial vein and facial nerve.
label: Parotid Gland Superficial Lobe

description: The posterior surface of the glottic opening at the level of the vocal cords.
label: Laryngeal Posterior Commissure

description: The anatomic space comprising the sinonasal tract and the oral cavity.
label: Sinonasal Tract and Oral Cavity

description: A narrow channel that connects the frontal sinus, anterior ethmoid air cells, and maxillary sinus to the middle meatus, allowing drainage and ventilation. It includes the maxillary ostium, infundibulum, ethmoid bulla, uncinate process, and hiatus semilunaris.
label: Ostiomeatal Complex

description: The curved or bowlike structure formed by the arrangement of teeth within the jaw.
label: Dental Arch

description: The elliptical shaped curve of the bottom border of the upper eyelid, extending from the medial canthus to the lateral canthus.
label: Palpebral Fissure

description: The structures of the lacrimal system (upper and lower puncta, canaliculi, lacrimal sac, nasolacrimal duct) that serve as conduit for tear flow from the eye to the nasal cavity.
label: Lacrimal Drainage System

description: The anatomical opening formed by the arch of the hard palate at the back of the mouth, where the oral cavity and pharynx meet.
label: Oropharyngeal Isthmus

description: The creases or folds in the oral mucosa covering the roof of the oral cavity.
label: Palatal Rugae

description: The peripheral edge of the tongue that delineates the tongue from adjacent structures in the oral cavity.
label: Border of Tongue

description: The inferior surface of the tongue, which is adjacent to the floor of the mouth. It is attached to the floor of the mouth by the frenulum.
label: Ventral Surface of Tongue

description: The anterior two thirds of the tongue, roughly corresponding to the portion of the tongue anterior to the sulcus terminalis.
label: Anterior Two-Thirds of Tongue

description: A central core of loosely arranged stellate cells located between the outer and inner epithelial enamel of the developing tooth.
label: Stellate Reticulum

description: A layer of condensed cells in the developing tooth that is located between the inner enamel epithelium and the stellate reticulum.
label: Stratum Intermedium

description: The anterior extreme of the tongue which can be made pointed for sensing or probing and which rests against the lingual aspect of the incisor teeth.
label: Apex of Tongue

description: A membranous fold extending between the arytenoid cartilage and the epiglottis.
label: Aryepiglottic Fold

description: A lacrimal duct found in the majority of the population, which is formed by the union of the superior and inferior lacrimal canaliculi, and which connects to the lacrimal sac. In a small percentage of people the common duct is absent, and the superior and inferior lacrimal canaliculi enter the lacrimal sac separately.
label: Common Canaliculus

description: Any accessory organ of the eye, including the eyelids, eyebrows, lacrimal apparatus, or conjunctiva.
label: Eye Appendage

description: A thin, transparent tissue divided into the palpebral conjunctiva (covering the inner side of the eye lid) and the bulbar conjunctiva (covering the eyeball).
label: Conjunctiva

description: The part of the conjunctiva, a thin transparent mucous membrane, that covers the posterior surface of the eyelids.
label: Palpebral Conjunctiva

description: The part of the conjunctiva, a thin transparent mucous membrane, that is loosely attached the orbital septum and covers the anterior surface of the sclera.
label: Bulbar Conjunctiva

description: A thin membrane of skin with the purpose of covering and protecting an eye.
label: Eyelid

description: The small thin membrane of skin extending from below the orbit and that covers the bottom portion of the eye.
label: Lower Eyelid

description: The larger thin membrane of skin extending from above the orbit and that covers a great portion of the eye.
label: Upper Eyelid

description: The arched strip of hair on the bony ridge above each eye socket.
label: Eyebrow

description: The organs associated with the production and removal of tears including the secretory glands, drainage system, and nerves.
label: Lacrimal Apparatus

description: The superior, convex surface of the tongue, which is divided by the sulcus terminalis into anterior or oral (presulcal) and posterior or pharyngeal (postsulcal) parts. The mucosal membrane of the anterior two-thirds contain numerous varieties of papillae while the posterior one-third has no papillae and a cobblestone appearance due to underlying nodules of lymphoid tissue.
label: Dorsum of Tongue

description: The portion of the aryepiglottic fold in the area where the larynx and esophagus join.
label: Hypopharyngeal Aspect of the Aryteno-Epiglottic Fold

description: Either of two ducts (superior and inferior) that originate at the puncta lacrimalia of the eye and terminate at the lacrimal sac.
label: Lacrimal Canaliculus

description: A tube-like structure that conveys tears from the lacrimal sac to the nasal cavity.
label: Nasolacrimal Duct

description: A crease in the skin of the lower eyelid.
label: Inferior Palpebral Fold

description: An oval shaped cavity at the upper extremity of the nasal duct.
label: Lacrimal Sac

description: A fusiform fossa on the lateral sides of the larynx between the inferior and superior vocal cords.
label: Laryngeal Ventricle

description: A chamber, continuous with collections of mastoid cells throughout the mastoid portion of the temporal bone, connecting the tympanic cavity with the mastoid process.
label: Opening of the Antrum

description: A crease in the skin of the upper eyelid.
label: Superior Palpebral Fold

description: A dense fibrous tissue layer located in the eyelid, which gives the lids shape, strength, and a place for muscles to attach. It contains numerous Meibomian glands.
label: Tarsal Plate

description: The portion of the hypopharynx that is located posteriorly to the larynx.
label: Postcricoid Region

description: A triangular-shaped area of mucosa located posterior the last mandibular molar tooth.
label: Retromolar Trigone

description: The lips are the structures that surround the mouth, which is the oral aperture that opens into the oral cavity. The oral cavity is the space bounded superiorly by the hard and soft palates, inferiorly by the tongue and laterally by the cheeks.
label: Lip and Oral Cavity

description: The medial corner of the eye where the upper and lower eyelids join.
label: Inner Canthus

description: The lateral corner of the eye where the upper and lower eyelids join.
label: Outer Canthus

description: The narrow passage from the mouth to the cavity at the back of the mouth.
label: Throat

description: The area of the head comprised of the nasal cavity and paranasal sinuses.
label: Sinonasal Tract

description: The horseshoe-shaped part of the oral cavity bounded superiorly by the ventral surface of the tongue, inferiorly by the mylohyoid muscle, anterolaterally by the gingival surfaces of the mandible, and posteriorly by the anterior tonsillar pillar.
label: Floor of Mouth

description: The anterior aspect of the floor of the mouth.
label: Anterior Floor of Mouth

description: The lateral aspect of the floor of the mouth.
label: Lateral Floor of Mouth

description: The crest of the gingiva surrounding a tooth.
label: Gingival Margin

description: Any part of a tooth.
label: Tooth Part

description: The portion of a tooth between the crown and the root.
label: Collum Dentis

description: The portion of the tooth covered by enamel.
label: Crown

description: The part of a tooth below the neck of the tooth which is covered by cementum.
label: Root

description: The portion of the pulp chamber that extends towards a cusp.
label: Pulp Horn

description: Grooves or clefts in the surface of a tooth.
label: Dental Fissure

description: The gingival margins of the tooth surfaces.
label: Class V Surface

description: Minute branching canals in the tooth dentin that contain filamentous protoplasmic processes of the odontoblasts and extend radially from the pulp to the dentoenamel junction.
label: Dentinal Tubule

description: The area of a tooth where the enamel of the crown and the cementum of the root(s) are joined.
label: Cementoenamel Junction

description: The region of a multirooted tooth at which the root divides.
label: Root Furcation

description: The central cavity of the tooth crown that is occupied by the dental pulp.
label: Pulp Chamber

description: A raised area of the biting surface of a tooth.
label: Tooth Cusp

description: The cutting edge of an incisor tooth.
label: Incisal Edge

description: The area of a tooth where the enamel and the underlying dentin are joined.
label: Dental-Enamel Junction

description: The interface between the more apically located alveolar mucosa and the more coronally located gingiva.
label: Mucogingival Junction

description: The part of the face below the lower lip and including the protruding part of the lower jaw.
label: Mentum

description: The thickened bony structures in the mandible and maxilla that contain the sockets of the teeth.
label: Alveolar Ridge

description: The alveolar ridge of the maxilla.
label: Upper Alveolar Ridge

description: The alveolar ridge of the mandible.
label: Lower Alveolar Ridge

description: The part of the face between the eyebrows and the normal hairline.
label: Forehead

description: The superficial areas of head and neck including the oral cavity, buccal mucosa, and the parotid region.
label: Non-Parameningeal Head and Neck Area

description: The point at which the gingival sulcus terminates because the tissue attaches directly to the tooth.
label: Bottom of Gingival Sulcus

description: The portion of the parotid gland parenchyma lying deep to the facial nerve.
label: Parotid Gland Deep Lobe

description: Any component of the enveloping membrane of the body, including the epidermis and dermis, and all of the derivatives of the epidermis.
label: Integumentary System Part

description: Any component of the organ that constitutes the external surface of the body, including the epidermis, dermis, and skin appendages.
label: Skin Part

description: The part of the epidermis layer of the skin containing Langerhans cells, which are dendritic, MHC class II-expressing antigen presenting cells.
label: Stratum Spinosum

description: The deepest layer of the epidermis, which is adjacent to the dermis, and which is the primary location of mitotically active cells of the epidermis.
label: Stratum Basale

description: A compact sublayer of stratum corneum in the epidermis.
label: Stratum Conjunctum

description: The most superficial layer of the epidermis and the surface coating of the skin, primarily consisting of layers of corneocytes, which are dead, flat, enucleated, keratin-filled cells. The stratum corneum serves as a physiological barrier for the protection of underlying tissues, as well as a barrier to fluid and solute loss from within the body.
label: Stratum Corneum

description: The more superficial and permeable sublayer of the stratum corneum.
label: Stratum Disjunctum

description: A thin layer of cells in the epidermis that is located between the stratum lucidum and the stratum spinosum.
label: Stratum Granulosum

description: A translucent layer of the epidermis comprising dead, clear cells located between the stratum corneum and the stratum granulosum; it is only found in areas of thick skin, including the palms of the hand and the soles of the feet.
label: Stratum Lucidum

description: The most superficial layer of the dermis, located immediately inferior to the epidermal basement membrane, comprising loose areolar connective tissue with projections of dermal papilla into the epidermis.
label: Stratum Papillare

description: The deepest layer of the dermis, located immediately inferior to the stratum papillae, comprising dense, irregular connective tissue and an abundance of nerves and blood vessels.
label: Stratum Reticulare

description: The deepest layer of the epidermis, which includes both the stratum basale and stratum spinosum as a single layer.
label: Rete Malpighii

description: Part of the infrastructure of the collagen fiber. Individual collagen polypeptides assemble into trimers that that assemble into a fibril, which then form a fiber.
label: Collagen Fibril

description: list()
label: Elastin Fiber

description: The grooves in the outermost layer of skin on the palms of the hands and soles of the feet where sweat glands open.
label: Epidermal Ridge

description: A site of slightly thickened desmosomes in the stratum spinosum of the epidermis.
label: Node of Bizzozero

description: Tissue composed of three layers- epidermis, dermis and subcutis which protect underlying muscles and organs. Skin is used for insulation, vitamin D production, sensation, and excretion through sweat.
label: Skin Tissue

description: The lower layer of the skin containing connective tissue, blood vessels, oil and sweat glands, nerves, hair follicles and other structures.
label: Dermis

description: The skin layer that separates the papillary dermis from the reticular dermis.
label: Papillary-Reticular Dermal Interface

description: The lower portion of the dermis beneath the papillary dermis. It is composed of thick collagen fibers.
label: Reticular Dermis

description: The upper portion of the dermis beneath the epidermis. It is composed of thin collagen fibers.
label: Papillary Dermis

description: The epithelial portion of the skin (cutis). It consists of the following layers: stratum corneum (horny layer), stratum granulosum (granular layer), stratum spinosum (prickle cell layer), and stratum basale (basal cell layer).
label: Epidermis

description: Adipose tissue located under the dermis. It binds underlying structures with the skin. The subcutis is important in the regulation of temperature of the skin itself and the body. The size of this layer varies throughout the body and from person to person.
label: Subcutis

description: list()
label: Dermo-Epidermal Junction

description: A projection of the dermis into the epidermis.
label: Dermal Papilla

description: The part of the nail bed that contains nerves and vessels.
label: Nail Matrix

description: The integument under the nail plate.
label: Nail Bed

description: The area underneath a fingernail or toenail.
label: Subungual Space

description: Part of the horny plate, which is attached to the nail bed, and is the intervening portion between the cuticle and the free edge of the nail.
label: Body of the Nail

description: The filamentous outgrowth of the epidermis.
label: Hair

description: Anyone of the short hairs that grow on the edge of the eyelid.
label: Eyelash

description: Hair growing in the pubic area.
label: Pubic Hair

description: The side of the nail extending over the finger or toe which can be trimmed.
label: Free Edge of the Nail

description: A pale, convex shaped area on the surface of the proximal end of the nail plate.
label: Lunula

description: The cutaneous plate on the dorsal surface of the distal end of a finger or toe.
label: Nail

description: A thin, horny translucent plate covering the end of each toe.
label: Toenail

description: The nail at the end of a finger.
label: Fingernail

description: The most proximal region of the nail plate, which is located underneath the skinfold, and which is formed from the nail matrix.
label: Root of the Nail

description: Any component of the filamentous outgrowth of the epidermis.
label: Hair Part

description: A tube-like invagination of the epidermis from which the hair shaft develops and into which the sebaceous glands open; the follicle is lined by a cellular inner and outer root sheath of epidermal origin and is invested with a fibrous sheath derived from the dermis.
label: Hair Follicle

description: The lower segment of the hair that circles the dermal papilla and the hair matrix.
label: Hair Bulb

description: The lower portion of a hair follicle from the base of the bulb to the arrector pili muscle.
label: Hair Follicle Inferior Segment

description: The upper portion of a hair follicle extending from the sebaceous gland duct to the follicular orifice.
label: Hair Follicle Infundibulum

description: The middle segment of a hair follicle that extends from the insertion of the erector pili muscle to the entrance of the sebaceous gland duct.
label: Hair Follicle Isthmus

description: The portion at the base of the hair follicle containing blood vessels and the matrix.
label: Hair Papilla

description: The portion of the hair that is enclosed within the hair follicle.
label: Hair Root

description: The segment of the hair that projects above the skin surface.
label: Shaft of the Hair

description: An outer layer of stratified epithelium contiguous with the epidermis surrounding the hair follicle, which is thinnest at the level of the bulb and thickest in the middle portion of the hair follicle.
label: Outer Root Sheath

description: list()
label: Pilar Sheath

description: Any component of the anatomical structure consisting of similarly specialized cells and intercellular matrix, aggregated according to genetically determined spatial relationships, performing a specific function.
label: Tissue Part

description: A tag or fold of skin or mucous tissue that extends from an anatomical structure without bony support.
label: Fleshy Tab

description: Any structures that are not enclosed intracellularly are considered extracellular structure, including structures on the cell surface. (NCI)
label: Extracellular Structure

description: The extracellular matrix is a network of fibers that hold cells together. It is found within the extracellular space and in association with the basement membrane of the cell surface. It promotes cellular proliferation and provides a supporting structure to which cells or cell lysates in culture dishes adhere. It is broken down during normal physiological and disease processes such as bone remodeling, embryogenesis, cancer, and arthritis.
label: Extracellular Matrix

description: A network of extracellular fibrillar structures containing granule proteins, chromatin fibers and DNA that are released by neutrophils as part of the host defense response. Extracellular release of antimicrobial proteins such as neutrophil elastase, cathepsin G and histones can bind, disarm, and kill microbes independent of phagocytosis and the fibrillar nature of these structures may target these effects locally by preventing diffusion of these proteins outside the target site.
label: Neutrophil Extracellular Trap

description: A filamentous extracellular structure that is rich in the glycoprotein, fibrillin-1, and found in connective tissues where it can act as a scaffold for elastin.
label: Fibrillin Microfibrils

description: A layer of extracellular matrix found beneath the single pavement layer of cells which line the luminal surface of the entire vascular system.
label: Basal Lamina of the Vascular Endothelium

description: One of three main components of connective tissue (fibers, ground substance and cells), of which there are three types: collagenous (thick bundles of collagen), reticular (thin bundles of collagen), and elastic fibers (branching bundles of elastin).
label: Connective Tissue Fiber

description: Proteinaceous fibrils found in connective tissue that are comprised of type III collagen and form a mesh that can support soft tissue structure.
label: Reticular Fiber

description: A structural protein and connective tissue component in fiber form composed of numerous fine fibrils, which provides strength and flexibility to tissue.
label: Collagen Fiber

description: A type of connective tissue consisting of an outer mantel of microfibrils and an amorphous elastin inner core capable of repetitive cycles of extension and recoil.
label: Elastic Fiber

description: The body substance in which tissue cells are embedded.
label: Ground Substance

description: Small nerve fibers that innervate blood vessels.
label: Nervi Vascularis

description: A layer of connective tissue that is located between the endothelium and the internal elastic lamina of the tunica intima of blood vessels, which is, depending on the vessel, highly variable in its size.
label: Subendothelial Layer

description: Any component of the avascular cellular layers that cover body surfaces and cavities and may form glands.
label: Epithelium Part

description: Ubiquitous supportive tissue adjacent to epithelium and around smooth and striated muscle cells. This tissue contains intrinsic macromolecular components such as collagen, laminin, and sulfated proteoglycans. As seen by light microscopy one of its subdivisions is the basal (basement) lamina.
label: Basement Membrane

description: A transparent homogeneous acellular layer, 6 to 9 um thick, lying between the basal lamina of the outer layer of stratified epithelium and the substantia propria of the cornea; it is considered to be a basement membrane.
label: Bowman's Membrane

description: A sheet of amorphous extracellular material upon which the basal surfaces of epithelial cells rest and is the covering surface of a glomerular capillary, interposed between the cellular elements and the underlying connective tissue.
label: Glomerular Basement Membrane

description: A thin hyaline membrane between the chief part of the sclera and the endothelial layer of the cornea.
label: Descemet's Membrane

description: list()
label: Bronchus Basement Membrane

description: list()
label: Renal Tubule Basement Membrane

description: list()
label: Trachea Basement Membrane

description: The free part of the epithelium that faces the exterior surface or the lumen of an organ.  It may contain cytoplasmic processes (microvilli, stereocilia, and cilia).
label: Apical Domain of the Epithelium

description: The free part of the epithelium that faces the interior surface of the lumen of an organ or towards the interstitium.
label: Basal Domain of the Epithelium

description: A layer of extracellular matrix found beneath epithelial tissues. It is secreted by epithelial cells and comprised of proteoglycans, laminin and type IV collagen.
label: Basal Lamina

description: list()
label: Bronchus Basal Lamina

description: list()
label: Trachea Basal Lamina

description: A family of large fibrous proteins contained within the layer of extracellular matrix found beneath epithelial tissues.
label: Basal Lamina Collagen

description: An organelle that protrudes outward from the cell body. It consists of a specialized arrangement of 9 doublet microtubules in a ring with or without a core of 2 microtubules and is enclosed in a plasma membrane coat. Motile cilia contain the motor protein dynein.
label: Cilium

description: The finger-like projections that increase the surface area of the apical membrane of the thin layer of tissue that covers organs, glands, and other structures within the body.
label: Epithelial Microvillus

description: A non-motile microvillus-like structure found in certain epithelial tissues. It is comprised of plasma membrane that is supported by longitudinal actin filaments.
label: Stereocilium

description: A structure created by the folding over of the thin layer of tissue that covers organs, glands, and other structures within the body.
label: Epithelial Plica

description: A motile cilium-like structure found in hair cells of the sensory epithelium of the inner ear. It has a core microtubule structure similar to that of a cilium.
label: Kinocilium

description: An electron-lucent layer within the basement membrane zone between the lamina densa and the epidermis comprised mainly of laminin.
label: Lamina Lucida

description: The non-free sides of an epithelial cell that connect to other epithelial cells when forming the epithelium.
label: Lateral Domain of the Epithelium

description: Complexes of tight and adherent junctions formed where the cytoplasmic leaflets of epithelial cells meet.
label: Terminal Bar

description: Any component of the thin sheet or layer of pliable tissue, serving as a covering or envelope of a part, as the lining of a cavity, as a partition or septum, or to connect two structures.
label: Membrane Part

description: The part of the pericardial sac that surrounds the great vessels.
label: Apex of the Pericardium

description: The inferior surface of the conical membranous sac in which the heart and roots of the aorta and other large blood vessels are contained. This surface rests on the diaphragm and is fused with the diaphragm's central tendons.
label: Base of the Pericardium

description: The portion of the serious membrane that composes the lining of the abdominal cavity.
label: Parietal Part of the Peritoneum

description: The peritoneal reflection of the superior part of the posterior wall of the vagina, anterior to the rectum, which is the deepest point of the peritoneal cavity in females.
label: Recto-Vaginal Pouch

description: The peritoneal reflection between the urinary bladder and the rectum in males.
label: Recto-Vesical Pouch

description: A peritoneal recess in the female pelvis that is located between the uterus and the bladder.
label: Utero-Vesical Pouch

description: The serous membrane that covers the surface of all organs located in the peritoneal cavity.
label: Visceral Part of the Peritoneum

description: Any component associated with the anatomic structures in the head responsible for special sensations rather than general sensations, including the eyes, ears, nose, and tongue.
label: Organ of Special Sense Part

description: Any component pertaining to the organ for hearing including the external, middle, and inner ear.
label: Ear Part

description: The part of the ear including the eardrum and ossicles. The middle ear leads to the inner ear.
label: Middle Ear

description: The external part of the ear.
label: External Ear

description: The snail shell-shaped auditory component of the inner ear. It contains the sensory organ of hearing.
label: Cochlea

description: A tubular structure that runs from the middle ear to the nasopharynx and is approximately 3-4 cm length. Its lumen is roughly triangular and has average diameter of 2-3 mm. The lumen is lined by ciliated pseudostratified, columnar epithelium, which sweeps material from the middle ear to the nasopharynx. It is functionally collapsed at rest, with slight negative pressure present in the middle ear, and opens during swallowing, sneezing, and yawning.  It serves to ventilate pressure differences between the middle ear and nasopharynx. This tube also allows middle ear secretions to drain into the nasopharynx.
label: Eustachian Tube

description: A part of the ear canal that is external to the ear drum.
label: External Acoustic Meatus

description: The portion of the ear located within the temporal bone that is involved in both hearing and balance and includes the semicircular canals, vestibule, and cochlea. (from American Heritage Dictionary online)
label: Inner Ear

description: A bony pouch in the tympanic cavity that is sealed by the secondary tympanic membrane.
label: Round Window Niche

description: A small curved flap of auricular cartilage on the external ear anterior to the concha and inferior to the crux of the helix.
label: Tragus

description: A sensory receptor of the ear located in the membranous ampulla of the semicircular duct.
label: Ampullary Crest

description: The irregular lower chamber of the middle ear.
label: Atrium of the Middle Ear

description: The three small bones in the middle ear that transmit acoustic vibrations from the eardrum to the inner ear.
label: Auditory Ossicle

description: The smallest and most medial of the three auditory ossicles located in the middle ear, which functions in concert with the remaining ossicles to transmit vibrations from the tympanic membrane into the inner ear.
label: Stapes

description: One of the three bones comprising the middle ear. This anvil-shaped bone is positioned between the malleus and the stapes.
label: Incus

description: A hammer-shaped bone, part of three interconnected small bones located in the middle ear. It is attached to the inner surface of the tympanic membrane and its function is to transmit sound vibrations.
label: Malleus

description: The external shell-like structure of ear on the side of the head.
label: Auricle

description: A fluid-filled membrane suspended in the osseous cochlea of the inner ear, which contains the cochlear duct and the perilymphatic space.
label: Cochlear Labyrinth

description: A bone structure within the semicircular canal of the inner ear.
label: Common Bony Limb

description: The anterior aspect of the tympanum.
label: Anterior Wall of the Tympanum

description: The curved cartilage ridge on the flap of the ear that is parallel to the helix.
label: Antihelix

description: A projection or prominence opposite the tragus that is found on the lower exterior portion of the ear.
label: Antitragus

description: The concave area of the auricle next to the ear canal.
label: Concha

description: The external rim of the auricula (ear).
label: Crus Helicis

description: A channel or tunnel for the tensor tympani muscle within the tympanic cavity which acts to dull sounds.
label: Canal for Tensor Tympani

description: The cavity-like space in the lower portion of the concha that forms the vestibule, leading to the external acoustic meatus.
label: Cavum Conchae

description: A hollow area in the upper portion of the tympanic cavity.
label: Epitympanic Recess

description: The superior part of the concha (a fossa of the external ear).
label: Cymba Conchae

description: An oval, membrane covered opening from the tympanic cavity of the middle ear to the vestibule of the inner ear.
label: Fenestra Ovalis

description: An opening into the cochlea of the inner ear that allows for fluid within the cochlea to move.
label: Fenestra Rotunda

description: The cells forming the inner spiraled tunnel walls in the organ of Corti within the inner ear.
label: Inner Rod of the Corti

description: The wall facing the inside of the vestibule of the inner ear.
label: Inner Wall of the Vestibule

description: An opening in the cochlea where the scala tympani and scala vestibuli join to communicate.
label: Helicotrema

description: A twisted curved structure such as a coil spring or corkscrew.
label: Helix

description: The internal wall of the tympanic cavity.
label: Inner Wall of the Tympanum

description: The soft fleshy portion of the lower external ear composed of areolar and adipose connective tissues.
label: Lobule of the Auricle

description: The conical central core located in the cochlea, which contains the cells of the spiral ganglion.
label: Modiolus

description: The bony projection from the inner wall of the modiolus that makes two and three quarter turns around the modiolus partially dividing the cochlea cavity.
label: Lamina Spiralis Ossea

description: A vestibular receptor area located on the saccule of the membranous labyrinth of the inner ear, which functions to detect vertical linear acceleration and position of the head.
label: Macula of Saccule

description: A vestibular receptor area located on the utricle of the membranous labyrinth of the inner ear, which functions to detect horizontal acceleration and position of the head.
label: Macula of Utricle

description: The portion of the membranous labyrinth found in the cochlea of the inner ear, which contains the organ of corti, and is concerned with hearing.
label: Membranous Canal of the Cochlea

description: Part of the inner ear contained within the bony labyrinth that contains endolymph, and houses specialized sensory receptors involved in hearing and equilibrium.
label: Membranous Labyrinth

description: The principal sensory structure of the auditory system, which is located on the basilar membrane in the cochlea.
label: Organ of Corti

description: The opening of the eustachian tube at its pharyngeal end.
label: Orifice of the Eustachian Tube

description: A part of the inner ear located in the petrous part of the temporal bone consisting of a series of bony cavities that contains the membranous labyrinth, which is structurally and functionally divided into the vestibule, the semicircular canals, and the cochlea.
label: Osseous Labyrinth

description: Crystals of calcium carbonate embedded in the otolithic membrane in the maculae of the saccule and utricle in the inner ear, which comprise the otolith organs containing receptors that respond to gravity and head tilt.
label: Otolith

description: The cells forming the outer spiraled tunnel walls in the organ of Corti within the inner ear.
label: Outer Rod of the Corti

description: The wall facing the outside of the vestibule of the inner ear.
label: Outer Wall of the Vestibule

description: The crest on the medial wall of the tympanic cavity, superior and posterior to the fenestra ovalis, which transmits impulses from the facial nerve, and which is the superior part of the tympanic segment of the bony facial canal.
label: Ridge of the Aqueductus Fallopii

description: A globular sac and one of two otolith organs, the other being the utricle, located in the vestibule of the inner ear near the opening of the scala vestibuli of the cochlea; it has a specialized lining to sense changes in linear acceleration.
label: Saccule

description: list()
label: Pars Externa

description: list()
label: Pars Interna

description: list()
label: Pars Media

description: The wall in the tympanic cavity that opens into the mastoid antrum.
label: Posterior Wall of the Tympanum

description: The bony termination of the septum of the pharyngotympanic tube, superior to the anterior end of the vestibular window, over which the tendon of tensor tympani muscle is stretched, forming a pulley-like mechanism and allowing the tensor tympani to contract and reduce sound transmission.
label: Processus Cochleariformis

description: A prominent bulge in the medial wall of the tympanic cavity, which reflects the basal turn of the cochlea.
label: Promontory

description: Any one of the three curved, tubular canals (posterior, anterior or lateral) containing endolymph and located in the bony labyrinth of the inner ear; all three are important components of the vestibular system.
label: Semicircular Canal

description: A tube extending from the middle ear to the outer ear.
label: External Canal

description: The inferior portion of the semicircular canal found in the inner ear, which detects anterior and posterior rotation of the head.
label: Posterior Semicircular Canal

description: One of the three semicircular canals found in the osseous labyrinth of the inner ear, which detects rotation of the head around a rostral-caudal (anterior-posterior) axis.
label: Superior Semicircular Canal

description: The membranous tube that is located within the osseous semicircular canal.
label: Semicircular Duct

description: A specialized hair cell, located in the organ of corti, and existing in two forms: the outer hair cells, which serve to mechanically amplify incoming sounds, and inner hair cells, which function to convert vibrations into electrical stimuli for transmission to the cochlear nerve.
label: Sensory Hair

description: The six patches of hair cells in the membranous labyrinth located in the receptor organs of the inner ear, including the organ of corti, the macula of the utricle, the macula of the saccule, and the ampullary crest in each of the three semicircular canals.
label: Sensory Receptor of the Ear

description: A hollow conical structure in the inner wall of the middle ear.
label: Pyramid of Tympanum

description: A vestibular sac and the larger of the two otolith organs that is located in the elliptical recess of the vestibule of the inner ear; it contains receptors on a specialized lining that detect linear acceleration in the horizontal direction.
label: Utricle

description: The innermost part of the ear in vertebrates, which primarily functions as sound detection and balance.
label: Vestibular Labyrinth

description: The central cavity of the osseous labyrinth.
label: Vestibule of the Ear

description: A canal in the petrous region of the temporal bone that serves as the passage for cranial nerves (mainly the VII and VIII cranial nerves) towards the middle and inner ear.
label: Internal Auditory Canal

description: Any component associated with the organ for sight or vision.
label: Eye Part

description: The pigmented layer of the eyeball between the tough, white outer coat of the eye and the retina.
label: Uvea

description: The white, opaque, fibrous, outer tunic of the eyeball, covering it entirely excepting the segment covered anteriorly by the cornea. It is essentially avascular but contains apertures for vessels, lymphatics, and nerves. It receives the tendons of insertion of the extraocular muscles and at the corneoscleral junction contains the canal of Schlemm. (From Cline et al., Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed)
label: Sclera

description: A dome-shaped, transparent, avascular tissue covering the front of the eye. It is composed of five layers: squamous epithelium, Bowman's membrane, stroma, Descemet's membrane, and endothelium. Refraction of light contributing to eye's focusing ability is its characteristic function. It contains unmyelinated nerve endings which are responsible for the high sensitivity of the tissue.
label: Cornea

description: A light-sensitive membrane that lines the back wall of the eyeball. The retina is continuous with the optic nerve and this way transmits optical images to the brain.
label: Retina

description: Tissue located behind the iris and composed of muscle and epithelium. Its functions include the production of aqueous humor and changing the shape of the crystalline lens.
label: Ciliary Body

description: The thickest layer of corneal tissue, composed of collagen fibrils, that is located between the epithelium and the inner endothelium, and extends from behind Bowman's layer to in front of Descement's membrane.
label: Corneal Stroma

description: A biconvex transparent structure of the eye through which light is focused on the retina. The lens sits behind the iris and is supported by the zonule, which connects it to the ciliary body. The lens is an avascular structure.
label: Lens

description: The colored disc of the eye composed of connective tissue, epithelium, and endothelium. It separates the anterior chamber from the posterior chamber.
label: Iris

description: A portion of the retina at which the axons of the ganglion cells exit the eyeball to form the optic nerve. No light-sensitive photoreceptors are contained within this portion of the retina.
label: Optic Disc

description: The transitional zone where the cornea becomes continuous with the sclera.
label: Corneoscleral Limbus

description: The interior surface of the eye opposite the lens including the retina, optic disc, macula, fovea, and posterior pole.
label: Eye Fundus

description: The scleral curvature of the eye comprising the retina, inclusive of the macula and optic disc.
label: Posterior Pole of the Eye

description: The intraocular area that refers to the uvea, retina, vitreous body, and optic nerve.
label: Vitreoretinal Area

description: The protuberance of the eye seen when the eyelid is closed.
label: Eye Bulge

description: The opening of the Bruch membrane in the choroid and sclera of the eye through which the optic nerve passes.
label: Scleral Canal

description: The permeable supporting tissues of the iris which contain blood vessels, nerves, and pigment granules.
label: Iris Stroma

description: Transparent components of the eye that admit and focus light onto the cells of the retina to form images comprising the cornea, the aqueous humor, the lens and the vitreous body.
label: Refractile Media

description: Area consisting of a small depression in the retina containing only cones and where vision is most acute.
label: Fovea Centralis

description: A yellowish, highly pigmented, oval shaped area slightly lateral to the center of the retina of the eye which contains the fovea centralis and is mostly comprised of retinal cones, for high-acuity vision, and which if damaged will result in the partial/complete loss of central vision.
label: Macula

description: One of three spaces (anterior, posterior, and vitreous chamber) in the eye.
label: Chamber of the Eye

description: The space in the eye, filled with aqueous humor, bounded anteriorly by the cornea and a small portion of the sclera and posteriorly by a small portion of the ciliary body, the iris, and that part of the crystalline lens which presents through the pupil. (Cline et al., Dictionary of Visual Science, 4th ed, p109)
label: Anterior Chamber of the Eye

description: A space within the eye located between the iris and the lens. It is filled with aqueous humor.
label: Posterior Chamber of the Eye

description: The largest space within the eye which is bounded by the lens and the retina and filled with the gelatinous vitreous humor.
label: Vitreous Chamber

description: The central area in the anterior surface of the lens.
label: Anterior Pole of the Lens

description: The 60 to 80 radiating pigmented ridges that form a frilled circle around the eye lens behind the iris.
label: Ciliary Process

description: The mitochondria rich section of a photoreceptor within the retina that provides phosphates to the outer segment and is the source of the dark current that when suppressed by light induces a voltage change and subsequent release of transmitters from the cell.
label: Ellipsoid Portion of the Inner Segment of the Photoreceptor Cell

description: The section of a photoreceptor within the retina between the outer and inner segment which contains altered nonmotile cilium.
label: Connecting Segment of the Photoreceptor Cell

description: The outermost layer of the eyeball consisting of both the sclera and the cornea.
label: Corneoscleral Coat

description: A circular vascular-like structure in the anterior chamber of the eye through which aqueous humor passes when returning to the blood.
label: Canal of Schlemm

description: The back surface, which is in contact with the vitreous humor, of the crystalline lens in the eye.
label: Facies Posterior Lentis

description: The portion of the photoreceptor cell between the outer segment and nucleus that is divided into an ellipsoid and myoid section.
label: Inner Segment of the Photoreceptor Cell

description: The transparent, elongated cells extending from the posterior to anterior pole of the eye forming the concentric layers of the crystalline lens.
label: Lens Fiber

description: The portion of the inner segment of a photoreceptor cell between the ellipsoid portion and the nucleus that is rich in ribonucleic acids (RNA) and is a major site for protein synthesis.
label: Myoid Portion of the Inner Segment of the Photoreceptor Cell

description: The posterior three quarters of the retina that contains the rods and cones and terminates at the ora serrata.
label: Photosensitive Region of the Retina

description: An area on the periphery of the retina, located anterior to the ora serrata, which is composed of pigmented epithelium.
label: Nonphotosensitive Region of the Retina

description: An annular zone of the ciliary body continuous with the retina at the ora serrata and covered with ciliary plicae.
label: Orbiculus Ciliaris

description: The distal portion of the photoreceptor cells made up of densely packed disks containing opsin proteins that absorb light.
label: Outer Segment of the Photoreceptor Cell

description: The center of the dorsal portion of the ocular lens.
label: Posterior Pole of the Lens

description: One of two portions (anterior or posterior) of the eye.
label: Eye Segment

description: The part of the eye anterior to the lens, including but not limited to the anterior chamber, cornea and related structures.
label: Anterior Eye Segment

description: The larger portion of the eye behind the lens containing the retina, vitreous humor, choroid, and optic nerve.
label: Posterior Eye Segment

description: One of five layers of the cornea, located between Bowman's layer and Descemet's membrane, composed of thin lamellae of collagen fibers and ground substance, which forms the bulk of the cornea.
label: Substantia Propria

description: The round, central aperture of the eye, surrounded by the iris, through which light enters.
label: Pupil

description: Any of the irregularly shaped spaces of the iridocorneal angle within the trabecular reticulum that communicate with the sinus venosus sclera.
label: Space of Fontana

description: A clear, avascular, gelatinous body that occupies the posterior chamber of the eye.  It is bounded by the retina except anteriorly where it lies adjacent to the lens and iris.
label: Vitreous Body

description: The outer portion of the nose that protrudes from the face.
label: External Nose

description: The inner portion of the nostrils of the nose.
label: Internal Nare

description: One of the two channels of the nose, from the point where they divide to the external opening.
label: Nostril

description: Numerous, tiny, vertical projections on the anterior two thirds of the dorsal side of the tongue that consist of four types: filiform, fungiform, foliate, and circumvallate.
label: Papilla of the Tongue

description: One of eight or ten projections from the dorsum of the tongue forming a row anterior to and parallel with the sulcus terminalis; each papilla is surrounded by a circular trench (fossa) having a slightly raised outer wall (vallum); on the sides of the vallate papilla and the opposed margin of the vallum are numerous taste buds.
label: Circumvallate Papilla

description: The most numerous type of lingual papillae, which covers most of the front two thirds of the tongue, and do not contain taste buds.
label: Filiform Papilla

description: A type of lingual papillae located on the posterior lateral borders of the tongue, which are arranged in several transverse folds, and contain a moderate number of taste buds.
label: Foliate Papilla

description: A type of lingual papillae located on the anterior aspect of the tongue, with greatest density at the tip, and which are large, deep red in color, and contain a moderate number of taste buds.
label: Fungiform Papilla

description: A V-shaped groove on the dorsal surface of the tongue with the apex of the V located at the foramen caecum; it demarcates the anterior two-thirds of the tongue from the posterior one-third.
label: Sulcus Terminalis

description: The opening at the apex of the taste bud.
label: Taste Pore

description: An oval body that is located in a tongue papilla and occupies the entire thickness of the epithelium.  It is composed of neuroepithelial (sensory) cells, supporting cells, and basal cells. The opening at the apex of the taste bud is called taste pore.
label: Taste Bud

description: Any component associated with the end of a pointed or elongated structure.
label: Extremity Part

description: The palmar aspect of the hands and the bottom of the feet.
label: Palms of Hands and Soles of Feet

description: The palmar aspect of the hands, the bottom of the feet, and the nails.
label: Palms of Hands, Soles of Feet, and Nails

description: Any component of the region of the body that includes the arm, the forearm, and hand.
label: Upper Extremity Part

description: The raised part of the palm of the hand that is adjacent to the wrist.
label: Heel of the Hand

description: The most distal end of the finger.
label: Fingertip

description: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the elbow. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole superior limb.
label: Arm

description: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the wrist and located on the left side of the body.
label: Left Arm

description: The portion of the upper extremity between the shoulder and the wrist and located on the right side of the body.
label: Right Arm

description: Any of the digits of the hand.
label: Finger

description: The fifth and smallest finger from the radial side of the hand.
label: Hand Digit 5

description: The thick and short hand digit which is next to the index finger in humans.
label: Hand Digit 1

description: The second finger from the radial side of the hand, next to the thumb.
label: Hand Digit 2

description: The middle or third finger from the radial side of the hand.
label: Hand Digit 3

description: The fourth finger from the radial side of the hand.
label: Hand Digit 4

description: The distal portion of the upper extremity. It consists of the carpus, metacarpus, and digits.
label: Hand

description: The structure on the upper limb, between the elbow and the wrist.
label: Forearm

description: The distal half of the left upper limb between the elbow and the wrist.
label: Left Lower Forearm

description: The distal half of the right upper limb between the elbow and the wrist.
label: Right Lower Forearm

description: Any component of the hip, thigh, leg and foot.
label: Lower Extremity Part

description: The front part of the leg from below the knee to the ankle.
label: Shin

description: The rounded back part of the foot below the ankle and behind the arch.
label: Heel of the Foot

description: One of the terminal digits of the foot.
label: Toe

description: The largest and most medial toe of the foot.
label: Foot Digit 1

description: The second toe from the medial side of the foot.
label: Foot Digit 2

description: The middle or third toe from the medial side of the foot.
label: Foot Digit 3

description: The fourth toe from the medial side of the foot.
label: Foot Digit 4

description: The smallest and most lateral toe of the foot.
label: Foot Digit 5

description: The area pertaining to the top of the foot.
label: Dorsal Region of Foot

description: The structure found below the ankle joint.
label: Foot

description: The portion of the lower extremity between the knee and the ankle. For clinical purposes this term is also used to refer to the whole inferior limb.
label: Leg

description: The portion of the lower extremity between the knee and the ankle on the left side of the body.
label: Left Leg

description: The portion of the lower extremity between the knee and the ankle on the right side of the body.
label: Right Leg

description: A part of the lower limb, located between hip and knee.
label: Thigh

description: A part of the lower limb, located between the hip and the knee and located on the left side of the body.
label: Left Thigh

description: A part of the lower limb, located between the hip and the knee and located on the right side of the body.
label: Right Thigh

description: A finger or toe in human beings or corresponding part in other vertebrates.
label: Digit

description: Either of two (upper and lower) openings in the chest.
label: Opening of the Thorax

description: A hole in the base of the chest formed by the twelfth vertebrae, tenth and twelfth ribs, costal arch and the xiphoid process through which arteries, veins and nerves pass.
label: Lower Opening of the Thorax

description: A hole in the top portion of the chest through which the arteries and veins of the head and neck, esophagus and trachea pass.
label: Upper Opening of the Thorax

description: Any component of the system of organs and tissues, including the bone marrow, spleen, tonsils, and lymph nodes, involved in the production of blood considered together with the interconnected system of spaces and vessels between body tissues and organs by which lymph circulates throughout the body.
label: Hematopoietic and Lymphatic System Part

description: The anatomic system that includes the lymph nodes, lymphoid tissues in various organs (spleen, thymus, tonsils, gastrointestinal tract), and lymphatic vessels.  It is part of the immune system that offers protection against infections.
label: Lymphatic System

description: The bodily system of organs and tissues, primarily the bone marrow, spleen, tonsils, and lymph nodes, involved in the production of blood.
label: Hematopoietic System

description: The total system of structures outside the lungs that move as a part of breathing; it includes all structures from the skin to the parietal pleura.
label: Chest Wall

description: A body structure consisting of nerves traveling together with arteries, veins, and/or lymphatics.
label: Neurovascular Bundle

description: The fold of peritoneum, or mesentery, attached to the upper portion of the rectum and connecting it with the sacrum.
label: Mesorectum

description: The tissues that surround the organs that are present within the abdominal cavity. The abdominal wall tissue is composed of layers of fat, parietal peritoneum, fascia, and muscles.
label: Abdominal Wall

description: A portion of the peritoneal cavity formed by the greater and lesser omentum. It is located posteriorly to the stomach and extends into the greater omentum.
label: Omental Bursa

description: Anatomic structures forming the upper respiratory tract and upper part of the digestive tract. They include the oral cavity, sinonasal tract, pharynx, pyriform sinus, larynx, trachea, and esophagus.
label: Aerodigestive Tract

description: A small fold of tissue that limits the movements of an organ or body part; for example, the lingual frenulum connects the tongue to the floor of the mouth and restrains its movement.
label: Frenulum
